itics/stories/wage_3.html">allow a vote</A> on the minimum wage increase within the next two weeks.<br><br><LI><strong>Independent truckers try to organize in California</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>The <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/BUSINESS/t000041307.html">Los Angeles Times</A> reports on a high-risk organization strategy among California truckers, and also has a story about the <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/FRONT/t000041373.html">growing middle-class</A> in Russia.<br><br><LI><strong>Volunary job reduction on schedule at 3M</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>3M Corporation announced a major restructuring and downsizing plan in November, but has intended to accomplish most of it by offering incentives rather than laying off workers. So far, it seems to be working, and the company's chairman says they're <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/stonline/html/ddd/mmm11.htm">three-quarters finished</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Washington conference focuses on developing "pockets of prosperity"</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>The Fannie Mae Foundation 1996 Housing Conference at the Washington Hilton andTowers yesterday was called "The Future of American Cities: Shaping a New UrbanDiversity" and was co-sponsored by the U.S. Conference of Mayors and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development. Research was presented suggesting that increased diversity in the core cities can help save them. According to Wendy R. Sherman, President and Chief Executive Officer of the FannieMae Foundation, "Our cities work best when they reflect the full breadth of American life." Strategies for attracting middle-income households back to the urban core were discussed. <br><br><LI><strong>Midwest workforce conference scheduled</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>Academics and policy makers will meet Wednesday at the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago to examine "Work Force Developments/Issues for the Midwest Economy." Discussion will focus on new roles for the public and private sectors in enhancing worker productivity. Interested members of the media can obtain additional information by calling (312) 322-5108.<br><br><LI><strong>Cray and Silicon Graphics expect more staff cuts</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>Cray Research, once the leading maker of supercomputers, was bought recently by Silicon Graphics Inc. According to <b>Knight-Ridder</b>, 118 jobs were cut last week and more are expected, but they should not be "Draconian."<br><br><LI><strong>New index testifies to California's recovery</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br><b>Business Wire</b> reports that the new Market Watch Index (MWI) shows strength in the market for new housing in many major California communities, which should be followed by job growth in the construction industry. During recent years, several California communities lost large numbers of manufacturing jobs. A strong housing market is encouraging, because, generally, manufacturing jobs pay better than service jobs, and better support housing purchases.<br><br><LI><strong>Bank governor supports Serbian strike</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>According to <b>Reuters</b>, Yugoslav central bank governor Dragoslav Avramovic supports the thousands of striking workers in southern Serbia who are protesting taxes and unpaid wages. He predicts widespread unrest unless the government meets their demands.<br><br><LI><strong>Hotel workers must reapply for their jobs</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>Cathleen Ferraro, writing in the <b>Sacramento Bee</b>, reports that the new owners of the Beverly Garland Hotel are requiring hotel workers to reapply if they are interested in retaining their jobs at reduced wages under the new management.<br><br><LI><strong>Achievements by women in science and technology recognized</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>Women in Technology International has announced that it is sponsoring a month of activities recognizing women in science and technology and inspiring women to their best. WITI has declared June to be Women in Science and Technology Month. A variety of activities and programs are scheduled, including the first inductees into the WITI Hall of Fame. The organization has 5,000 members worldwide. Further information can be obtained at the <A HREF="http://www.witi.com">WITI web site</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Study says school kids lack necessary computer skills</strong> (Saturday, 5/11/96)<br>Elisa Williams and Katie Hickox report in the <b>Orange County Register</b> that a study commissioned by the Children's Partnership, of Santa Monica, California, says that the majority of American schoolchildren won't be prepared for modern careers because of insufficient computer skills. Fewer than one in 10 of American classrooms are connected to the Internet, according to the study, and, given current trends, only a fifth of new workers will have the computer skills required by 60 percent of the news jobs.<br><br><LI><strong>Study says finding mentor is getting harder</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>The Chivas Regal Report on Working Americans reports that, of 1000 full-time workers surveyed, only 17% indicated that they have an older, more experienced colleague who is taking a special interest in their careers. This contrasts with 43% who said they had a mentor earlier in their careers. Fifty-five percent of the respondents said that senior managers are less interested in helping younger persons than previously. The study was released along with the beginning of <A HREF="http:/www.careertoolbox.com">Career Toolbox</A>, a free career guidance service on the web. We've had difficulty accessing the site, but it may be a temporary problem. <br><br><LI><strong>California transportation workers suing to speed up payment</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>According to <b>PRNewswire</b>, hundreds of California Department of Transportation workers have filed suit against CALTRANS in order to recover damages associated with habitually late payment of wages and benefits. California law requires that the workers be paid on time. <br><br><LI><strong>Personal bankruptcies on the increase</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>John Dunbar, writing in the <b>The Florida Times-Union</b>, says the economy's "cooking," but Americans going broke at an unprecedented rate. Filings for personal bankruptcies reached a record high during the early months of 1996. High debt levels, corporate downsizing, and a lack of health insurance are blamed. Simon Barker-Benfield, also writing in the <b>Times-Union</b>, says that BellSouth will cut 181 jobs in Jacksonville, Florida by the end of June. Most will be operators who answer "dial 0" calls. Automated systems will take over the work, according to the Communications workers of America.<br><br><LI><strong>Textile plant to close</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Champion Products in Fitzgerald, Georgia will close, according to the <b>Macon Telegraph</b>. The plant employs 230 people. It is the latest of several textile plants in the region to close during the past few months.<br><br><LI><strong>Police blast students and teachers with water cannon</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Students and teachers march in protest of cuts to education in Brussels. The march turned violent, and <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/international/stories/belgium_1.html">riot police responded</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>New laws needed to control economic espionage</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>According to <b>Reuters</b>, FBI Director Louis Freeh told Congress Thursday that critical technological and other economic information <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/politics/stories/fbi_1.html">is being stolen</A> by foreign governments and new laws are needed. <br><br><LI><strong>"Worker backlash" expected</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br><b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> report that Morgan Stanley economist Stephen Roach expects a "worker backlash" against retail and fast food industries. Investment strategies are being developed to benefit from it. <br><br><LI><strong>Swiss employers resist social charter</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br><b>Tages Anzeiger</b> reports that Switzerland's main employers group is challenging the government's plan to ratify the European social charter which gives employees the right to strike. It also entitles foreign workers to equal social benefits. The paper also reports that Swiss truckers are protesting the Swiss Federal Railways plan to sell its interest in Cargo Domizil AG, in which the truckers own a minority interest. Railway workers are demonstrating against the sale to Cargo Domizil's chief competitors.<br><br><LI><strong>Austrian court rules that Turkish workers will receive residency rights</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br><b>Salzburger Nachrichten</b> reports that Turkish citizens living in Austria are entitled to unlimited residency in the country after four years. The decision will affect more than 51,000 Turkish immigrant workers.<br><br><LI><strong>Social security reform wanted before summer</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Belgium Premier Dehaene is urging lawmakers to give the government additional powers to push ahead with social security reform before summer. He also wants to move ahead with the 1997 budget in order to cut the country's deficit in time for European monetary union. <b>Le Soir</b> reports the story this morning.<br><br><LI><strong>German labor law change proposed</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Germany's Labor Minister Bluem will propose legislation intended to save companies more than 3 billion marks by reducing sick pay and vacation pay, according to <b>Handelsblatt</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Business organizations get ready to oppose AFL-CIO in election</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Today's <b>Wall Street Journal</b> reports that business groups are concerned about the AFL-CIO's plan for election spending and intend to do some spending of their own. The <b>Journal</b> also has stories today about employees given the burden of downsizing, about the decrease in jobless claims last week, and about Senator Dole's proposal that unions "loath." <br><br><LI><strong>More work for secretaries forecast</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>The expansion of Russian employment improves outlook for secretaries, according to the <A HREF="http://www.spb.su/times/160/bigmark.html">St. Petersburg Times</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Barnard College to withhold diplomas</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Six Barnard College seniors won't get their diplomas right away because of their <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/barnard-strike.html">participation in a campus strike</A>, according to the <b>New York Times</b>. The <b>Times</b> also reports today on how a former Democrat has <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/politics/ohio-politics-wages.html">become a Republican</A>, and why. Hint: it has to do with the minimum wage issue.<br><br><LI><strong>Getting back to work faster</strong> (Friday, 5/10/96)<br>Dave Beal's column in the <b>St. Paul Pioneer Press</b> today tells about a company that is making Minnesota's workers' compensation system <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/business/index.htm">work better</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Politicians trade accusations about "logjam"</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>President Clinton says he would <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960508/politics/stories/clinton_6.html">sign bills</A> to increase the minimum wage and to cut the gasoline tax, but only if they are presented "clean," rather than combined with Senate majority leader Robert Dole's proposal to <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/politics/stories/labor_1.html">ease rules barring company unions</A>. While Clinton and Dole <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/news/stories/gastax_15.html">spar over this issue</A>, recently almost invisible House Speaker Newt Gingrich accuses Clinton of <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/news/stories/gingrich_1.html">political "posturing"</A>. It's not even easy to pass legislation that enjoys bipartisan popularity during an election year.<br><br><LI><strong>Generally good news from the Fed Wednesday</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>According to latest report, the economy <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960508/business/stories/economy_5.html">picked up a little speed</A> in March and April through most areas of the United States, and indications of feared inflation are not strong. Also, the U.S. Department of Labor reports that <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960509/news/stories/economy_9.html">new unemployment claims dipped</A> last week, which is not what Wall Street expected.<br><br><LI><strong>Aw, go ahead, take a week off</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br><b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> report that demand has been slack for AMP, Inc.'s electrical connectors, so they're asking their entire U.S. workforce to take a week off without pay to help out. The company has 18,000 employees in the U.S. The proposal is an effort to save jobs, spokespersons say. <br><br><LI><strong>Government downsizing in Spain</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>The new conservative Spanish government has announced that it intends to eliminate 80 government departments and make the deepest cuts in the Finance Ministry, among the survivors. The conservatives recently displaced the previous Socialist government. <b>Cinco Dias</b> and other Spanish papers report the story this morning. <br><br><LI><strong>Temps up in Belgium</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br><b>La Libre Belgique</b> reports that temporary employment increased 17% in 1995. About 200,000 people found temporary jobs in the country last year, as companies strive for workforce flexibility during a period of sluggish economic growth.<br><br><LI><strong>Concern about pension funds in the Netherlands</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>The Dutch insurance industry regulator is worried about the financial health of a number of smaller Dutch pension funds and is taking a look at their investment policies. A number of the smaller funds had problems last year.<br><br><LI><strong>French population not optimistic</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>A new survey indicates that nearly two-thirds of those responding say they don't expect a significant decrease in unemployment in France during the next twenty years. Eight percent they favor reduction of hours and early retirement to help save jobs and stimulate employment of young people, respectively. <b>La Tribune Desfosses</b> has this story today, as well as one about the French Finance Ministry's plan to cut spending by 60-100 billion francs with a lowering of taxes in mind. Most of the cuts will come from subsidies intended to create jobs as well as from housing benefits.<br><br><LI><strong>More flexibility in business dress</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>Jane Turnis, writing in the Colorado Springs <b>Gazette Telegraph</b>, says that an increasing acceptance of women in the workplace has led to greater options, so far as acceptable business dress is concerned. However, John T. Molloy, in his <b>The Woman's Dress for Success Book</b>, published in 1977, said that most women dress for failure, and that some of his advice still holds today. Even though women should not "dress like little men," the emphasis should still be on dressing to be taken seriously. <br><br><LI><strong>Parity for the mentally ill advocated</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>In her nationally syndicated column today, Molly Ivins says the government finally seems in danger of doing something right now that the Senate has unanimously passed a bill that would require that mental illness be treated the same as physical illness under health insurance. She says objections from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and other business organizations are based on outdated information and misinterpretations. She points out that many companies, including Honeywell and IBM, already provide parity for mental illness treatment without being overwhelmed by costs, and evidence has been accumulating that overall operating costs go down when treatment is covered. An investment in human resources has bottom-line implications. It does seem remarkable that so many Americans, including leaders who presumably attended college, can remain so entirely ignorant of most psychiatric and psychological issues, suggesting that the availability of systematically verifiable knowledge is not enough to impact public perceptions. She's right when she indicates that many new and effective treatments have been developed during the past ten years, even the past two years. Ivins writes for the <b>Fort Worth Star-Telegram</b>, and also appears on CBS-TV's "60 Minutes."<br><br><LI><strong>FMLA no hardship to business, Goodman says</strong> (Thursday, 5/9/96)<br>In her syndicated column today, Ellen Goodman reports that a Congressional commission studying the effects of the Family and Medical Leave Act has found that it is helping millions of Americans balance family and work and is not burdening business, despite earlier fears. The law guarantees unpaid leave up to 12 weeks for full time employees in larger companies so that they can care for family members during crisis periods. Goodman writes for the <b>Boston Globe</b> and is syndicated nationally by the <b>Washington Post Writers Group</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Women increasing online presence</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>A new survey shows that a <A HREF="http://nytsyn.com/live/News3/128_050796_114006_11599.html">large number of women are online</A> now, in part because more are working at home, according to <b>Computer News Daily</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Major cost cutting, job cutting at Georgia-Pacific</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>A depressed lumber market will lead to cuts at Georgia-Pacific. Incentives for voluntary retirement will be offered, but cuts will have to come, voluntary or not, says <A HREF="http://cnnfn.com/news/wires/9605/07/georgia_pacific_wg/">CNN Financial</A> and <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960508/business/stories/georgiapacific_1.html">Reuters</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Olympics pushing wages up in Georgia</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>Georgia already has "full employment," according to some economists, and lots more workers will be needed for the Summer Olympics, according to <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960508/business/stories/olympics_1.html">Reuters</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>Workers release executive</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>Workers at Forges de Clabecq, a Belgium steel company that is in danger of going out of business, locked the company's chief executive in his office Monday, protesting planned jobs cuts. They've released him, and talks are underway on how to save the company and the jobs. <b>Le Soir</b> has the story this morning, as well as a story about Caterpiller Belgium's plan to save 1.8 billion Belgian francs during the next few years in personnel costs. Labor unions are studying the plan.<br><br><LI><strong>Argument about Austria's "welfare state" heats up in Parliament</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br><b>Kurier</b> reports this morning that Austrian unemployment is lower than average in Europe at 3.2 percent last month, but accusations are flying among legislators over labor and welfare policy.<br><br><LI><strong>Unions may strike Philips over pension plan</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>Philips Electronics in the Netherlands is threatened with industrial action because of disputes over modified pension arrangements. Only FNV, the country's largest union, and CNV, its Christian counterpart, are involved. Agreements have been signed with other unions, according to <b>Het Financieele Dagblad</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Talks break off in Germany</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>Public employees unions in Germany want a 4.5 percent wage increase at a time when the German government is trying to implement an austerity program in a sluggish economy. The second round of talks have broken off, but they will meet again on May 13. <b>Handelsblatt</b> and other German news organizations have the story today.<br><br><LI><strong>Pensions may be smaller at the beginning to pay for long-term care</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>A new government proposal in the UK could produce "variable pensions" for more than 20 million people in an effort to fund long-term care. According to the plan, pensions would be smaller during the early part of the retirement period, leaving more money for later, according to London's <A HREF="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/et/access?ac=112546844310&pg=//96/5/8/npens08.html">Electronic Telegraph</A>. The <b>Telegraph</b> also has a story about Britain's Labour Party's pledge to cut the social security budget and encourage more private welfare provisions in a Labour government. With the Conservative government of John Major facing dwindling support, a government led by Labour's Tony Blair could be on the horizon.<br><br><LI><strong>U.S. agrees to notify Mexico about detainees</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>The <b>New York Times</b> reports this morning that the U.S. Secretary of State has signed an agreement with Mexico that, among other things, means that the U.S. will <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/mexico-us.html">notify Mexican diplomats</A> whenever pregnant women or children are detained as illegal immigrants. Mexico has expressed concern about the safety of Mexicans in the United States following several incidents in California during recent weeks. The <b>Times</b> also reports today that Bennington College is having financial trouble and <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/bennington-educ.html">is being sued</A> by some of its professors, and also that Democrats have used the minimum wage issue to <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/washpol/gas-tax.html">stall Republican efforts</A> to roll back the gasoline tax.<br><br><LI><strong>Life on the insurance cliff</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br><b>CNN Financial</b> examines the need for <A HREF="http://cnnfn.com/news/wires/9605/07/insurance_cliffs_wg/">insurance portability</A> today, but points out that a new law will not guarantee insurance affordability. <br><br><LI><strong>Ambitious plans for old tank plant</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>The government's tank manufacturing plant in Warren, Michigan has been closed. Plan hopes to <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/menu/stories/47031.htm">create jobs</A>, increased tax base, according to the <b>Detroit News</b>. The <b>News</b> also has stories today about why it's getting <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/menu/stories/47017.htm">harder to find school principles</A> in Michigan and about a <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/STRAT/9605/06/couples/couples.htm">working couple's book</A> to help working couples. Also, thinking about <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/STRAT/9605/06/careers/careers.htm">cabinetmaking</A> as a career? Here's some information. <br><br><LI><strong>Minnesota firm tries work sharing</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>Today's <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> reports on Norwest Mortgage's experiments with cutting back hours rather than jobs. A <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/stonline/html/ddd/col108.htm">new state program</A> allows employees to collect unemployment benefits on a temporary basis in order to recover their lost hours. Job sharing has been widespread in Europe, but is relatively new in the United States, where the tendency has been to keep some workers at full strength and lay off others.<br><br><LI><strong>Beck says insurance companies should look to benefits of mental illness coverage</strong> (Wednesday, 5/8/96)<br>In her <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/opinion/columns/index.htm">syndicated column</A> today, Joan Beck writes that matters will be made worse, including lost productivity, if society continues to give second-class status to insurance coverage for the treatment of psychiatric illnesses. The version of the "portable" insurance bill that passed the Senate includes a provision that gives equal status to mental and physical illnesses. However, a compromise bill must be worked out with the House, and many are saying the mental health provision will not survive. Beck writes for the <b>Chicago Tribune</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Survey says U.S. workers among happiest</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>According to a new survey commissioned by <b>Inc.</b> magazine, American workers are among the most satisfied of those from many countries surveyed, despite widespread anxieties about corporate restructuring, downsizing, and other broad issues. <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/business/stories/workplace_1.html">Reuters reports</A>. The world's largest wire service also reports today that there may be <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/business/stories/astra_1.html">more suspensions</A> at the American division of a Swedish drug company because of sexual harassment charges. There are also stories about <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/business/stories/salaries_1.html">people whose earnings</A> make those of many top executives seem modest, as well as expected <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/business/stories/farm_1.html">strong farm income</A>, but within a highly volatile market.<br><br><LI><strong>Conflicting stories on Greek museums</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>The <A HREF="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/et/access?ac=112546844310&pg=//96/5/7/wgrec07.html">Electronic Telegraph</A> reports that a strike is on which has closed several Greek archeological sites and museums, but <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/entertainment/stories/art_greecemuseums_1.html">Reuters</A> reports that the strike has been postponed. Stay tuned.<br><br><LI><strong>Bad news about job applicant preparation</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>The American Management Association has released the results of a survey indicating that a third of persons applying for jobs with major companies last year lacked the <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/APONLINE/BUSINESS/slugs2024.htm">basic math or reading skills</A> to do the job. However, things are still better than they were. <br><br><LI><strong>Hong Kong women in entertainment form union</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>The Entertainment and Personal Services Workers Union in Hong Kong has been approved. It will represent "masseuses, nightclub hostesses and Karaoke girls," according to the <A HREF="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/et/access?ac=112546844310&pg=//96/5/7/wkara07.html">Electronic Telegraph</A>. The future of any non-governmental organization is uncertain, because China takes control of Hong Kong in a bit more than a year.<br><br><LI><strong>Connecticut governor puts truancy policy on hold</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>The plan was to withhold welfare checks from families whose children skip school, but a problem has been discovered. The <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/ct-welfare.html">New York Times</A> has the story. Also in the <b>Times</b> today, you'll find a story about how praise for Republicans <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/ny-labor-dems.html">put a snag</A> in a labor meeting intended to boost Democrats. Labor leaders are finding it harder to put the resources of their unions behind Democratic candidates, because some of their members have been voting Republican in recent years. Finally, the <b>Times</b> reports that complaints about sexual harassment are rare in Japan, even though <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/japan-sex-harass.html"> harassment itself isn't</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>Largest sex discrimination lawsuit brewing</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>Following the largest sexual harassment lawsuit against Mitsubishi, we may be seeing the largest sex discrimination lawsuit as well, but against a different company. <b>Knight-Ridder</b> reports that 12 women have filed a class action suit against Publix Super Markets Inc. If they win, as many as 100,000 women across several southern states could file claims against the company. However, as has been the case at Mitsubishi, fellow employees are not all enthusiastic about what is happening.<br><br><LI><strong>Majority of Hungarians want to limit immigration</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>According to the <b>Hungary Report</b>, a recent poll indicates that a third of Hungarians feel there are too many foreigners in the country, and 2/3 would favor limitations on the number of foreigners allowed to move in. The <b>Report</b> also projects 500,000 unemployed in Hungary by the end of the years. <br><br><LI><strong>European commissioner speaks in U.S. about choices</strong> (Tuesday, 5/7/96)<br>Padraig Flynn, a member of the European Commission, spoke at George Washington University in Washington, D. C. on May 3. He said that the choice between higher employment and inequality, on the one hand, or social welfare and rising unemployment, on the other, are "false, unnecessary, and unwise," as indicated in the recent G-7 meeting in Lille. It is commonly believed that the U.S. has been following the former strategy, while, for the most part, Europe has been following the latter.<br><br><LI><strong>Newt sees minimum wage vote coming "soon"</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>House Speaker Newt Gingrich, appearing on CBS-TV's "Face the Nation," said that he expects the minimum wage issue to <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960506/news/stories/wage_1.html">come to a vote</A> within the next month or so. He favors exemptions for small businesses and farms in order to save jobs. <br><br><LI><strong>Coming to terms with a "diminished future?"</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>Steve Berg writes in the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> today that American aspirations may have leveled off, and that candidates in this year's presidential election are trying to decide how to deal with the new attitudes. The article is on the <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/stonline/html/ddd/vnwv06.htm">paper's web site</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Cairo leads in air pollutants</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br><b>USA Today</b> tells about the conflict between economics and the environment in Cairo, where <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/nws4.htm">many deaths per year</A> are attributed to polluted air. The issues are familiar ones, but some say that the arguments often imply a false dichotomy. Environmental damage and consequent health effects should be factored in to the economic models. As one Nobel Prize winning chemist has said, "the economy is a wholly owned subsidiary of the environment." <b>USA Today</b> also reports that hospitals in Komsomolsk-on-Amur in eastern Russia have cut back to two meals per day because of cash shortages. They claim that they're receiving only half as much money from the government per patient as promised.<br><br><LI><strong>A year off with pay offered</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>Austria's <b>Die Presse</b> reports that talks between the Austrian government and major labor unions about loosening restrictive work rules have bogged down. The government will now offer a full year off with pay to government employees in exchange for a 20% pay cut, with future raises linked to performance. No response from the unions yet.<br><br><LI><strong>New Spanish government pledges no cuts in social services</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>Spanish Vice President Rodrigo Rato says social services will not suffer as a consequence of the new government's austerity program. He emphasizes that reforms in the economy are more important than budget cuts to help the country qualify for European Monetary Union. <b>La Gaceta de Negocios</b> reports. Also, <b>USA Today</b> reports that Spain's new prime minister, sworn in Sunday, promises a better economy.<br><br><LI><strong>More fast food workers in Belgium</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>Belgium's <b>Le Soir</b> reports that Quick SA will hire an additional 2,600 people this year, with 500 of the new jobs in Belgium. The increase will result from the opening of 60 new restaurants. The paper also reports that teachers in French-speaking Belgium will strike for two days in protest of proposed budget cuts.<br><br><LI><strong>Demonstration against police actions in Switzerland</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br><b>Tages Anzeiger</b> reports today that more than 2,000 persons marched in Zurich streets Saturday to protest police actions during May Day demonstrations, in which several persons were injured and 64 were arrested.<br><br><LI><strong>German Finance Minister says social security benefits should be taxed</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>Finance Minister Theo Waigel says other forms of aid to the elderly are taxed, social security benefits should be too, according to today's <b>Allgemeine Zeitung</b>. A controversy is raging in Germany over the need to cut costs in a sluggish economy.<br><br><LI><strong>Technology gives new meaning to the term "home work"</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>The <b>New York Times</b> has an article on home offices, and it's <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/library/jobmarket/0505sabra.html">on the web</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>Smaller pay increases and variable bonuses ahead in Singapore</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>The <b>Singapore Business Times</b> reports that 103 companies were surveyed and <A HREF="http://www.sph.com.sg:80/biztimes/pages/nsing01.html">more modest rewards</A> are expected during the year. <br><br><LI><strong>Korean economy may be one of top 7 in 25 years</strong> (Monday, 5/6/96)<br>A recent forecast reported in the <b>Korea Herald</b> says that the growing Korean economy should be a <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0507/m0507b05.html">member of G-7</A> by 2020. The <b>Herald</b> also reports today that 45 union activists <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0507/m0507l12.html">have been arrested</A> because of a violent strike. <br><br><LI><strong>Armey calls for cuts in education spending</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br>How to pay for repeal of gas tax, if it's coming? Try cutting education spending, says House Republican leader Dick Armey. Here's the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960505/news/stories/gastax_3.html">Reuters version</A> of the story. <b>Reuters</b> also has more on <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960504/news/stories/clinton_3.html">President Clinton's action</A> to require states to find ways to keep teen welfare mothers in school. Also, while a <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960505/business/stories/fed_2.html">Federal Reserve official</A> seems satisfied that the economy is growing well with low inflation, <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960505/business/stories/stocks_13.html">inflation concerns rise</A> on Wall Street. <br><br><LI><strong>Lawyers as temp workers</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br>Today's <b>St. Paul Pioneer Press</b> reports on the growing number of lawyers who are doing <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/business/index.htm">temporary or contract work</A>. Also, in his column this time, Dave Beal tells about an organization helping young people deal with the gap between formal educational credentials and real learning so that they can become employable. The paper also has a major section on how the high cost of college is pricing many middle class families <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/index.htm">out of the market</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>Confidence in Japanese bureaucrats declining</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br>The <b>New York Times</b> reports on the role of civil servants in Japan and <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/japan-bureaucrats.html">changes in public perceptions</A> during recent months. The <b>Times</b> also examines <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/earn-foreign-bias-adv05.html">issues of apparent bias</A> when one has a foreign boss.<br><br><LI><strong>Working multiple jobs</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br>Tad Shannon, writing in the Eugene, Oregon's <b>Register-Guard</b>, tells the story of a mother of two teenagers who is working two part-time jobs to make ends meet. He reports that, according to U.S. Department of Labor statistics, 7.7 million Americans hold multiple jobs, and, while the overall number of workers in this category has increased only a bit during the past 20 years, the number of women holding multiple jobs has nearly tripled. In another article, Shannon describes community college programs for helping women who must return to the workforce to make the transition. Some have been trapped in abusive relationships, but lack job skills. In Oregon, the number of homemakers entering the workforce increased by 26 percent between 1980 and 1990. Shannon says that, according to the National Displaced Homemakers Network, more than 50% of homemakers returning to the workforce are mothers, and nearly 2/3 are at or near the federal poverty level. Most have limited education, and few have received job training. In Oregon, new welfare rules won't allow women on assistance to return to school.<br><br><LI><strong>Irish unemployment increases</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> reports that unemployment in Ireland increased from 12.9 percent in March to 13.0 percent in April. <br><br><LI><strong>Blue-collar women targeted by Democrats</strong> (Sunday, 5/5/96)<br>Hanna Rosin, writing in the <b>New Republic</b> this time, says that blue-collar women in the United States are angry, and that the Democrats are trying hard to tap that discontent in the presidential campaign. It might be a hard sell, because they're not enthusiastic about Clinton, she says, but they're even less enamored by the Republicans. <br><br><LI><strong>Things aren't so good after all, so stocks rebound</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br>Good economic news sent fears of higher interest rates and inflation through Wall Street Thursday, sending stock prices sharply down. However, Friday's jobs report was encouraging to investors, so stocks <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960503/business/stories/stocks_11.html">recovered somewhat</A>. The economy has been growing at a respectable pace during the first months of 1996, and, while unemployment was the lowest in sometime during April, the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960503/business/stories/jobs_2.html">overall jobs picture</A> remains relatively weak. <br><br><LI><strong>Garment shops slipping through the cracks</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br>U.S. Department of Labor studies find that nearly half of the garment manufacturing shops in the U.S. may be <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960504/business/stories/sweatshops_1.html">violating wage and hour laws</A>, according to <b>Reuters</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Strong demand in the military</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> reports that the U.S. military needs a lot of personnel, and many are <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960504/business/stories/military_1.html">finding the appeal attractive</A> in relation to civilian job opportunities. <b>Reuters</b> also reports that Senator Dole expects <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960503/politics/stories/taxes_1.html">minimum wage increase and a gas tax decrease</A>, which should be welcome news to an incumbent president running for reelection.<br><br><LI><strong>UAW not willing to play dead</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> report that the United Auto Workers is sending clear messages to General Motors that they will not be underestimated, even in the present climate. The UAW intends to press for gains despite GM's commitment to cutting costs. Organized labor has been showing renewed signs of life. <br><br><LI><strong>Private package delivery hurting Swiss postal service</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>Tages Anzeiger</b> reports that the Swiss postal service expects to cut more than 1500 of 6000 jobs in its package delivery division in order to try to compete more efficiently with private delivery firms. The government postal system in the United States used to have a near monopoly on message and package delivery, but that has eroded significantly in the U.S. too, given an array of private alternatives. Also, in Switzerland, officials are defending arrests made and other police responses to violent demonstrators on May Day. <b>Neue Zuercher Zeitung</b> reported the story yesterday.<br><br><LI><strong>Job creation slowdown in Spain</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>Cinco Dias</b> reports that job creation has slowed in Spain, evidenced by a slowdown in the number of workers paying into the country's social security system. <br><br><LI><strong>Flying in Italy may not be easy</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br>Negotiations between Italian air traffic controllers and Alitalia have broken down, so a new round of strikes is planned. Strikes made air travel in Italy difficult last fall. <b>Corriere della Sera</b> reported the story yesterday. <br><br><LI><strong>Kohl determined to push ahead</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>Sueddeutsche Zeitung</b> reports that German Chancellor Helmut Kohl says he will move ahead with his plan for cutting social spending and changing work rules, despite labor opposition. He says the action is needed to create jobs and keep the country competitive in the new world economy. Labor unions object to proposed measures that would make layoffs easier, among other things. Also in Germany, The German Federation of Employers have refused to raise the minimum wage for workers in the construction industry, saying that such a policy would push wages up in other industries. Labor unions have been seeking the increase in construction in order to discourage cheaper foreign labor from taking good jobs from German workers, according to <b>Frankfurter Rundschau</b>.<br><br> <LI><strong>Another analysis of downsizing in the U.S.</strong> (Saturday, 5/4/96)<br><b>The Economist</b> this time contains a useful analysis of jobs lost and jobs gained in the American economy, and <A HREF="http://www.enews.com/magazines/economist/current/960427-006.html">it's on the web</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Wall Street gets a headache over good economic news, again</strong> (Friday, 5/3/96)<br>The American economy has been <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/stonline/html/ddd/econ03.htm">growing at a robust rate</A> during the first months of 1996, business activity is brisk, and workers will enjoy higher pay and greater job options this year than last, according to an article in the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> by Mike Myers, the paper's national economics correspondent. However, the stock market is interpreting this as meaning higher interest rates and inflation, which is cooling the market's enthusiasm, driving prices down. The interests of people who work and people who invest are often at odds, but competition between capital and labor has helped define the nature of modern economies since the beginning of the Industrial Revolution. Things are complicated in the contemporary American economy, because many of the workers and investors are the same people, given the significant role played by pension funds in the stock market. Of course, these are also ordinary cyclical issues, and they do not alter the more fundamental and historic structural changes that are occurring.<br><br><LI><strong>Blaming victims</strong> (Friday, 5/3/96)<br>Columnist Ellen Goodman writes today that people who blew the whistle at the Normal, Illinois Mitsubishi plant have become the focus of hostility both within and outside the company. Some have received death threats, and many have tried to discredit women who have been harassed and abused, with the apparent support of some local politicians. The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has brought the largest sexual harassment suit so far against the company. Goodman writes for the <b>Boston Globe</b>, and her column is syndicated throughout North America.<br><br><LI><strong>Biggest layoffs ever at Pearl Harbor Naval Shipyard</strong> (Friday, 5/3/96)<br>The <b>Honolulu Star Bulletin</b> reports that <A HREF="http://starbulletin.com/today/news/index.html">546 workers</A> will lose their jobs. The shipyard is Hawaii's largest industrial employer. <br><br><LI><strong>British employers get ready for flood of compensation claims</strong> (Friday, 5/3/96)<br>The <b>London Times</b> <A HREF="http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/tim/96/05/03/timbizana01001.html?1067812">examines the fallout</A> from a recent work-related stress case. The <b>Times</b> also reports on a <A HREF="http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/tim/96/05/03/timbizbiz01020.html?1067812">threatened postal strike</A> in the UK.<br><br><LI><strong>For many, family leave not affordable</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>The <b>St. Paul Pioneer Press</b> reports this morning that almost 3 million workers have taken advantage of the new <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/news/nation/">family leave law</A> which allows time off without pay to deal with personal or family emergencies. However, many others have not done so, mostly because they can't afford it, they say. The story's on the paper's web site, but you'll have to subscribe to read the entire thing. Similarly with the story on Kathie Lee Gifford's <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/news/breakingnews/index.htm">angry response</A> on TV yesterday to criticisms of her using, then dumping the Honduran plant that manufactured clothes in her designer line. Most of her anger was reserved for Charles Kernaghan of the National Labor Community who appeared before a Congressional committee Monday. He says she should have kept the children and pregnant women employed, but should have "cleaned up the place," providing a living wage.<br><br><LI><strong>American economy showing more signs of strength</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>Consumer spending was down toward the end of 1995, but has been <A HREF=" http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960502/news/stories/economy_3.html">robust during 1996's first quarter</A>, according to U.S. Department of Commerce data. The economy grew substantially <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960501/business/stories/economy_2.html">without inflation</A>, with Gross Domestic Product in the U.S. increasing at an annual rate of 2.8 percent during the first three months of this year. <br><br><LI><strong>Austrian Chancellor warns against wage cuts</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br><b>Die Presse</b> reports that Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told more than 35,000 people at a May Day rally that "we must be better and more skilled than the others, not cheaper and poorer." The government and unions are trying to work out plans for loosening strict work rules to provide greater flexibility. <br><br><LI><strong>Ramos says no to minimum wage increase</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>Philippine President Ramos has rejected calls for a change in the law to raise the minimum wage. Instead, he offers tax exemptions for minimum wage earners and Philippine citizens working in other countries, according to the <b>Manila Times</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>A new day off in Cambodia</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>Cambodian government employees will <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/APONLINE/INTERNAT/slugs2236.htm">not work on Saturdays</A> from now on, as part of an effort to cut costs. Teachers and professors are exempted. <br><br><LI><strong>More needed to reform labor-management relations in Korea, President says</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>South Korean President Kim Young-sam says that easing the country's <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0503/m0503l02.html">restrictive labor laws</A> will not be all that's needed, according to the <b>Korea Herald</b>. He spoke to executives and labor leaders. The <b>Herald</b> also reports a 20.6 increase in <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0503/m0503l16.html">employment for college graduates</A> in the nation's largest businesses.<br><br><LI><strong>Labor issues at issue as constitutional talks deadlock</strong> (Thursday, 5/2/96)<br>The main parties in negotiations for a new South African constitution <A HREF="http://www.hkstandard.com/online/news/001/world/news006.htm">have deadlocked</A> over labor, education, and property issues, according to the <b>Hong Kong Standard</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Truckers park it in Mexico</strong> (Wednesday, 5/1/96)<br><b>Bloomberg</b> and <b>Reforma</b> report this morning that about 10,000 truckers throughout Mexico have stopped their trucks in protest over wages and alleged police corruption. The National Confederation of Mexican Transport Workers reports that many union members did not participate because of fear of government reprisals. <b>Reforma</b> also reports that four marches through Mexico City have been scheduled in celebration of Labor Day. Political parties and independent labor unions are participating.<br><br><LI><strong>Former Control Data workers claim age discrimination in layoffs</strong> (Wednesday, 5/1/96)<br>What is left of the former Control Data Corporation is called Ceridian Corporation now, and, according to today's <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b>, it is doing better. However, about 300 former workers are suing Ceridian for age discrimination, which the company denies. The suit claims that older workers were targeted for layoff during the company's long restructuring process. The paper also quotes research indicating that wrongful termination claims have been increasing, and age discrimination claims are receiving the largest awards. The <b>Strib</b> also reports that Cray Research will lay off 118 workers because of the company's sale to California-based Silicon Graphics. Also, the print version of the paper today contains an editorial that discusses research in progress that suggests that overworking employees may not only be hard on them, but also counterproductive for the company. Multiple studies are indicating that more flexible work practices that allow more time for employees' private lives result in greater productivity, morale, and customer satisfaction. In general, these findings are consistent with many others over many years which large numbers of companies have chosen to ignore. The paper is <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/">on the web</A>, but none of these stories are.<br><br><LI><strong>Columnists comment on minimum wage issue</strong> (Wednesday, 5/1/96)<br>D. J. Tice, writing in the <b>St. Paul Pioneer Press</b> today, tells how the Earned Income Tax Credit could offer solutions on wage and welfare issues, and Myriam Marquez says we should expect no deals on the minimum wage increase because it's an election year. On the contrary, says David Rosenbaum of the <b>New York Times</b>. The political deal has already been made, but economists will argue endlessly about whether it's a good idea, all the time quoting the same data. Both <b>Pioneer Press</b> columns are available <A HREF="http://www.pioneerplanet.com/opinion/columns/index.htm">on the paper's web site</A>, if you're a subscriber.<br><br></UL><br><center><hr width=200; size=5><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="default.html"><b>Return to top of home page</strong></A><p><FONT SIZE=+1><strong><A HREF="Today's_news.html">NewWork News</A> | <A HREF="Guest_commentary.html">Guest Commentary</A> | <A HREF="NewWork_reviews.html">Reviews</A> | <A HREF="Tech_watch.html">Tech Watch</A><br><A HREF="Ed_watch.html">Ed Watch</A> | <A HREF="Resources.html">Resources</A> | <A HREF ="Archives.html">Archives</A> | <A HREF ="Feedback.html">Feedback</A></FONT></strong></center><center><hr width=200; size=5></center><p><p><center><img src="LogoB.GIF" alt="[BraveNewWorkWorld and NewWork News are at http://www.newwork.com. All about work. All the time. For business, education, and careers.]"></center><p><p>