South Korea was an "underdeveloped country," but has suddenly become one of the world's principal industrial powers with the 15th economy in the world. Priority has been given to growth and development, with other issues, including safety, infrastructure, and so on, taking second place. Now, though, with economic success and industrial power assured, attention is shifting to neglected issues.<br><br> <LI><strong>Dole tax plan and middle-class anxiety</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> Blaine Harden of the <b>Washington Post</b> says American presidential candidate Robert Dole hopes to energize his campaign by appealing to <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/06/064L-080696-idx.html">middle-class economic insecurity</A>, but Dan Balz of the <b>Post</b> says that his tax proposal and populism are <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/06/057L-080696-idx.html">going to be risky</A>. Kurt Shillinger of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> asks if Dole's numbers <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/us/us.2.html">all add up</A>, while the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> editorializes that the whole thing is <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=ED06">"Dole's voodoo"</A>.<br><br> <LI><strong>Indicators strong</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> The Index of Leading Indicators were up in June for the fifth month in a row, suggesting <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960805/news/stories/economy_10.html">strong economic activity ahead</A>, <b>Retuers</b> reports. The Index is considered one of the best forecasters of economic activity six to nine months in the future. <b>Reuters</b> also reports today that Albert Shanker, newly re-elected president of the American Federation of Teachers, says he <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960806/politics/stories/teachers_1.html">doesn't think that school vouchers will work</A> as a campaign issue for Dole. Public school teachers unions have tended to be opposed to vouchers because they believe they would weaken public education. <br><br> <LI><strong>Fidelity reconsidering new hires</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> The <b>Wall Street Journal</B> reports that Fidelity Investments is concerned with rising costs and has told its managers to reconsider the need to fill about 1,500 current job openings. Today's <b>Journal</b> also contains a story on the affirmative action debate and the fear of white backlash in Brazil, as well as a story about the growth of outsourcing in the public sector as taxpayers save but jobs are lost. <br><br> <LI><strong>Use of foreign cabin crews questioned</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> Troubled Swiss airline Swissair's plan to increase the number of foreign cabin crew members on long flights is coming under investigation by the Federal Department for Industry, Commerce and Employment. They're not sure it can be done under Swiss labor law, according to <b>Neue Zuercher Zeitung</b>.<br><br> <LI><strong>Largest Dutch union wants 3% increase</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> <b>De Telegraaf</b> reports that FNV, the largest union in the Netherlands, says it will demand a 3 percent pay raise for next year. <br><br> <LI><strong>Letter service monopoly suspended in UK</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> The UK's postal service has temporarily lost its monopoly on the delivery of letters. Ian Lang, the British trade and industry secretary, suspended the monopoly in response to the Communication Workers' Union call for more 24-hour strikes. Today's <b>Daily Telegraph</b> and other papers report the story this morning.<br><br> <LI><strong>German tiremaker to cut jobs in Austria</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> <b>Der Standard</b> reports that the Continental AG, the German tiremaker, will cut 900 jobs at its Semperit Reifen plan in Taiskirche, Austria. Some production will be moved to the Czech Republic. The announced cuts are fewer than expected. In Germany itself, <b>Sueddeutsche Zeitung</b> announces that unemployment rose in July. The information comes from unnamed sources. The official report has not yet been released by the Federal Labor Office.<br><br> <LI><strong>More on GM/UAW negotiations</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> Today's <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> has another story on General Motors' demand for more flexibility in <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=gm06">replacing retirees</A>. <br><br> <LI><strong>New health law may produce surge in job seekers</strong> (Tuesday, 8/6/96) <br> <b>USA Today</b> says that large numbers of people may <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/money/mds9.htm">choose to change jobs</A> after the new health coverage law takes effect. The combination of a strong job market and being able to keep health benefits may make many people want to change. Also, here is a summary of the <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/money/economy/econ0001.htm">latest economic statistics</A> from <b>USA Today</b>. <br><br> <LI><strong>Travel agent job role may be in jeopardy</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> Russell Blinch, writing for <b>Reuters</b>, says that the travel agents may <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960805/compute/stories/plugged_1.html">succumb to the Internet</A> and join a long list of formerly popular occupations that have now receded into history. <br><br> <LI><strong>Clothing workers strike ends</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> According to South Africa's <b>Business Report</b>, a week-long strike of clothing workers has ended after a compromise agreement on a 9 percent wage increase. More that 80,000 workers in 1,200 factories were affected. <br><br> <LI><strong>Retail sales not greatly affected by strikes in Germany</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> <b>Handelsblatt</b> reports that strikes by retail workers unions in Germany have not greatly affected sales. Unions are protesting plans to extend legal store hours and also want more pay.<br><br> <LI><strong>Pragmatism wins over gridlock, according to Monitor</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> In an opinion piece today, the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/edit/edit.2.html">analyzes the resolution</A> of the welfare and health care bill struggles that have been going on so long. Both bills are about to become law. <br><br> <LI><strong>Men falling behind at home</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> Patricia Marks Greenfield, writing for the <b>Los Angeles Times</b>, says that while women's roles at work have been expanding, men's roles at home <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=gree05">haven't kept up</A>. Here article is distributed to many other papers around the country, including the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b>.<br><br> <LI><strong>States worry about finding sufficient jobs</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> Dana Milbank, writing in today's <b>Wall Street Journal</b>, says that the new welfare law's rules requiring work are worrying the states, where finding sufficient jobs may not be possible. The <b>Journal</b> also has a story today about Albania's attraction for foreign business. Inexpensive labor has something to with it. <br><br> <LI><strong>Colleges restructure as budgets shrink</strong> (Monday, 8/5/96) <br> Here's today's <b>USA Today</b> story about the vast changes beginning <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/life/lds007.htm">on the nation's campuses</A>. <br><br> <LI><strong>More bills for President to sign</strong> (Saturday, 8/3/96) <br> After months of conflict and gridlock, the American Congress has brought several long-contested projects to completion. First, the welfare bill is sent to the President, who says he will sign it. Senator Moynihan objects vigorously, saying that it could result in a third of a million children on the streets. If education benefits are denied to children of illegal immigrants, this should also contribute to the number of impoverished street children in the United States, a condition common in third-world countries. This issue is <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/03/048L-080396-idx.html">holding up the immigration bill</A>, reports the <b>Washington Post</b>. However, the Congress has passed the minimum wage bill, as <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960803/news/stories/wage_3.html">Reuters</A> reports. It has <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960803/news/stories/health_11.html">passed the health bill</A> as well. <br><br> <LI><strong>Garment makers say they will move to crackdown on sweatshops</strong> (Saturday, 8/3/96) <br> Both <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960802/news/stories/sweatshops_1.html">Reuters</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/03/032L-080396-idx.html">Washington Post</A> have the story this morning. <br><br> <LI><strong>Miners strike continues in Russia, conditions worsen</strong> (Saturday, 8/3/96) <br> Striking Russian miners haven't been paid for five months and are <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=russ03">beginning to starve</A>, according to a <b>Los Angeles Times</b> story available today in the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b>. Meanwhile, Russian President Yeltsin is said to be so exhausted that he needs two months to recover amid growing concerns about his health. <br><br> <LI><strong>Clinton set to sign</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> President Clinton will sign the new welfare bill, as all American news organizations are reporting, now that it's passed the Senate. Incidentally, here's <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/APONLINE/WASHDC/slugs5327.htm">how the Senators voted</A>. Today's <b>New York Times</b> contains a <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/library/politics/0802clinton-welfare.html">major analysis</A> of how Clinton's position on welfare reflects the "new Democrat." The <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> examines the <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/us/us.3.html">impact of the historic legislation</A> on the states. Today's <b>Washington Post</b> looks at <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/1996-08/02/008R-080296-idx.html">California's situation</A>, and the <b>New York Times</b> reports that a <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/front/welfare-newyork.html">special legislative session</A> may be in the works for New York to deal with implications. <br><br> <LI><strong>Unemployment rate slightly higher</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> <b>Reuters</b> reports that the U.S. unemployment rate <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960802/news/stories/economy_6.html">increased slightly</A> in July, but the number of new unemployment benefit claims fell to a <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/business/stories/jobless_1.html">seven-year low</A> last week. Overall, the <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/econ/econ.1.html">American economy is cooking</A>, and President Clinton's campaign should be helped by the latest figures, according to the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b>.<br><br> <LI><strong>Health care and minimum wage bills soon to become law as well</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> Here's the <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/digest/nat2.htm">Washington Post</A> story and here's the story from <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960802/news/stories/health_9.html">Reuters</A>, which also reports today on <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960802/international/stories/indonesia_4.html">accusations of subversion</A> in Indonesia, and a new <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960802/business/stories/aetna_1.html">pension company</A> in the United States.<br><br> <LI><strong>Pilots to be recalled</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> American Airlines laid off 610 pilots in 1993 and 1994, but the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> reports that they're all getting their jobs back, now that the remaining 376 are being recalled. Crew shortages were resulting in flight cancellations in late July.<br><br> <LI><strong>Fall in Belgium unemployment</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> <b>L'Echo</b> reports that total joblessness in Belgium fell 5.2 percent compared to a year ago. Unemployment is running at 14 percent currently. <br><br> <LI><strong>Japanese firm reduces hiring, rejects racing</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> <b>Nihon Keizai</b> says that Meitec Corporation in Japan will hire 1,500 new employees next year, rather than the 3,500 that were planned. It has also demoted its president because he was prepared to expand the company's business into horse racing. <br><br> <LI><strong>Time to plan retirement is NOW</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> Here's a <b>Washington Post</b> article on <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/business/longterm/mym/columns/retire/whenplan.htm">retirement planning</A>, which is part of a <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/business/longterm/mym/columns/stylist.htm#Retire">larger collection</A>. You'll probably have to scroll downward to see the list. <br><br> <LI><strong>Tokyo Chamber of Commerce wants fewer public servants</strong> (Friday, 8/2/96) <br> <A HREF="http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/news8-96/news.html#story7">Here's the story</A> from today's <b>Japan Times</b>. <br><br> <LI><strong>Welfare bill to become law of the land</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> The top headline above the fold in nearly all American newspapers this morning is that <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/01/154L-080196-idx.html">President Clinton will sign</A> the compromise welfare reform bill passed the House of Representatives yesterday and which is expected to pass the Senate today before being <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/news/stories/welfare_15.html">forwarded to the President</A>. It will be the biggest change in the American social safety net in 60 years. Clinton's decision to sign the bill is <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/news/stories/welfarepolitics_1.html">angering some Democrats</A>. The division among Democrats was reflected in the House vote. By signing the basically Republican bill, Clinton has taken welfare as a presidential campaign issue away from the Republicans, although Candidate Dole is <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/politics/stories/dolewelfare_1.html">claiming credit</A> for it. Robert Reno, writing in <b>Newsday</b>, talks about reform for a "new dark age" and remarks on our <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=reno01">short memories</A>. The ability of the politicians to accurately forecast the behavioral effects of this huge social engineering project depends on the accuracy of their assumptions about human nature, and what they know depends entirely on how they know it. Reports cited here are from the <b>Washington Post</b>, the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b>, and <b>Reuters</b>. <br><br> <LI><strong>New welfare laws in effect in Germany</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> <b>Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung</b> reports that stricter welfare laws take effect today requiring people to accept a wider range of jobs, not just ones specifically tailored to their skills. Otherwise, they will lose 25% of their assistance. <br><br> <LI><strong>American GDP up strongly</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> <b>Reuters</b> reports that the American Gross Domestic Product rose at the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/news/stories/economy_4.html">fastest rate in two years</A> during the second quarter. <br><br> <LI><strong>Agreement on health and minimum wage seems imminent</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/news/stories/health_6.html">Reuters</A> and the <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/01/116L-080196-idx.html">Washington Post</A> report on the flurry of activity in Washington that seems to mean new legislation is on the horizon in additional long-contested areas. However, Democrats worry about the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/politics/stories/wages_1.html">tax cuts</A> included in the minimum wage bill, some calling them <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/business/stories/wage_1.html">"loopholes"</A>. Clay Chandler of the <b>Washington Post</b> says the cuts may <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-08/01/161L-080196-idx.html">help some small businesses</A> but may raise the price of an airline ticket. Incidentally, with respect to the health care issue, today's <b>Wall Street Journal</b> reports that health care costs increased by the smallest amount on record, according to the latest Department of Labor figures. The market seems to be fixing some of the problems that led to heavy discussion of massive health care reform two years ago. The problem of access is still major, however, and the new health care bill will fix only a small part of that. <br><br> <LI><strong>Downsizing at the IRS</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> The Internal Revenue Service, the American agency that collects federal taxes, will <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/news/stories/irs_1.html">eliminate 5,000 jobs</A>. Speaking of taxes, Russia says it will <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960731/international/stories/russia_1.html">crack down on collections</A> in order to ease the "gridlock" problem in the Russian economy. Large numbers of workers have not been paid by the government for months because of inadequate revenues. Among other things, this has led to a major coal minters strike that is further paralyzing the Russian economy.<br><br> <LI><strong>Job cuts at U.S. West</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> U S West Communications has already announced 9,000 jobs overall. Now, it's saying that <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/business/stories/uswest_1.html">5,000 of those</A> will occur by the end of 1997, 1,500 by the <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=jobs01">end of this year</A>. <br><br> <LI><strong>More on the McDonnell Douglas benefit issue</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> Here's <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960801/business/stories/mcdonnell_1.html">another story</A> from <b>Reuters</b> on striking McDonnell Douglas workers' eligibility for unemployment benefits, according to a Missouri state government ruling. <b>Reuters</b> also reports today on a man's winning a $250,000 <A HREF="http://www.latimes.com/HOME/NEWS/APONLINE/NATIONAL/slugs5537.htm">sexual harassment suit</A>. <br><br> <LI><strong>Italian postal service resumes hiring</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> <b>La Repubblica</b> reports that more employees of the Italian postal service than expected have accepted early retirement, so the service will resume hiring. The service had been cutting jobs in order to stem major losses. <br><br> <LI><strong>UK rail workers vote for strikes</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> Disputes over productivity policies and rest breaks have led to a vote to hold a series of 24-hour strikes beginning on August 23. Today's <b>Financial Times</b> reports. <br><br> <LI><strong>France's unemployment at post-war high</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> <b>La Tribune Desfosses</b> reports that France's unemployment rate of 12.5% is the highest since the Second World War. Business is gloomy about the general state of the French economy. <br><br> <LI><strong>Catholic publication sued for questioning morality of job cuts</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> Today's <b>Wall Street Journal</b> reports on a novel libel suit today, as well as the cost of making more than $100,000 per year for an auto worker, and also the cost of free e-mail from your employer.<br><br> <LI><strong>Korean trade union coalition threatens withdrawal</strong> (Thursday, 8/1/96) <br> The Korea Confederation of Trade Unions doesn't like how the labor reform campaign is going, and <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0802/m0802l10.html">may pull out</A>, according to today's <b>Korea Herald</b>. <br><br> </UL> <br> <center><hr width=200; size=5> <FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="default.html"><b>Return to top of home page</strong></A> <p> <FONT SIZE=+1><strong> <A HREF="Today's_news.html">NewWork News</A> | <A HREF="Guest_commentary.html">Guest Commentary</A> | <A HREF="NewWork_reviews.html">Reviews</A> | <A HREF="Tech_watch.html">Tech Watch</A><br> <A HREF="Ed_watch.html">Ed Watch</A> | <A HREF="Resources.html">Resources</A> | <A HREF ="Archives.html">Archives</A> | <A HREF ="Feedback.html">Feedback</A> </FONT></strong></center> <center><hr width=200; size=5></center> <p> <p> <center><img src="LogoB.GIF" alt="[BraveNewWorkWorld and NewWork News are at http://www.newwork.com. All about work. All the time. For business, education, and careers.]"></center> <p> <p> <p> <p> <p> <P><HR><STRONG><FONT SIZE=-1>Copyright &copy; 1996 Gary Johnson Communications. All rights reserved. BraveNewWorkWorld, NewWork, and Women in the New Economy are trademarks of Gary Johnson Communications.</FONT></STRONG> </BODY></HTML> 
