/b> also has stories today on the Labor Secretary's <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/02/085L-090296-idx.html">Labor Day message</A>, <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/02/000L-090296-idx.html">union organizing</A> in Washington, D. C. on a day when the District seems to have <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/02/001L-090296-idx.html">little to celebrate</A>, and some thoughts by Linton Weeks on <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/02/039L-090296-idx.html">Labor Days past</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Trend reverses on women's wages</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> reports that <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960902/business/stories/wages_1.html">women's wages have fallen</A> during the 1990's, reversing a trend through the previous decade. The world's largest wire service also reports that companies with safety violations are still <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960902/business/stories/safety_1.html">getting federal contracts</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>A look at the impact on technology on careers</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>Today' <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> contains an article by Jill Hodges and Jonathan Gaw examining the various ways in which <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=lab02">technology is influencing work</A>. Also, Peter Rachleff looks at how labor activists are <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/rootEval.cgi?currentStory=15026457">learning from each other</A>, and Tom Hamburger explores organized labor's <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/rootEval.cgi?currentStory=15029776">role in politics</A> and its renewed political clout. <br><br><LI><strong>Growth of employment testing</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>Today's <b>New York Times</b> reports that a growing number of employers are adopting the use of <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/front/job-seekers-testing.html">psychological testing</A> in employment situations. We can also report that many psychologists are uneasy, because of the widespread abuse of testing, including the adoption of procedures which have no demonstrable validity whatever. The <b>Times</b> also has advice for those facing the <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/library/jobmarket/0901sabra.html">interviewing ordeal</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>More flexibility on pensions in the Netherlands</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>The Dutch government is liberalizing pension rules. Employees will have more freedom on when they can take their pensions and how large they will be by deciding how much to set aside as they go along. <b>De Telegraaf</b> has the story today.<br><br><LI><strong>Bank mergers blocked by labor laws</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br><b>La Expansion</b> reports that Spain's labor laws are preventing major bank mergers. The country's labor laws are very strict and prevent the kinds of labor cost reductions common with bank mergers in other countries, because of the high cost of firing employees in Spain.<br><br><LI><strong>Hotel workers may strike in Philippines</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>The Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation summit is scheduled for November in the Philippines. Hotel workers are warning that they may strike during that period to protest what they regard as ``exploitation'' by hotel owners. <br><br><LI><strong>Internal conflict in Australian labor organizations</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>The <b>Australian Financial Review</b> reports that Council of Trade Unions President Jennie George is claiming that a "campaign of destabilization" is being waged against her from within the federal Australian Labor Party.<br><br><LI><strong>Hyundai strike continues</strong> (Monday, 9/2/96)<br>The <A HREF="http://zec.three.co.kr/koreaherald/kh0903/m0903l11.html">strike at Hyundai</A> in South Korea has continued nearly a week, according to the <b>Korea Herald</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>American labor movement seen as awakening on Labor Day eve</strong> (Sunday, 9/1/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> says that the American labor movement may not be growing, but it's <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960901/news/stories/labor_1.html">on the move</A>. Today's <b>Washington Post</b> says labor is <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/01/066L-090196-idx.html">getting a young look</A>. The <b>Post</b> also reports that many studies find that American workers are <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-09/01/067L-090196-idx.html">most productive</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>One economist says rates should go up</strong> (Sunday, 9/1/96)<br>A strong economy pleases a lot of people, but makes others nervous about the possibility of inflation getting out of control. <b>Reuters</b> says one economist thinks the Fed should <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960901/business/stories/rates_1.html">raise interest rates</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>What makes officers stay?</strong> (Sunday, 9/1/96)<br>The <b>Jerusalem Post</b> says that a well-paid career, not the strengthening of Zionism, is what makes most Israeli army officers stay in uniform.<br><br><LI><strong>Japanese semiconductor firms cut back on new hiring</strong> (Sunday, 9/1/96)<br>The price of computer chips is continuing to decline. <b>Nihon Keizai</b> reports that major Japanese semiconductor firms are scaling back their hiring as a consequence. <br><br><LI><strong>Entrepreneurial adventure</strong> (Sunday, 9/1/96)<br>Today's <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> contains a story about how one woman is finding the business world to be a <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=blod01">great entrepreneurial adventure</A>. Also, in the <b>Strib</b> today, writer Ed Murphy explains why the <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=murcp">new welfare law disappoints</A>. <br><br></UL><br><center><hr width=200; size=5><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="default.html"><b>Return to top of home page</strong></A><p><FONT SIZE=+1><strong><A HREF="Today's_news.html">NewWork News</A> | <A HREF="Guest_commentary.html">Guest Commentary</A> | <A HREF="NewWork_reviews.html">Reviews</A> | <A HREF="Tech_watch.html">Tech Watch</A><br><A HREF="Ed_watch.html">Ed Watch</A> | <A HREF="Resources.html">Resources</A> | <A HREF ="Archives.html">Archives</A> | <A HREF ="Feedback.html">Feedback</A></FONT></strong></center><center><hr width=200; size=5></center><p><p><center><img src="LogoB.GIF" alt="[BraveNewWorkWorld and NewWork News are at http://www.newwork.com. All about work. All the time. For business, education, and careers.]"></center><p><p><p><p><p><P><HR><STRONG><FONT SIZE=-1>Copyright &copy; 1996 Gary Johnson Communications.All rights reserved. BraveNewWorkWorld, NewWork, and Women in the New Economy are trademarks of Gary Johnson Communications.</FONT></STRONG></BODY></HTML>
