rday that the new Islamic government has announced that women will not be permitted to work. <br><br><LI><strong>Retailing crowded in Shanghai</strong> (Saturday, 10/5/96)<br>The current edition of the <b>Far Eastern Economic Review</b> reports that too many retailers want a piece of the action.<br><br><LI><strong>Joblessness rises</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Latest figures on unemployment from the U.S. Department of Labor in Washington suggest the American economy may be slowing. <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/news/stories/jobs_1.html">Here's the story</A> from <b>Reuters</b>. Interestingly, unemployment is down in the <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/04/019L-100496-idx.html">Washington area itself</A>, but job creation seems centered in the suburbs, according to the <b>Washington Post</b>. Also from <b>Reuters</b> today, the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/news/stories/benefits_1.html">Social Security Administration</A> says "Whoops," the Senate filibuster <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/news/stories/aviation_1.html">has been cut off</A>, clearing way for passage of the aviation bill, and the GM strike in Canada may hurt that country's <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/business/stories/gmcanada_1.html">economic recovery</A>. The <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> reports that it could also <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=AUTO04">delay the release</A> of some of GM's models this fall, and the <b>New York Times</b> says progress in the Canadian talks <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/gm-strike.html">is slow</A>. Things are still hung up over outsourcing for parts. <br><br><LI><strong>French doctors to join in strike</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br><b>Le Figaro</b> reports today that three unions representing French physicians will call on their members to strike on October 17, the day that French civil servants plan to walk out in protest of the French government's planned cuts in public spending. <br><br><LI><strong>Spanish employers have their own plan</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>The Spanish government and representatives of Spanish trade unions have agreed on a plan for reforming pensions, but the Employers trade association CEOE, which has stayed out of the talks, says it has its own plan. The CEOE wants financing of pensions for people who haven't worked shifted from the pension budget into the government's general budget. The employers may also want the government to reduce the amount that corporations will contribute to worker retirement. <b>El Pais</b> reports this morning.<br><br><LI><strong>More on Robert Maxwell's legacy</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Kevin Maxwell, son of the late Robert Maxwell, concealed the transfer of a 32 million-pound transfer of shares from a pension fund that were used to secure a loan for a private Maxwell company, according to <b>The Independent</b> in London. The jury that cleared Robert Maxwell's sons last January was not told of the concealment. <br><br><LI><strong>Legal moves begin against alleged discrimination</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Civil rights organizations are beginning to move against what they say is a pattern of <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/business/stories/lending_1.html">racial discrimination</A> in home mortgage lending throughout the United States.<br><br><LI><strong>New European trends: cuts and picketing</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Gail Russell Chaddock of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> reports on increasing efforts in many European countries to <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/intl/intl.3.html">cut public deficits</A> in order to qualify for the coming common currency, and labor's reactions. Along those lines, here's more on the big <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/intl/intl.4.html">auto workers walkouts</A> in Germany. The <b>Monitor</b> also says today that baseball is <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/opin/opin.4.html">striking out again</A>, and <b>Reuters</b> reports that the umpires <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961004/news/stories/baseball_1.html">plan to strike after all</A>. Finally, here's a story from the <b>Monitor</b> about <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/edit/edit.2.html">Davy, Davy Crockett, sage of the new welfare</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Unions wary of superstores</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Jill Hodges of the <b>Minneapolis Star Tribune</b> reports that <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=TARG04">unions are watching closely</A> as Dayton Hudson Corporation builds very large Target stores. Also, the <b>Strib</b> editorializes today on the new federal budget, which it says is a <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=ED04">betrayal of the world's poor</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Pension rescue in suit industry</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br>Today's <b>New York Times</b> reports on a <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/pensionplan-rescue.html">plan to rescue</A> a pension fund affecting a lot of workers in the men's suit industry. The <b>Wall Street Journal</b> also has the story in today's edition. <br><br><LI><strong>Women now forbidden to work in Afghanistan</strong> (Friday, 10/4/96)<br><A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/afghan-code.html">Peace with repression</A> are reported in this <b>New York Times</b> story. The paper also has stories today on Tony Blair's promises of a <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/britain-labor.html">new future for Britain</A>, very visible <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/ny-cbs-shakeup.html">cuts at WCBS-TV</A> in New York, and a CEO who will receive <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/ceo-compensation.html">zero salary</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Auto strike in Canada</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Talks at General Motors in Canada stalled over outsourcing parts, and the strike deadline arrived without settlement. <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961003/business/stories/canada_1.html">Here's the story</A> from <b>Reuters</b> this morning, and <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/03auto.html">here it is</A> from the <b>New York Times</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Kennedy filibusters on FedEx issue</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Under an old law, Federal Express is considered an airline, while its competitor UPS is considered a trucking company. Adjournment of the 104th Congress is being held up over the issue, as <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961003/business/stories/union_1.html">Reuters</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=FEDX03">Minneapolis Star Tribune</A> report. <br><br><LI><strong>Shift from retirement benefits to stocks</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Corporate shareholders are demanding more accountability, according to a new study from Towers Perrin. It's influencing how outside directors are <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961003/business/stories/directors_1.html">being compensated</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Westinghouse considers cuts</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Westinghouse Electric Corporation plans to conduct a workforce review. It <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/business/stories/westinghouse_1.html">may mean job cuts</A> at its corporate headquarters and elsewhere. Speaking of cuts, troubled <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/tech/stories/ctrn_1.html">Computron Software</A> is slicing 12 percent of its workforce.<br><br><LI><strong>Trotman says they're not trying to hurt GM</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>The head of Ford Motor Company says that the recent agreement at Ford was not aimed at weakening General Motors, according to <b>USA Today</b>. Analysts are suspecting otherwise, given that Ford will save 95 percent of its jobs over the next three years, while GM has to reduce its workforce by more than 40,000 in order to compete effectively. <br><br><LI><strong>Unemployment drops in Belgium</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br><b>De Financieel Economische Tijd</b> reports that Belgians claiming jobless benefits in September declined 7.7 percent compared to a year earlier. However, unemployment is still more than 14 percent in the country. <br><br><LI><strong>Retailers will investigate how suppliers treat workers</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Several major retailers in the United Kingdom are promising to investigate allegations that some of their suppliers are abusing workers by violating codes of practice governing minimum pay and working conditions, according to today's <b>Financial Times</b>. Also in Britain, the <b>Daily Telegraph</b> and the <A HREF="http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/tim/96/10/03/timnwspol02006.html?1067812">London Times</A> report that Tony Blair has defeated a move to commit the Labour Party to higher pensions.<br><br><LI><strong>Spanish government won't wait for union support, they say</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Spanish Labor Minister Javier Arenas says that the Spanish government will reform the labor market with or without union support. Reforms won't include a reduction in the cost of firing workers, but legal criteria for dismissal will be redefined. <b>La Gaceta de Negocios</b> has the story. <br><br><LI><strong>Horse racing organization drops pension fund manager</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>According to Hong Kong's <b>South China Morning Post</b>, the Jockey Club has dropped Jardine Fleming Investment Management. The management firm had handled the majority of Jockey Club's pension funds. Jardine Fleming was fined last month following disclosures that the company had cheated clients. <br><br><LI><strong>Dock workers reject agreements</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Dock workers in <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/03/079L-100396-idx.html">Baltimore</A> and in <A HREF="http://www.boston.com/globe/eco/cgi-bin/retrieve.cgi?%2Fglobe%2Fbgc%2F277%2Feco%2F012">Boston</A> reject pacts. Stories from the <b>Washington Post</b> and the <b>Boston Globe</b>, respectively.<br><br><LI><strong>More on how states are coping with workfare</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>Welfare wasn't well, so now states have to make workfare work. Peter Grier of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> tells <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/us/us.1.html">how states are doing</A>. Also, here's a story about how Americans <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/opin/opin.3.html">have always expected</A> things to get bigger, better. <br><br><LI><strong>Sexual harassment in Central Europe</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>It's not likely that sexual harassment on the job is new in the former communist states of Central Europe, but <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/europe-sex-harass.html">raising the issue</A> seems to be. Jane Perlez of the <b>New York Times</b> reports. The <b>Times</b> also has stories today on the vote to <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/calif-health.html">limit HMOs in California</A> and the high stakes involved, a temporary Congressional change of mind on <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/washpol/aliens-foodstamps.html">food stamps for legal immigrants</A>, and <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/workplace-chaplains.html">clergy working on the job</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Labor conflicts in Boston</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br>The <b>Boston Globe</b> reports that strikers are alleging <A HREF="http://www.boston.com/globe/eco/cgi-bin/retrieve.cgi?%2Fglobe%2Fbgc%2F277%2Feco%2F002">illegal home work</A> at one company, and a union has <A HREF="http://www.boston.com/globe/eco/cgi-bin/retrieve.cgi?%2Fglobe%2Fbgc%2F277%2Feco%2F004">filed a complaint</A> with the NLRB at another. Both companies are involved in the textile industry.<br><br><LI><strong>New immigration bill should be called "Murphy's Law," according to magazine</strong> (Thursday, 10/3/96)<br><b>US News</b> says the new immigration bill might be <A HREF="http://www.usnews.com/usnews/issue/7immig.htm">too tough for our own good</A>. Also, here's a story about the <A HREF="http://www.usnews.com/usnews/issue/7jers.htm">movement of immigrants</A> into American politics. <br><br><LI><strong>Strike deadline tonight; talks snagged</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>Things were looking good for a quick settlement at General Motors in Canada, but now hopes have dimmed. <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/business/stories/gmcaw_1.html">Here's the story</A> from <b>Reuters</b>. <b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> are reporting that agreement between the UAW and GM in the U.S. may be only about a week away. Also, here are <b>Reuters</b> stories about the umpires' <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/news/stories/umps_5.html">decision not to strike</A>, more on the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/business/stories/pension_1.html">pension funds' problems</A> with the ArcherDaniel Midlands Co.'s board, the Teamsters effort to <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961002/politics/stories/teamsters_1.html">organize Capitol police</A>, and Secretary Reich's claim that society has a <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/politics/stories/wage_2.html">moral obligation</A> toward to those who work hard. <br><br><LI><strong>Big protest in Germany</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>More than 100,000 workers have walked out in protest over the new law that enables employers to reduce sick pay. Today's <b>Washington Post</b> <A HREF="http://wp1.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/02/132L-100296-idx.html">has the story</A>, and, of course, it's being reported by all major papers in Germany. <br><br><LI><strong>Japanese salaries up a bit</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br><b>Nihon Keizai</b> reports a 0.4 percent increase in salaries in the private sector last year. The paper also reports that Japan's Ministry of Health and Welfare will allow ailing corporate pension funds to make reduced payments to retirees beginning next April. <br><br><LI><strong>Why savings might be declining</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>Savings slipping because older folks are spending more? Maybe. <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/02/017L-100296-idx.html">Here's the story</A> from today's <b>Washington Post</b>. Also, here's more on that <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/02/012L-100296-idx.html">Federal Express story</A> reported yesterday. <br><br><LI><strong>Study says poorer outcomes for the elderly with HMOs</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>A new study finds <A HREF="http://wp1.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/02/098L-100296-idx.html">worse care for older people</A> from HMOs, according to a <b>Washington Post</b> story this morning. Meanwhile, the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> reports on the <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/us/us.4.html">growing backlash</A> against HMOs. <br><br><LI><strong>Big change in Mongolia</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>Sheila Tefft of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> reports that state ownership may be <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/intl/intl.9.html">on the way out</A> now that Mongolia has new leadership. <br><br><LI><strong>Labor problems, injuries at a plastics factory</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br><A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/plastics-factory-safety.html">Here's the story</A> from the <b>New York Times</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Job guarantees more symbolic than real</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>Daniel Howes of the <b>Detroit News</b> says that the big auto companies don't much mind the job guarantees in the new contracts, because there are <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/1996/menu/stories/67627.htm">plenty of exceptions</A>. Also, today's <b>News</b> reports on <A HREF="http://www.detnews.com/1996/menu/stories/67629.htm">changes in the UAW</A> under President Steve Yokich. <br><br><LI><strong>Kiwi to cut flights and jobs</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>The <b>Chicago Sun-Times</b> <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/business/bizitems/KIWI_Oct02.html">reports on the bankruptcy</A> of Kiwi International Air Lines. <br><br><LI><strong>First day of welfare reform in the Bay area</strong> (Wednesday, 10/2/96)<br>Kevin Fagan of the <b>San Francisco Chronicle</b> reports on <A HREF="http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/chronicle/article.cgi?MNE12188.DTL:/chronicle/archive/1996/10/02">welfare limbo</A> as the changes kick in. <br><br><LI><strong>Happy birthday to us, happy birthday to us</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br><b>BraveNewWorkWorld</b> is a year old. However, <b>NewWork News</b> won't be able to celebrate its first anniversary until January 2. <br><br><LI><strong>Key welfare changes begin today</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>The new welfare law in the United States is beginning to take effect. Today's <b>New York Times</b> says that welfare's new future will <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/welfare-assess.html">depend on the states</A>. Also in the <b>Times</b> today, a commentary by Clyde Haberman on the impact being felt in <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/haberman-column.html">soup kitchens</A>, a story on how a New York union leader is in hot water because of <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/ny-labor-welfare.html">workfare concessions</A>, and a story about the New York mayor's <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/national/ny-mayor-welfare.html">legal challenge</A> to the new welfare law. The <b>Washington Post</b> reports on a struggle with the <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/01/073L-100196-idx.html">concept of "work"</A> in Alaska. Also, <b>Reuters</b> reports that George Soros doesn't like the new welfare system's impact on immigrants at all, and draws on his own experience as well as his bank account to help. He's <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960930/news/stories/immigrants_1.html">contrbuting $50 million</A>.<br><br><LI><strong>How new immigration policy looks from California</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>Today's <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/us/us.3.html">reports on the view</A> from the American west coast. <br><br><LI><strong>Senate stays in session to vote on union issue</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>The issue affects only Federal Express Corporation. <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/news/stories/senate_2.html">Here's the story</A> from <b>Reuters</b>, which also has stories today on a <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/news/stories/umps_1.html">threat from baseball umpires</A>, the beginning of the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/business/stories/wage_1.html">new minimum wage</A>, and more on the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960930/international/stories/france_1.html">teachers strike</A> in France. Incidentally, the <b>New York Times</b> today suggests that the <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/minimumwage-impact.html">new minimum wage</A> may not have much effect. <br><br><LI><strong>Progress at GM in Canada</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> reports on the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/business/stories/caw_1.html">GM negotiations in Canada</A>, as well as on what the Chrysler agreement will mean for <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/960930/business/stories/autos_9.html">negotiations at GM in the U.S</A>. <b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>Wall Street Journal</b> say that GM may benefit from job-guarantee escape clauses included in the new agreements at both Ford and Chrysler. <br><br><LI><strong>Labor looks at IBM</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br><b>Reuters</b> reports on a Department of Labor investigation over whether IBM violated <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/tech/stories/ibm_13.html">wage and hour laws</A>. Also, here's a story about a speech by a European Union official and the need for <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961001/tech/stories/people_1.html">people to come first</A> in the information society.<br><br><LI><strong>Law firm folds over pay dispute</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br><A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/01/029L-100196-idx.html">Here's the story</A> from today's <b>Washington Post</b>, as well as a story about <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-10/01/058L-100196-idx.html">Indonesia's economic transformation</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Coping in the Russian economy</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>Peter Ford of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> tells about making it, or not making it, in <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/graphical/today/intl/intl.2.html">today's Russia</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Manager in name only</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>Being a boss at the bottom of the ladder isn't easy, according to today's <b>Wall Street Journal</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>More benefit cuts coming in Germany</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>More companies plan to scale back employee benefits in Germany, according to this <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/germany-labor.html">New York Times story</A>. Also in Germany today, <b>Frankfurter Rundschau</b> reports that strikes are planned at Ford, Opel, and Daimler over the sick pay issue. German papers are also reporting that Finance Minister Waigel wants a maximum income tax of 40% by 1999, and that union leaders at IG Metall are willing to start wage negotiations earlier than originally planned. <br><br><LI><strong>Want to start a business? What does it take?</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>What makes a good entrepreneur? <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/library/jobmarket/0929sabra.html">Here are some thoughts</A> from the <b>New York Times</b>, which also reports today on complaints from <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/adm.html">two large pension funds</A>. <br><br><LI><strong>Ten percent tax rate promised</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>The UK's opposition Labour Party's annual conference is continuing, and Gordon Brown, shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer, says a Labour government would commit to a 10 percent income tax rate for the nation's lowest paid workers. The <b>Financial Times</b>, the <b>Daily Telegraph</b>, and other major papers have the story this morning. <br><br><LI><strong>Semperit Reifen employees to resist "by all means"</strong> (Tuesday, 10/1/96)<br>Austria's <b>Wiener Zeitung</b> reports that employees at the Austrian tiremaking division of Germany's Continental AG threaten to prevent the move of factory equipment to the Czech Republic. An overwhelming majority voted to resist the move. <br><br></UL><br><center><hr width=200; size=5><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="default.html"><b>Return to top of home page</strong></A><p><FONT SIZE=+1><strong><A HREF="Today's_news.html">NewWork News</A> | <A HREF="Guest_commentary.html">Guest Commentary</A> | <A HREF="NewWork_reviews.html">Reviews</A> | <A HREF="Tech_watch.html">Tech Watch</A><br><A HREF="Ed_watch.html">Ed Watch</A> | <A HREF="Resources.html">Resources</A> | <A HREF ="Archives.html">Archives</A> | <A HREF ="Feedback.html">Feedback</A></FONT></strong></center><center><hr width=200; size=5></center><p><p><center><img src="LogoB.GIF" alt="[BraveNewWorkWorld and NewWork News are at http://www.newwork.com. All about work. All the time. For business, education, and careers.]"></center><p><p><p><p><p><P><HR><STRONG><FONT SIZE=-1>Copyright &copy; 1996 