LI><strong>Report says many will qualify for common currency</strong> (Thursday, 11/7/96)<br><b>Bloomberg</b> and the <b>New York Times</b> report that the European Commission is saying that many countries are <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/euro.html">on course to qualify</A> for the intended common European currency by 1999. Many nations must reduce budget deficits in order to do so. <b>La Libre Belgique</b> says that Belgium will make it, and <b>Salzburger Nachrichten</b> reports that Austria will qualify as well. Both have been among European countries that have experienced considerable union resistance to government efforts to cut budgets in order to reduce deficits as part of their qualification efforts. <br><br><LI><strong>Italian government can hire part-timers</strong> (Thursday, 11/7/96)<br><b>Corriere della Sera</b> reports that the lower house has approved a new rule that will allow the Italian government to hire part-time workers. Workers will also be allowed to earn money from other work outside the government. One of the principal trends in many countries has been toward greater reliance on part-time and temporary or contract work, as opposed to full-time jobs with benefits. <br><br><LI><strong>Philippine official warns about inflation</strong> (Thursday, 11/7/96)<br>Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Habito warns that inflation in the Philippines could average 11 percent this year if the minimum age is increased immediately. Original inflation projections were for an average of 8.7 percent. Trade unions want a 45 peso increase in the daily minimum wage which is now set at 165 pesos, according to <b>Business Daily</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>Fun at work may pay off</strong> (Thursday, 11/7/96)<br>Kim Campbell of the <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> writes that companies are beginning to think that fun is good for morale and <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/reduced/today/econ/econ.1.html">good for business</A>. Also, he