961101/news/stories/economy_8.html">Reuters</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/financial/econ-report-art.html">New York Times</A> today. <br><br><LI><strong>Job cuts at Dayton Hudson</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>About <A HREF="http://www.startribune.com/cgi-bin/article/slugEval.cgi?currentSlug=DH02">180 jobs will be cut</A> from Dayton Hudson's department store unit, most of them in the central headquarters in Minneapolis. An analyst thinks it's <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/business/bizitems/FIELD_Nov02.html">just the beginning</A>, given the company's commitment to reducing costs. Also, a major <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961101/business/stories/usrobotics_1.html">modem manufacturer</A> is cutting jobs. <br><br><LI><strong>Hard times for grads in Japan</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>Only about 2/3 of <A HREF="http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/news10-96/news.html#story5">last spring's university graduates</A> got jobs, according to the <b>Japan Times</b>, and the largest number were in the service sector. It's the worst for graduates since 1950. The once mighty Japanese economy has been struggling for some time. <br><br><LI><strong>Dip in federal contracts hits Maryland suburbs</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>Peter Behr writes in today's <b>Washington Post</b> that the decline in federal contracts has resulted in <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-11/02/018L-110296-idx.html">slower job growth</A> in the D. C. suburbs. <br><br><LI><strong>Republicans want investigation into Administration's immigration policies</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>Congressional Republicans thinks that the Clinton Administration may have engaged in <A HREF="http://wp2.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-11/02/079L-110296-idx.html">criminal activity</A> in accelerating the naturalization of immigrants in advance of the new immigration law. It's only one of a number of accusations being made against the Administration that will undoubtedly be pursued if Clinton wins the election Tuesday, as expected. Candidate Perot thinks that the Administration will have major legal problems and that a scandal on the level of Watergate may develop. The latest charges relate to campaign fund raising activities. <br><br><LI><strong>Tougher strike ballots called for in Britain</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br><A HREF="http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/tim/96/11/02/timnwsnws01036.html?1067812">Here's a story</A> from the <b>London Times</b> resulting from a leak. Philip Bassett reports. <br><br><LI><strong>Replacements to be hired in Illinois teachers strike</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>Schools will open in Niles Township with <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/news/newsitems/NILE_Nov02.html">replacement teachers</A>, according to today's <b>Chicago Sun-Times</b>. Talks have proved unproductive. <br><br><LI><strong>Big controversy over pregnant illegal immigrants in California</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>California's Governor Wilson says the state <A HREF="http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/chronicle/article.cgi?file=MN31100.DTL&directory=/chronicle/archive/1996/11/02">must end prenatal services</A> to illegal immigrants because of the new welfare law. Counties in the San Francisco area refuse to halt benefits, according to the <b>San Francisco Chronicle</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Want to buy something? Don't be a nuisance</strong> (Saturday, 11/2/96)<br>German retailers are <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/news/world/germany-storehours-art.html">trying to be nice to customers</A> as new retail hours take effect. Here's a report by Edmund Andrews from the <b>New York Times</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>U.S. unemployment steady</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>The U.S. unemployment rate <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961101/news/stories/economy_7.html">remained at 5.2 percent</A> in October, according to Labor Department statistics. <br><br><LI><strong>Auto talks resume this morning</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>Negotiations continued late into the night last night at General Motors, but no agreement was reached. They're starting up again this morning. Here's the story from <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961101/news/stories/gm_31.html">Reuters</A> and also from the <A HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1996-11/01/042L-110196-idx.html">Washington Post</A>. <b>Reuters</b> also reports on the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961031/business/stories/suppliers_1.html">wage pressures</A> GM is feeling from parts makers, and a parts company executive paints a grim picture of the future. <br><br><LI><strong>Luggage manufacturer to cut jobs</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/961101/business/stories/samsonite_1.html">About 6%</A> of the workforce will go at Samsonite, according to <b>Reuters</b>. <br><br><LI><strong>Privatization in Turkey</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>The Turkish government has put eight seaports on the market and has announced that 45 bids have come in, according to <b>Hurriyet</b>.<br><br><LI><strong>U.K. and E.U. to clash over work week</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>London's <b>Financial Times</b> reports today that the European Court of Justice is expected to impose a maximum 48-hour work week on Britain. In response, the British government intends to veto EU reforms. <br><br><LI><strong>You can shop longer in Germany beginning today</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>A new German law allows retail stores to stay open longer, and estimates are that about 75 percent of the stores in the country will take advantage of it, beginning today. Retail worker trade unions have resisted the change. A similar move is underway in Austria. <b>Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung</b> has the story in Germany this morning. <br><br><LI><strong>Battle over Proposition 209 appears to narrow</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>All of the U.S. and some other parts of the world are watching an attempt in California to roll back affirmative action. Today's <b>Christian Science Monitor</b> reports that the it <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/reduced/today/us/us.5.html">may be a close vote</A> on Tuesday. Also, David R. Francis examines the <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/reduced/today/econ/econ.1.html">debate over Social Security</A> in the U.S., and Paul A. Eisenstein reports that Chrysler Corporation is intending to become even more <A HREF="http://www.csmonitor.com/todays_paper/reduced/today/econ/econ.2.html">lean and efficient</A> in its operations, which may have further implications for employment. <br><br><LI><strong>Teachers strike in Illinois</strong> (Friday, 11/1/96)<br>Susan Dodge writes in the <b>Chicago Sun-Times</b> today about the strike in Niles Township and looks at <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/news/newsitems/TEAC_Nov01.html">how well the teachers are paid</A>. Also in the <b>Sun-Times</b> today, stories about a <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/business/bizitems/TEAM_Nov01.html">different presidential election</A> than the one that may be on your mind, and ratification of <A HREF="http://www.suntimes.com/business/bizitems/RAIL_Nov01.html">a new labor agreement</A> at Illinois Central Railroad.<br><br></UL><br><center><hr width=200; size=5><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="default.html"><b>Return to top of home page</strong></A><p><FONT SIZE=+1><strong><A HREF="Today's_news.html">NewWork News</A> | <A HREF="Guest_commentary.html">Guest Commentary</A> | <A HREF="NewWork_reviews.html">Reviews</A> | <A HREF="Tech_watch.html">Tech Watch</A><br><A HREF="Ed_watch.html">Ed Watch</A> | <A HREF="Resources.html">Resources</A> | <A HREF ="Archives.html">Archives</A> | <A HREF ="Feedback.html">Feedback</A></FONT></strong></center><center><hr width=200; size=5></center><p><p><center><img src="LogoB.GIF" alt="[BraveNewWorkWorld and NewWork News are at http://www.newwork.com. All about work. All the time. For business, education, and careers.]"></center><