<HEAD>
<TITLE>Holographic Temperature Measurement within the Thermal Boundary Layer </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Holographic Temperature Measurement within the Thermal Boundary Layer</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>
Summary:
<P>

</B>
Heat transfer measurements in internal combustion engines are complex due to the non-steady pressure gradients, turbulence parameters and reaction zones. In steadystate conditions the physical mechanisms of heat transfer at the interface between the hot gas and the wall are basically the same as in dynamic considerations. For engines, variables of interest include surface  heat transfer, boundary layer temperature distribution and boundary layer thickness. In heat transfer experiments the objective among them is to determine the temperature distribution throughout a gas or fluid. Since the laminar sublayer thickness can be in the regime of micrometers, an appropriate high-resolution measurement technique is considered.
<P>
The experimental approach within this project relies on known physical foundations where functional relations depend in e.g. thermal refractive index change of the gas or terms of the scattering mechanism for phonon heat conduction. For quantitative determination of temperature profiles in the boundary layer, heterodyne holographic interferometry, a special opto-electronic measurement technique, has been introduced. The basic idea is to introduce a small frequency shift between the optical frequencies of the two interfering light fields. This results in an intensity modulation of the two light fields for any given point in the interference pattern. With this technique the interference phase can be measured with an accuracy of +/- 0.3% at any point in the fringe pattern corresponding to an interpolation of better than 1/1000 of one fringe with a high spatial resolution.
<P>
Contacts:
<P>
R. M&uuml;ller, B. Ineichen
<P>
Electronic Contacts:
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:"rene.mueller@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch>mueller@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch</A>  
<P>
Index Terms:
<P>
Holography<BR>
Interferometry<BR>
Measurement Technique<BR>
Temperature Measurement
<P>
Supported By:
<P>
Swiss Federal Office Commission for Scientific Research (KWF), Grant Number 2207.1, and the National Energy Research Fund (NEFF), Grant Number NEFF 638.
<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Public.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="Home Page Public"></A>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Intern/Erste_Seite_Intern.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Intern.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="Home Page Intern"></A>
<A HREF="mailto:www@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Administrator.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="e-mail to administrator"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-DOWN.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ DOWN"></A>
