<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hybrid III - a powertrain for an advanced Hybrid vehicle</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Hybrid III, - a powertrain for an advanced Hybrid vehicle</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>
Summary:
</B>
<P>
The ETH flywheel hybrid power train is a project, to explore the potential of ultimate fuel economy of power trains assigned to passenger cars. The project has been launched in spring 1990. All the major simulations have been completed and the individual components of the power train have been submitted to excessive testing. The different test results show, that the major goals of the project can be achieved.
<P>
<B>
Concept:
</B>
<P>
This concept of the parallel hybrid power train shown in Fig.1 contains some features which are specifically designed or adapted for the project's purpose; among them a combustion engine (SI engine, 1.3l, 50 kW), an electric motor, a flywheel and a continuously variable transmission with a very high gear ratio (i2 - CVT).
<P>
The vehicle is supposed to be powered by the flywheel when operating at moderate speed (up to 10 kW power demand). If the flywheel's capacity falls short of the tolerated minimum level, it will be recharged by the SI engine at open throttle. The engine will be cut off after the flywheel has reached the proper frequency. This operating mode is called "Duty Cycle Operation" (DCO). There is the possibility to store a considerable amount of braking energy into the flywheel during decelerations. The power train is switched from flywheel power to direct engine power at higher speeds, while the i2 - CVT is running the engine at its highest possible efficiency.
<P>
The power train includes an additional specially designed electric motor (6 kW) to give the vehicle a possibility of a short driving range (20 km) by zero tail - pipe emissions. This motor is also able to provide engine starting- and alternator- duties. Despite of the motor's modest performance and the additional weight of the concept, there is sufficient power available since the flywheel can be used to cover the peak power needs of the electric motor.
<P>
The individual test trials of the different components have shown a considerable fuel economic potential of up to 40% at part load. The power train has been submitted to dynamic trials in July 1996 with good results concerning fuel consumption and emissions at ECE-Cycles.
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG VALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH=270 SRC="PtrainI.GIF" ALT="The ETH Hybrid Powertrain"></CENTER>



Contacts:
<P>
Philipp Dietrich; Martin Ender, Christian Wittmer
<P>
