<HEAD>
<TITLE>Novel Load Control System for IC-Engines</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Optimization of Part Load Performance of S.I. Engines Using Secondary Inlet Valves</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<I>
COPYRIGHT SAE
<P>
PLEASE NOTICE THAT ONLY SOME PARTS ARE PRESENTED AT THIS SITE. FOR FURTHER INFORMATION PLEASE CONTACT US OR BUY THE ORIGINAL PAPER.
<P>
</I>
<FONT SIZE=5>
An Initial Study of Variable Valve Timing
Implemented with a Secondary Valve
in the Intake Runner
</FONT>
<P>
<B>
O. Vogel (1), K. Roussopoulos (1), L. Guzzella (1), J. Czekaj (2)
</B>
<P>
(1) Swiss Federal Institute of Technology
(2) Ford Motor Company
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
SAE Paper 960590
</FONT>
<P>
<I>
To be presented at the 1996 SAE Annual Congress and Exposition, Detroit, MI, 26-30 February 1996
and published in SAE Special Publication SP -1171 'Variable Valve Actuation and Power Boost.'
</I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
ABSTRACT
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
This paper describes an investigation of implementing variable valve timing with the use of a secondary valve in the intake tract. The secondary valve acts in series with the conventional poppet valve of the engine, which is actuated in the conventional manner and with fixed timing. It is significantly easier to adjust the timing of the secondary valve than that of the main valve. There are two possible modes of operation of this device. One is to control valve overlap, improving low speed low load performance. The other is to use it as a load control mechanism, replacing the conventional throttle and therefore reducing the 'pumping losses' associated with conventional throttling. We have implemented such a system on a motored single-cylinder research engine using pneumatic actuation. Our experiments have demonstrated successful load control, significant pumping loss reduction, and control of backflow from the exhaust to the intake manifold.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
INTRODUCTION
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
Conventional automotive engines suffer from the drawback that the timing of the intake event is invariant with engine speed and load. It has long been known that improvements in gasoline engine performance would be obtainable if the valve timing were variable so that it could be optimised for any combination of load and speed in the engine's operating range. A great deal of work is currently under way on schemes for variable valve timing (VVT), some of which are starting to come to market. It remains true, however, that the difficulties of providing a variable valve timing mechanism with acceptable performance, cost and reliability for general usage have yet to be satisfactorily solved.<P>
This paper describes an investigation of a method of implementing VVT with the use of a secondary valve in the intake tract. The principle is that the secondary valve acts in series with the conventional poppet valve of the engine, which is actuated in the conventional manner and with fixed timing. The secondary valve is not required to withstand the temperatures and pressures of combustion, and therefore can be of relatively lightweight design. It is therefore significantly easier to adjust the timing of the secondary valve than that of the main valve.<P>
There are two possible modes of operation of this device. One is to use it as a load control mechanism, replacing the conventional throttle and therefore reducing the 'pumping losses' associated with conventional throttling.The other is to control valve overlap, improving low speed low load (idling) performance. In the load control mode, the secondary valve closes early in the intake stroke of the engine, limiting the flow of air and fuel into the cylinder. The timing of the valve closure governs the load of the engine. In this manner some losses resulting from the irreversible nature of flow past a throttle plate are avoided, and a fuel economy benefit should accrue. This is very similar to load control by use of early intake valve closure. In the overlap control mode, the secondary valve remains closed as the main valve opens, preventing the 'backflow' of air and exhaust residual from the exhaust to the inlet port that can deteriorate engine performance at idle. The secondary valve opens once the exhaust valve has been effectively closed. This of course allows the main valve timings to be set to a high degree of overlap, resulting in higher possible torque and power at high load high speed operating points (at which the secondary valve would be permanently open).<P>
The purpose of this study was not to develop actuators and algorithms suitable for deployment on a prototype or production vehicle, but to investigate in a laboratory what magnitude of benefits could be expected from such a deployment. We have implemented such a secondary valve and tested its performance on a motored single cylinder research engine. We wish to emphasise that we have made no effort yet to develop an actuator suitable for in-car use, and also that we have made no effort to develop an energy-efficient actuator: these tasks will be considered if it becomes clear that doing so is worthwhile.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
DISCUSSION
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>

We have implemented an actuator able to test the secondary valve concept. This actuator is able to open or close the intake port upstream of the poppet valve in a few milliseconds. With this actuator we were able to use the secondary valve concept to demonstrate the main identified benefits of variable valve timing: throttleless load control, with accompanying savings of pumping work, and backflow control at low loads (the latter obtained with extreme valve timings). The results obtained are in line with the predictions made on the basis of theoretical work: i.e., fuel savings at part load of around 5% and at idle of about 15% (the idle figure being based purely on analytical work alone). These predictions, along with the expected benefits of the backflow control possibilities, await validation on a firing engine.<P>
It is worth noting that when a secondary valve is used to regulate the engine load it becomes possible to vary the engine load from one cycle to the next -- indeed, in a multicylinder engine, from one cylinder firing to the next. This might have considerable value in enabling better control of an engine in transient conditions, as well as in controlling cylinder to cylinder variations in torque, air-fuel ratio, etc.<P>
The next stage of our study will be to implement the secondary valve concept on a production engine. We currently intend to implement a very similar actuator to that described in this paper on such an engine. This device has proved itself to be remarkably robust, reliable and repeatable. If the benefits deduced from the experiments described in this paper are indeed demonstrated on a production engine, the next task would be to investigate practical implementations of this concept for automotive application.
</FONT>
<P>
