<HEAD>
<TITLE>PALOS - Power Source for Lightweight Passenger Cars</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG
SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100%
BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>PALOS - Power Source for Lightweight Passenger Cars</FONT>
<P> 
<HR WIDTH=80%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=4>
<P>
<B>
Summary:
</B>
<P>
Calculations show that the carbon-dioxide output per energy unit of an
electric vehicle whose batteries are charged in the European grid is larger
than the output of a small and part-load optimized SI-engine. This
observation is the starting point for a multi-disciplinary project, whose
goal is to realize such a propulsion system especially well suited for
light vehicles. Based on the experiences of earlier projects the
keycomponents of such a device are now identified, i.e. part-load
optimization (EGR, valve-control, charged and small engine, etc.), friction
reduction (motor state-dependent coolant temperature, etc.),  heat storage
for reduction of the engine warm-up time, flexible and controllable
drive-trains (CVT, etc.),  storage of the kinetic energy  instead of
dissipation during decceleration (recuperation), engine deactivation
instead of idling and automatic reactivation, careful heat-management and
enhanced exhaust-gas treatment.
<P>
Special emphasis is laid on the modelling and a priori optimization of the
entire propulsion system using mathematical models of all components.
<P>
Contacts:
<P>
L. Guzzella, A. Amstutz, E. Cortona, R. Pfiffner, P. Soltic, F. Weber
<P>
