<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reduction of NOx-Emissions of Medium-Size/Medium-Speed D.I. Diesel Engines</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Reduction of NOx-Emissions of Medium-Size/Medium-Speed D.I. Diesel Engines</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>Summary:
</B>
<P>
Exhaust gas recirculation is a well established method to reduce NOx-emissions of diesel engines. The trade-off existing between NOx and fuel consumption leads to the fact that, in industrial practice, only limited recirculation rates are interesting. Thus, the target is to establish a method for reducing NOx without degradation of engine performance, especially fuel consumption.
<P>
The combination of exhaust gas recirculation with the Miller system and a flexible injection system is the most promising way to reach the goal of nitric oxide emission reduction without degradation in engine performance and efficiency.
<P>
The Miller system allows for operation at higher charging pressures by closing the inlet valve before BDC. The cylinder charge at BDC has thus for the same pressure higher density and lower temperature. This leads to generally lower temperatures during the complete process and by that to a further reduction of NOx-emissions as could be shown in the experiments, where reductions in brake specific nitric oxide emissions of up to 20% have been observed. At the same time, fuel consumption decreased in the order of 0.5 - 2%.
<P>
This improvement in fuel consumption can now be used to partially compensate for the losses associated with high recirculation rates when combining the Miller system with EGR to further reduce NOx. Measurements with recirculation rates of up to 13% yielded NOx- reductions of 35 to 60% while fuel consumption increased between 1 and 5%, respectively.
<P>
The additional application of a common rail injection system is expected to even  further improve engine efficiency and emissions.
<P>
In parallel to the experimental investigations models describing the formation and destruction of NOx in D.I. diesel engines are developed. A quasi-dimensional model with detailed chemistry serves as an instrument for the evaluation of potentials. Starting from detailed mechanisms reduced kinetic models are derived for the implementation into a CFD-code to enable the transfer of experimental results to other engine configurations and geometries.
<P>
Contacts:
<P>
G. Weisser, H.R. Stebler, K. Boulouchos
<P>
Electronic Contacts:
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:"stebler@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch>stebler@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch</A>   
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:"weisser@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch>weisser@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch</A>
<P>
Index Terms:
<P>
Miller-System<BR>
High Pressure Exhaust Gas Recirculation<BR>
Common Rail Injection System<BR>
Multiple Zone Model<BR>
Detailed Mechanism for NOx Formation
<P>
Supported By:
<P>
National Energy Research Fund (NEFF), The Swiss Federal Office of Energy (BEW), New Sulzer Diesel (NSD), and ABB Turbo Systems.
