<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Soot Particle Formation and Oxidation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Soot Particle Formation and Oxidation</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>Summary:
</B>
<P>
Laser light scatter transmission methods of Mie's theory have been used to study the behavior of soot particles in diffusion flames. These methods have made it possible to measure with some accuracy the diameter, number and density of soot particles in steady and non-steady flames. However, the determination of the soot particle diameter depends on the complex refractive index. A soot particle is an absorptive substance, its chemical composition is variable, and its optical constant differs according to the temperature. It is very difficult to determine accurately the complex refractive index (the optical constant) and the surface temperature of a soot particle. Under these circumstances, it is necessary to develop and establish a method of simultaneously measuring the diameter of soot  particles and their surface temperature and refractive index in a non-contact way using some means which can enhance the time and space resolution in flames. This study has established methods for measuring all of them. It is based on multiple pieces of in formation obtained from the combined use of an 
opto-acoustic deflection technique and of the light scatter and transmission methods. The surface temperature measurement technique has been tested in an actual flame and has been compared with a holographic method.
<P>
Contacts:
<P>
B. Mandel, B. Ineichen
<P>
Electronic Contacts:
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:"mandel@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch>mandel@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch</A>
<P>
Index Terms:
<P>
Laser Diagnostics
<P>
Soot Particle Characterization<BR>
Temperature Measurement<BR>
Diesel Combustion
<P>
