<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Research on Diesel Sprays in the High Pressure and High Temperature Cell
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF">
<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100%  BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER="2">

<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH=558><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="Spray.gif" ALT="Bildli Spray"></CENTER></TD>

<TD ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH=514>
<H1><CENTER>Study of the Atomization of Diesel Fuel Sprays in the High Pressure and High Temperature Cell </CENTER></H1>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<HR>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=5>Summary:</FONT> </B></U>
<P>
Realistic physical and computational models of the
atomization and penetration of high speed liquid fuel jets are
required if the fuel/air mixing processes in many combustors are
to be understood. This will lead to the formulation of effective
design criteria for optimizing the performance of the fuel injection
equipment and combustion system. 
<P>
This investigation into the fundamental processes
governing liquid atomization applies Phase Doppler Anemometry
to study a high pressure transient Diesel fuel spray injected
into a high pressure, high temperature combustion cell. This combustion
cell provides a flexible facility to study sprays over a wide
range of environments, including conditions found in Diesel engine
combustion chambers. 
<P>
The applied measurement technique, Phase Doppler
Anemometry (PDA), measures simultaneously the velocity and size
of individual droplets passing through a small measurement volume.
Scanning the measurement volume over a grid of measurement points
in the spray allows a visualization of the dynamic planar droplet
flow field structure to be presented in terms of the time varying
droplet trajectories, velocities and sizes. 
<P>
This project is supported by the Swiss Federal Office
of Energy (BEW), Grant Number EF-FOS(90)003
<HR>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=5>Contacts:</FONT> </B></U>
