<HEAD>
<TITLE>Systematic reduction of complex reaction mechanisms</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Systematic reduction of complex reaction mechanisms</FONT>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>
Summary:
</B>
<P>
Detailed reaction  mechanisms are usually too complex to be used in full simulations of combustion phenomena (i.e. including both hydrodynamic and chemical effects), since they dramatically increase the computational time by introducing a large number of chemical time scales  (and therefore stiffness). Simplified reaction schemes, that are capable of reproducing the chemical properties of the reacting system, offer a viable alternative.
<P>
The conventional method of obtaining a reduced mechanism, based on the educated use of steady state and partial equilibrium approximations, relies heavily on intuition and experience on the particular system. Furthermore, the optained reduced scheme is usually not only specific to the problem under consideration, but also depends strongly on the  initial conditions considered.
<P>
Computational Singular Perturbation (CSP) provides a systematic, automated way and a programmable algorithm to identify fast reactions and steady-state species, find exhausted reaction rates and derive simplified kinetic schemes. CSP data, obtained during the analysis, provide physical insight and understanding of the mechanism under consideration. They can also be used to asses sensitivity of solutions with respect to input rate coefficients, and offer an alternative to the  conventional method of sensitivity analysis.
<P>
Contacts:
<P>
C. Frouzakis
<P>
Electronic Contact:
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:"frouzakis@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch>frouzakis@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch</A>
<P>
Index Terms:
<P>
Reaction Kinetics<BR>
Computational Singular Perturbation<BR>
Low NOx Premixed Combustion
<P>
Supported By:
<P>
National Energy Research Fund (NEFF), Grant Number 670.
<P>
Collaboration with ABB Corporate Research, Switzerland.
<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Public.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="Home Page Public"></A>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Intern/Erste_Seite_Intern.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Intern.GIF" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0 WIDTH=33% ALT="Home Page Intern"></A>
<A HREF="mailto:www@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Administrator.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="e-mail to administrator"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/index.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-DOWN.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100% BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ DOWN"></A>
