<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>HEAT TRANSFER - Affection by a Dynamic Soot Layer</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Hintergrund.GIF" >
<A
HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Publik/Projects/X0013_Transition_to_Turbul.html"><IMG
SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Balken-UP.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100%
BORDER=0  ALT="IET/LVV ETHZ UP"></A><P><FONT SIZE=5>

Computational Investigation of Unsteady Heat Flux Through an I. C. Engine Cylinder Wall including Soot Layer Dynamics

</FONT><P><HR WIDTH=100%  ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=3><P><B>Summary:</B><P>

Heat transfer between fluid and combustion chamber wall is of importance and relevance to i. c. engines performance, thermal efficiency and pollutant emissions. This is particularly true with regard to low-heat-rejection engine concepts. There is an unresolved fundamental issue, as to what are the mechanisms of repeatedly observed enhancement of the apparent heat transfer coefficient, if reduced cooling and/or low-conductivity wall materials are used. Among several theories proposed, flame-wall interactions within the boundary layer and soot layer deposition and the oxidation have drawn particular attention during the last years.

<P>

This project deals with the influence of a wall soot layer of varying thickness on the unsteady heat transfer between the fluid and the engine cylinder wall during a full cycle of a four-stroke-engine operation. For that purpose a computational investigation has been carried out, using a 1-D model of a multi-layer solid wall for simulating the transient response within the confinement of the combustion chamber. The soot layer is thereby of varying thickness over time, depending on the relative rates of deposition and oxidation. The deposition rate is controlled mainly by thermophoretic effects, while the soot oxidation rate is obtained by means of an Arrhenius type process as a function of temperature and oxygen content, in the free stream. The input heat flux from the gas side to the wall includes well-known formulations for both the convective and the radiation mechanisms; for the latter process a zero penetration depth within the soot layer (i.e. heat absorption only at the soot surface) is assumed. In addition, the heat release due to soot burning is described as a source term within the considered soot sub-layer.

<P>

Results of the computations obtained so far show that the substrate wall temperature has a significant effect on the soot layer dynamics and thus on the wall heat flux to the combustion chamber wall. On the other hand a certain sensitivity of the results to the soot oxidation rate parameters and to the deposition process itself has been demonstrated.

<P>
Future computational work will include the thermal behavior of the laminar gas layer, while an appropriate experiment has to be designed for validation of the simulation results.
<P>
This project is supported by the National Energy Research Fund (NEFF).


<P>Contacts:<P>


K. Boulouchos, R. M&uuml;ller, A. Wolff


<P>
Electronic Contacts:
<P>
<A HREF="mailto: boulouchos@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch "> boulouchos@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch </A>
<P>
<A HREF="mailto: rene@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch "> rene@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch </A>
<P>
<A HREF="mailto: wolff@alfa1.it.pw.edu.pl "> wolff@alfa1.it.pw.edu.pl </A>
<P>

Index Terms:<P>

Heat Transfer<BR>
Soot<BR>
Numerical Analysis<BR>

<P>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch"><IMG
SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Public.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33%
BORDER=0  ALT="Home Page Public"></A>
<A HREF="http://troja.ethz.ch/Intern/Erste_Seite_Intern.html"><IMG  SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Home_Intern.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="Home Page Intern"></A>
<A HREF="mailto:www@lvv.iet.mavt.ethz.ch"><IMG
SRC="http://troja.ethz.ch/Seiten_Ausstattung/Administrator.GIF"
ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=33% BORDER=0  ALT="e-mail to administrator"></A>
<P>
<A
