<html>
<head>
<title>Australian Tourism - Facts and figures</title>
</head>
<body  BACKGROUND="/images/background.GIF">
<CENTER><H1><A NAME="xtocid187400">Australian Tourism - <BR> Key Facts and Figures </A></H1></CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=4>

<p>Tourism is one of Australia's fastest growing and economically 
important industries.<P>

<H2><A NAME="xtocid187401">Export earnings</A></H2>

<UL>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">In 1995-96 tourism 
generated export earnings of $14.1 billion, representing an increase of 16 per cent on 1994-95. <BR>

<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">Tourism export earnings accounted for 12.8 per cent of Australia's total export earnings and 63.1 per cent of services exports, compared with 12.6 per cent and 61.2 per cent respectively in 1994-95.<BR>

<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">By the year 2000, gross 
export earnings from tourism are estimated to rise to around $21 
billion.  By 2005 they are forcast to be $31 billion.<P>
</UL>

 <H2><A NAME="xtocid187402">Employment </A></H2>
<UL>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">

The tourism industry accounts for around 6.9 per cent of Australia's workforce.  In 1993-94, 
tourism directly employed about 535,600 people.

<BR>

<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">In the 10 years to 2003 the tourism industry is expected to generate directly around 160 000 new jobs. Two out of every three of these jobs are expected to be attributable to 
international tourism.<P>
</UL>

 <H2><A NAME="xtocid187403">Visitor numbers </A></H2>
<UL>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">
Nearly 2 million people visited Australia in the first six months of 1996 - an increase of 14 per cent over the same period last year. More than  3.7 million international visitors came in 1995, and in the year 2000, some 
6.3 million people are expected.<BR>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">Domestic tourism  
accounts for about 75 per cent of total tourism expenditure.  In 1995,  residents aged 14 and over undertook 59.7 million 
trips of at least one night's duration, spending a total of  251.8 million nights away from home.<p>
</UL>

 <H2><A NAME="xtocid187404">Major markets </A></H2>
<UL>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">Japan, Southeast Asia and 
 New Zealand are currently Australia's three largest tourism 
markets.  In 1995, 782 700 Japanese (720 100 in 1994) ,  566 000 people from South East Asia (487 800 in 1994) and 538 400 New Zealanders (480 400 in 1994) visited Australia.<BR>
<IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif">While Japan is expected 
to remain our single largest market, tourism from other Asian countries 
is becoming increasingly important.  Tourists from Asian countries other 
than Japan accounted for 28.5 per cent of all visitors in 1995 (26.3 per cent in 1994).<P>
</UL>

<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4>


