<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Organisational Structure of the Office of National Tourism</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="images/background.GIF">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>About the Office of National Tourism</H1>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4></P>

<UL>
<P>The Office of National Tourism in the Department of Industry, Science
and Tourism administers a young and dynamic policy program with a vital
role to play in developing and supporting one of Australia's most important
and rapidly expanding industries. </P>

<P>It is responsible for developing and implementing government tourism
policy, administering funding programs and organising Australia's participation
in international expositions.</P>

<P> The Office works with the tourism industry, other Federal Government
agencies, and State, Territory and local governments, to maximise the contribution
tourism makes to the well being of all Australians.</P>

<P> It does so by developing and implementing Federal Government policies
and programs which:<BR>
</P>

<P><img src="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  align=top> encourage
the development of tourism in Australia; <BR>
<img src="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  align=top> identify opportunities
in tourism; <BR>
<img src="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  align=top> reduce barriers
to industry development; and <BR>
<img src="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  align=top> provide information
to aid industry decision making. </P>

<P>These responsibilities are undertaken within three branches:</P>

<P> <IMG SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  ALIGN=TOP> the <B>Regional and
Environmental Tourism Branch</B> which undertakes activities to support
the development of a competitive, ecologically sustainable tourism industry
which draws on Australia's regional and cultural diversity and heritage;
<BR>
</P>

<P><IMG SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  ALIGN=TOP> the<B> International
Tourism and Industry Development Branch</B> which works to enhance the
international competitiveness of Australia's tourism industry and to strengthen
international relations in the tourism area; and <BR>
</P>

<P><IMG SRC="/icons/dots/blueball.gif"  ALIGN=TOP> the<B> Tourism Transport
and Business Development Branch</B> which works to develop an environment
in which tourism can most benefit the economy. </P>

<P><BR>
The Office of National Tourism is part of the Industry, Science and Tourism
Portfolio. Portfolio partners also includes the <B><A HREF="http://www.aussie.net.au">Australian
Tourist Commission</A></B> (a separate statutory authority responsible
for marketing Australian tourism internationally) and the <B>Bureau of
Tourism Research</B> (which is responsible for providing accurate, timely
and comprehensive statistics and analyses on tourism to aid industry and
government decision making).</P>

<P> </P>
</UL>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4><A HREF="http://tourism.gov.au/img/MAP/submenu.map?225,17">Search
Tourism | </A><A HREF="contact.html">Contacts</A> | <A HREF="welcome.html">Tourism
index</A></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><I>Last updated...8 October 1996</I> </P></CENTER>

</BODY>
