<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Backpacking</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"></P><H1>
Building up backpacking
</H1>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG BORDER=1 ALIGN=RIGHT vspace=5 hspace=10 SRC="motorbike.GIF"><CITE>
A new national strategy will guide the future development of the growing 
backpacker market. (Photo courtesy
 of the YHA.)
</CITE><P>The backpacker market is one of the most important sectors of 
Australia's tourism industry - and it's growing fast.
<P>In 1994, 217 000 backpackers travelled to Australia and, if recent 
projections prove correct, that number will more
 than double by the turn of the century and treble by the year 2004.
<P>That spells good news for the economy, because despite their 
reputation as being travellers on a shoestring budget,
 backpackers actually stay three times as long as other visitors and 
spend twice as much.
<P>They also like to travel off the beaten track, which helps spread the 
benefits of tourism to regional and rural Australia.
<P>To ensure Australia realises the full potential of this important 
sector of the industry, the Federal Government will
 release a new strategy in early October to guide the development and 
marketing of backpacker tourism.
<P>The <I>National Backpacker Tourism Strategy </I>
provides a plan of action for industry and governments to meet the goal 
of:
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>establishing Australia as the preferred destination for 
independent budget travellers by offering distinctive, world-class 
backpacker experiences provided by a competitive and viable 
industry.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The diversity of experiences to be had here, not the least being our 
unique natural environment and cultural
 heritage, already provide Australia with a strong competitive edge in 
attracting this type of traveller.
<P>But we also have some hurdles to overcome, including distance from 
major source countries, cost and availability of
 transport, and a lack of awareness about the range of activities and 
places worth exploring.
<P>The fragmented and 'small business' nature of the backpacker industry 
can also be an impediment to its growth. In
 particular, individual operators find it difficult to get finance and 
training to improve their facilities and services, and
 they sometimes have to struggle with local governments and communities 
to overcome negative, outdated images
 of the backpacker as an itinerant, scruffy wanderer.
<P>The approach outlined in the strategy seeks to overcome these 
impediments, while building on the strengths of the
 industry. Under the themes of access, diversity, cooperation and 
professionalism, it proposes actions to tackle a range
 of key issues including:
<UL>
<LI>marketing
<LI>accommodation
<LI>research
<LI>transport
<LI>safety
<LI>industry coordination
<LI>visas
<LI>employment
<LI>training
<LI>community awareness.
</UL>
␀<P>Funding will also be made available through the National Backpacker 
Program, administered by the Department of
 Tourism, to help establish the industry on a firmer footing so it can 
capture a greater share of the global backpacker
 market.
<P>The strategy was developed after extensive consultation with the 
tourism industry, State and Territory governments,
 and others with an interest in the issue. This process involved the 
formation of a Backpacker Consultative Forum,
 comprising industry and government representatives, which called for 
submissions to the strategy and identified
 the key issues to be addressed.
<P>

<H2>
Ratings released
</H2>


A new ratings guide for backpacker accommodation will also be released at 
the same time as the National
 Backpacker Strategy.
<P>The guide lists those establishments that have been assessed by the 
Australian Automobile Association (AAA) under a
 new voluntary backpacker accommodation ratings scheme, ranking them on a 
one to five 'backpack' system.
<P>A rating of one backpack indicates that the accommodation offers 
clean, simple and basic facilities, while a rating of
 five indicates a superior standard of facility. 
<P>The guide will help backpackers to make more informed choices about 
where they stay, provide a fair and
 independent guide to costs and standards of accommodation, and provide a 
marketing edge to those establishments
 that participate in the scheme.
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG BORDER=1 hspace=10 ALT="Photo of backpackers"ALIGN=RIGHT 
SRC="backpackers.GIF"><P>Copies of the <I>National Backpacker 
Strategy</I>
 and the <I>Backpacker Ratings Guide</I> are available from the 
information
 officer, Department of Tourism, (06) 279 7222 or 008 804 465 (toll 
free).
<P><CITE>
A new backpacker accommodation ratings guide will enable travellers to 
make informed choices about where
 they stay. (Photo courtesy of the YHA.)
</CITE>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
