<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tourism investment</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"></P><H1>
Tourism the focus of investment mission
</H1>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=189 HEIGHT=144 BORDER=1 hspace=10 ALT="Sunset" ALIGN=RIGHT 
SRC="sunset.GIF"><P>In recent years, Singaporeans have been astute 
investors of Australian hotel properties, recognising the opportunities
 that the strong growth of tourism in this country has offered.
<P>In August, a delegation of senior business people from Singapore and 
representatives from the Singapore Tourist
 Promotion Board (STPB) visited Australia on a 10-day 'tourism investment 
mission', reflecting the continued overseas
 investor confidence in the future of the Australian tourism industry.
<P>While past investment has tended to focus on existing hotels, this 
mission also looked at the potential for
 constructing new facilities in some of our key tourist destinations.
<P>Its itinerary, devised by the STPB, provided delegates with contrasts 
between the rainforest and reef of the tropical
 north to the red earth and spectacular sunsets of the west, taking in 
Brisbane, the Gold Coast, Cairns, Port Douglas,
 Darwin, Broome and Perth.
<P>The delegates were exposed to successful products and potential 
opportunities within both established and
 developing markets.
<P>The Department of Tourism also provided organisers and participants 
with extensive information on the Australian
 tourism industry and existing Singaporean investment in it.
<P>While impressed by the sheer size of the Australian continent and the 
range of opportunities it provides, the
 Singaporeans highlighted some of the associated barriers to be overcome, 
such as providing easy access to emerging
 destinations from international airports.
<P>From Australia's perspective, the timing of the investment mission is 
critical, given the combination of strong tourism
 growth (with international visitor numbers to Australia expected to 
double between now and the year 2000) and
 emerging shortages of accommodation in key destinations. 
<P>Annual occupancy rates across all standards of hotels and motels in 
Brisbane and Cairns are already approaching 80
 per cent, with the other destinations not far behind. During peak 
periods, supply is particularly short, especially in four
 and five star accommodation.
<P>The mission resulted from discussions in September 1994 between 
Australian Prime Minister, Mr Paul Keating, and
 Singaporean Prime Minister, Mr Goh Chok Tong, during which the two 
leaders agreed to seek closer tourism ties
 between our countries.
<P>The delegation was accompanied initially by Singapore's Minister of 
State for Trade and Industry, and for
 Communications, Mr Goh Chee Wee, reflecting the depth of Singaporean 
commitment to the mission.<P>

<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=236 HEIGHT=144 hspace=10 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left 
SRC="resort.GIF">On 4 August, Australian Minister for Tourism, Michael 
Lee, opened a session for mission participants at which they
 were briefed on the activities of the Department of Tourism, the 
Australian Tourist Commission and the Tourism
 Forecasting Council.
<P><CITE>
Delegates visited Broome's Cable Beach Club as part of their itinerary.
</CITE>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

