<HEAD>
<TITLE>Overseas visitors</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"></P><H1>
Overseas vistors - all you need to know
</H1>
<P>If you want to know all there is to know about the characteristics and 
behaviour of overseas tourists to our country, all
 you have to do is pick up the <I>1994 International Visitor Survey 
(IVS)</I>, released recently by the Bureau of Tourism
 Research (BTR).
<P>At the flick of a page you can find out where the tourists came from, 
why they came, where they went, how they
 went, how long they stayed for, where they stayed, what they did and how 
much they spent.
<P>At a glance, the survey found that:
<UL>
<LI3 361 700 international visitors came to Australia in 1994, a 12 per 
cent increase on the 1993 figure.<P>


<LI>International visitors spent an average of $1886 while they were 
here, compared with $1787 in 1993.<P>


<LI>People from the United Kingdom and Ireland spent the most number of 
nights here (20 per cent of the total),
 followed by New Zealanders (10 per cent of the total).<P>


<LI>While the Japanese accounted for 22 per cent of all visitors aged 15 
plus, they only stayed an average of eight
 nights.<P>


<LI>Sydney's attractions, including shopping, the Opera House, Darling 
Harbour and The Rocks, continued to
 draw the most tourist interest. Sydney also was the most popular region 
visited, followed by the Gold Coast,
 Melbourne, Cairns, Brisbane and Perth.<P>


<LI>The large majority of international visitors to Australia during 1994 
were satisfied with tourist facilities
 (including airport facilities, hotel and restaurant service, and the 
availability of tourist information).<P>


<LI>On the downside, 22 per cent of visitors were dissatisfied with the 
times when shops were open, and 15 per
 cent with the cost of goods in shops.
</UL>
␀<P>The IVS provides industry and government with a detailed insight into 
developments in Australian tourism, to help in
 industry planning and policy development.
<P>If you would like to order your copy of the IVS (at a cost of $65), 
contact Jenny Booth from the BTR on (06) 279
 7183 (phone), (06) 279 7298 (fax).
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR ALIGN=Center>
<B><P><IMG  Align=Left SRC="arrow.GIF"><!-- Link Tag -->
