<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bangs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"></P><H1>
Getting Bangs for your bucks 
</H1>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=222 hspace=10 BORDER=1 ALT="Tourist 
boat"ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="boat.GIF"><P>November will be an important month 
for ecotourism in Alice Springs this year, with a visit by two of the 
world's
 most successful and visionary ecotourism operators.
<P>Richard Bangs, a partner in Mountain Travel-Sobek, the world's largest 
adventure-travel company, and Stanley
 Selengut, feted as the travel industry's 'green guru', will be in town 
for a major forum on <I>
Innovative technology and design for tourism</I>. 
<P>The forum, to be held on 19 November, is being sponsored by the 
Federal Government under the National
 Ecotourism Program which is administered by the Department of Tourism. 
It will form part of a broader conference
 being run by the Ecotourism Association of Australia (EAA) from 18-23 
November.
<P>The forum will provide ecotourism operators with a wealth of 
information on how they can contribute to the
 sustainability of the industry by using energy and waste minimisation 
techniques, and environmentally friendly
 design. It will also give a round-up of the latest in information 
technology, and enable operators to share
 information, marketing initiatives and new ideas.
<P>New ideas are something that Richard Bangs is never short of. He has 
been in the adventure travel and ecotourism
 business since the mid-1970s when he combined his love of excitement and 
entrepreneurial flair by leading a rafting
 trip down the Awash, a little-known, crocodile and hippo-infested river 
in Africa.
<P>That was the beginning of Mountain Travel-Sobek and a mighty oak has 
now grown from that small acorn. The
 company is a paperless office, with extensive use of e-mail and 
Internet. Its promotional material is on 'Adventure
 Disk', a photo CD which previews the exotic sights and sounds of 
potential destinations through the use of stereo
 audio and high-resolution photography.
<P>Stanley Selengut has also taken nature-based travel to lofty new 
heights during his two decades in the industry.
 Some 18 years ago he developed the Maho Bay campground resort on St John 
in the Virgin Islands National Park.
 Here, 114 open-air tent cabins are connected by walkways above the 
forest floor so there is minimal disturbance to
 the natural surroundings.
<P>His next venture, the Harmony Resort built in the Virgin Islands in 
1991, went a step further in combining the latest ecological ideas, 
designs and technologies. With its recycled newspaper
 floorboards and crushed glass roof tiles, it is also the world's first 
luxury resort to operate exclusively on sun and wind
 power.
<P>Some of the best of Australia's ecotourism designers, consultants and 
operators will join these two American
 ecotourism pioneers to address the forum, including award-winning 
architect Ken Latona (of Cradle Mountain Huts
 and Freycinet Experience fame) and John Gertsakis (of the Royal 
Melbourne Institute of Technology's Centre for
 Design).
<P>For information on the forum contact Tanya Tear, Department of 
Tourism, on <NOBR>(06) 279 7234.</NOBR> For information on, or
 to register for, the broader conference contact Cherise Walmsley, EAA, 
on <NOBR>(07) 221 1811.</NOBR>
