<HEAD>
<TITLE>Accreditation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"><H1>
Accreditation on the agenda
</H1>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=327 HEIGHT=144 hspace=10 BORDER=1 ALT="Katherine 
Gorge"ALIGN=left SRC="katherine.GIF"><CITE>
The award-winning Nitmiluk Tours, a joint venture between the Jawoyn 
Association and Travel North, enables
 visitors to enjoy and learn about the cultural heritage of Katherine 
Gorge, NT, as well as its magnificent
 natural features.

</CITE><BR clear=all>
<P>A proposed National Ecotourism Accreditation Scheme (NEAS) will be the 
focus of a series of consultations soon to be held across Australia with 
a
 sample of operators.
<P>The industry-based scheme aims to establish Australia as a world 
leader, both in the delivery of tourism services
 and the way in which tour operators and their customers interact with 
the environment. The consultations will define national principles which 
those involved in the ecotourism industry must meet if they wish
 to be accredited, and will establish models of 'best practice'.
<P>The proposed scheme grew out of a report to the Department of Tourism 
by Manidis Roberts Consultants who
 investigated the feasibility of accreditation and, after extensive 
consultation with industry, government, land
 managers, trainers and consumers, recommended the form a national scheme 
should take.
 The initial proposal was made available for public comment, and as a 
result it was determined that the scheme be
 modified to meet concerns, particularly about cost and administration.
<P>The modification is being undertaken through a joint project, funded 
under the National Ecotourism Program,
 between the Tourism Council Australia (TCA), the Ecotourism Association 
of Australia (EEA) and the Victorian Tourism
 Operators Association (VTOA). While the TCA is managing the project, the 
EAA is providing its practical expertise in establishing national
 ecotourism standards for product delivery, service and training, taking 
into account regional differences and needs. These standards will be 
incorporated into a tourism accreditation model to be developed by VTOA. 
The new model
 will then be pilot-tested and fine-tuned through a cross-section of the 
industry to test both its acceptability and
 application to all the key stakeholders.
<P>The concept of an accreditation scheme has received wide support from 
ecotourism operators keen to distinguish
 their genuine product from others that claim the ecotourism tag. It aims 
not only to enhance the marketability of authentic operators, but also to 
give Australia a competitive edge in
 that visitors will come to know that if they choose an accredited 
operator for an ecotourism experience they will get
 a quality product.
<P>Ecotourism combines a growing interest in and awareness of the natural 
environment with a strong educational and
 interpretive component. Visitors to an area not only enjoy their 
experience but learn from it - and with minimal
 environmental impact.
<P>For further information contact Steven Holle, TCA, on <NOBR>(02) 360 
3500,</NOBR> Tony Charters, EEA, on <NOBR>(07) 229 7483,</NOBR> Peter
 Shelley, VTOA, <NOBR>(03) 965 2618</NOBR> or Paul Davies, Department of 
Tourism, on <NOBR>(06) 279 7126.</NOBR>
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
