<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>In brief</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="background.GIF" link="#42426f" vlink="#8e2323"</BODY> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG WIDTH=453 HEIGHT=18 ALT="Number 9, September 1995" 
SRC="issuenumbergold.GIF"></P><H1>
In brief
</H1>
<H2>
Tourism and Leisure Index celebrates first birthday
</H2>
<P>On 8 August 1994, the Tourism and Leisure Index was established to 
enable potential investors to track and assess
 the performance of tourism-related companies.
<P>It recently celebrated its first birthday with some very impressive 
results:
<UL>
<LI>The return on investment (including dividends and capital gains) 
across companies included in the index was
 14.8 per cent compared with a 7.4 per cent return from companies across 
the benchmark All Ordinaries Index (AOI).<P>


<LI>Of the 39 indexes, the Tourism and Leisure Index was the fourth best 
performing.<P>


<LI>In its first 12 months it grew from a nine-stock index capitalised at 
$3.6 billion to a fourteen-stock index
 capitalised at $5.7 billion.<P>


<LI>Of the $16.9 billion of equity raised on the Australian market last 
year, more than 8 per cent was directly
 attributable to the tourism and leisure sector.
</UL>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR ALIGN=Center><P>


␀<H2>
Fast-tracking visa applications
</H2>
<P>By the end of the year, tourists from at least 16 countries will be 
able to get Australian visas from selected travel
 agencies within 24 hours.
<P>Under the 'Agency Arrangement' scheme, visa applicants' details are 
collected by a travel agent or airline and
 transmitted electronically to the local Australian migration office for 
a quick decision, removing the need for people
 to go to an Australian mission to obtain their visa.
<P>The scheme was initially trialled, with great success, in Japan and 
was extended to the United Kingdom, Singapore,
 Malaysia, South Korea, Hong Kong and Slovenia in June. It is soon to be 
expanded again to North America, Italy,
 Greece, Germany, the Netherlands, Denmark, France, Indonesia and 
Tahiti.<P>


<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR ALIGN=Center>


<H2>
More than a rock and a croc
</H2>
<P>Australia must broaden its image as a tourist destination if it is to 
continue to compete with the emerging Asian
 markets for the international tourist dollar.
<P>That was the key message of an address to the 20th Ansett Travel and 
Transport Writers Seminar delivered by Federal
 Minister for Tourism, Michael Lee, on 27 August.
<P>Mr Lee said that, to many throughout the world, Australia was still 
perceived only in terms of beaches, the Rock and
 Crocodile Dundee. The reality is that Australia is an exciting, 
sophisticated and culturally diverse place that should be
 promoted in that light.
<P>To that end, the Australian Tourist Commission is investing $100 
million over the next three years on a new global
 television and print advertising campaign to sell Australia as a 
high-quality and diverse holiday destination. The series
 of ads will be seen in 10 countries by an estimated 500 million 
consumers.
<P>Mr Lee also stressed the importance of encouraging, but not 
exploiting, indigenous tourism ventures and managing
 the impact of tourism on ecologically sensitive areas such as national 
parks, world heritage areas and our coastlines.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><P>


<HR ALIGN=Center>


<H2>
New study of tourists with a disability
</H2>
<P>Tourism New South Wales and the Centre for Leisure and Tourism Studies 
at Sydney's University of Technology are
 currently investigating the tourism patterns of New South Wales 
residents with a physical disability.
<P>The study is focusing specifically on:
<UL>
<LI>patterns of domestic, overseas and day trips; <P>


<LI>travel requirements, reasons for travel and non-travel, and barriers 
encountered.
</UL>
␀<P>A questionnaire-based survey was sent to 8500 members of 10 
organisations representing people with a physical
 disability. To date, more than 2000 responses have been received and the 
preliminary analysis is expected to be
 completed by the end of September.
<P>The study aims to provide a quantitative base on which government and 
industry can make informed decisions
 about meeting the tourism needs of people with a physical disability.
<P>For further information contact Simon Darcy by phone: <NOBR>(02) 330 
5100,</NOBR> <NOBR>fax: (02) 330 5195</NOBR> or <NOBR>email:
 s.darcy@uts.edu.au.</NOBR><P>


