<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Talking Tourism - Overseas visitors to spend over $14B in 
2003</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 ALIGN=CENTRE SRC="TalkingTourismLogo.GIF"><P>

<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
 A QUARTERLY NEWSLETTER FROM THE
<BR>COMMONWEALTH DEPARTMENT OF TOURISM </H2>
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="14b.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
<EM>In the year 2003, overseas visitors to Australia will spend over $14 
billion, excluding expenditure on international air fares. Most of these 
tourists (some 6 out of 10) will be from Asia, with a growing number from 
emerging markets such as Indonesia, Taiwan and Korea.</EM>
<P>
The commercial accommodation sector will be a big winner, with the number 
of international visitor nights spent in hotels, motels and guest houses 
increasing from 15 million in 1993 to 42 million in 2003. 
<P>
These predictions are made in <I>Forecast </I>magazine, the second report 
of the Tourism Forecasting Council (TFC), released in April. 
<P>
The TFC is the peak advisory body to government and industry on future 
movements within the various sectors of Australia's tourism industry - 
its sophisticated forecasts providing vital information for sound 
investment and policy decision making.
<P>
The April issue of <I>Forecast </I>contains its most recent predictions, 
giving detailed information on visitor arrivals, resident departures, 
international visitor nights and expenditure, and the number of nights 
spent by international visitors in hotels, motels and guest houses. It 
also discusses the latest use of 'tourism leading indicators' in 
determining  short-term arrivals trends.<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>

<I>Photo courtesy of the ATC</I>
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="PeoplePicture.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT ><BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>

<B>SOME OF THE KEY FORECASTS ARE:</B> 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Expenditure by international tourists in Australia to grow at about 
9 per cent a year - from around $6 billion in 1993 to over $14 billion in 
2003. <P>
<LI> Amount of money spent directly in Australia by international 
visitors to increase from $5.4 billion in 1993 to over $12 billion in 
2003 (in 1993 $) - an average annual growth rate of 8.5 per cent.<P>
<LI> The total number of nights spent in Australia by international 
visitors to grow from 69 million in 1993 to 144 million in 2003 - an 
average annual growth rate of 8 per cent.<P>
<LI> Amount of money spent on pre-paid travel packages to increase from 
$700 million in 1993 to around $2.4 billion in 2003 - an average annual 
growth rate of 12.7 per cent. <P>
<LI> Based on current data, the projected increase in international 
visitor nights in hotels, motels and guest houses from 15 million in 1993 
to 42 million in 2003 is expected to create demand for an additional 15 
million <I>room nights</I> in the year 2003 - more than half for visitors 
from Asian countries other than Japan.<P>
<LI> Average length of stay of international visitors to decline, due 
largely to the increase in number of short-staying holiday makers from 
Asian countries other than Japan, but average expenditure per day per 
person to continue to rise.
</UL>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>
