<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Funding to ensure popular attractions aren't 'Loved to 
Death'
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Lovedtodeath.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT>
Victoria's Hanging Rock, Western Australia's Wave Rock, Kangaroo Island's 
Seal Bay, and Tasmania's Cradle Mountain are just four of 14 popular, 
natural attractions that are to receive Federal Government funding to 
protect them for the enjoyment of future generations.<P>
More than $660 000 in grants has been awarded under the Government's 
Sites of National Tourism Significance (SONTS) program to ensure that 
these natural icons are protected and aren't 'loved to death' by 
tourists.<P>

In announcing the grants, the Federal Minister for Tourism, Michael Lee, 
said the funding would be used to ensure that the special qualities that 
make these sites so attractive to Australians and overseas visitors  
alike are retained for future generations of visitors.<P>

Mr Lee said that responsible tourism development means attracting the 
maximum number of visitors to Australia while also protecting our unique 
and valuable natural drawcards.<P>

"This can be a very delicate balancing act given the growing importance 
of tourism to local economies, particularly in creating jobs," Mr Lee 
said.<P>

SONTS funding is provided to natural sites of national tourism 
significance to minimise the environmental impact of tourism, increase 
understanding of tourism management in sensitive areas and enhance 
visitor appreciation of the environmental value of these natural tourist 
icons.<P>

The SONTS grants, which were announced in May, come under the second 
round of funding offered under the Government's three-year, $2 million 
SONTS program.<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>

<P>
The following projects are being funded this financial year:
<UL>
<LI>Coastal Walk, Royal National Park, NSW ($81 150)
<LI>Viewing Platform, Kiama Blowhole Point, NSW  ($43 460)
<LI>Interpretive Trail at Hanging Rock, Vic.($22 500)
<LI>Alpine Walking Track, Victoria ($43 600)
<LI>Restoration of Kersop's Peak Track, Wilson's Promontory, Vic. ($45 
925)
<LI>Split Rock Interpretive Centre, Qld  ($80 000) 
<LI>Lava Caves, Undara Volcanic National Park, Qld ($80 000)
<LI>Valley of the Giants, Walpole-Nornalup National Park, WA  ($56 800)
<LI>Wave Rock Site Improvements, WA  ($59 900)
<LI>Seal Bay Visitor Interpretive Centre, SA  ($20 000)
<LI>Upgrade of the Overland Track, Cradle Mountain, Tas. ($60 000)
<LI>Devils Mountain Conservation Reserve, NT ($28 000)
<LI>Kings Canyon Climb, Watarrka National Park, NT ($30 000)
<LI>Ormiston Gorge, West MacDonnell National Park, NT ($10 000)
</UL>
Applications for funding in 1995-96 will be called for early in the new 
financial year.  
<ADDRESS>For further information, contact Peter Sesterka, Environment 
Management, on (06) 279 7146.</ADDRESS> 
This issue of <I>Talking Tourism</I> also contains details of funding 
under other grants programs.<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
