<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Royal National Park to receive $81 150
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="SONTSgrant.GIF"  ALIGN=LEFT> The devastating bushfires of 
January 1994 had a severe effect on Australia's oldest national park, the 
Royal National Park in Sydney, damaging 95 per cent of the 15 000 
hectares of vegetation.<P>

Ironically, the terrible fires have offered a unique opportunity to act 
to improve some of the park's infrastructure. 
<P>
The spectacular and immensely popular 26-kilometre Coast Walk had been in 
need of upgrading due to soil erosion caused by heavy use and unstable 
sandy surfaces even before the fires. With the coastal heath now burnt 
back, an opportunity exists to survey and reconstruct the track along 
better planned and more environmentally sensitive routes. 
<P>
Each year 1.8 million people visit the park and more than 30 000 walk the 
track.  The number of visitors is likely to rise dramatically over the 
next few years with increased tourism to Australia and the 
fast-approaching Sydney 2000 Olympics. 
<P>
To help protect the park from the impact of growing numbers of tourists, 
especially now that burnt out areas are beginning to regenerate, an $81 
150 grant from the Federal Government's SONTS program has been awarded to 
the park. 
<P>
The grant will be used to restore the section of the Coast Walk from 
Jibbon Beach to Marley. 
<P>
In announcing the grant, Federal Minister for Tourism, Mr Michael Lee, 
said there was an urgent need to ensure we could meet the needs of 
tourists without putting at risk the regeneration of this fragile 
environment. 
<P>
The SONTS grant will help to ensure that tourists won't be prevented from 
exploring the park's magnificent and diverse scenery. 
<P>
"SONTS is designed to help balance competing priorities by providing 
funding to enhance people's appreciation of our great natural assets 
while at the same time limiting the environmental impact of tourism," 
said Mr Lee. 
<P>
The  New South Wales National Parks and Wildlife Service received the 
grant on behalf of the park.   
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
