<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Encouraging Ecotourism
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="EncouragingEcotourism.GIF" ALIGN=MIDDLE>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">
Australia's growing ecotourism industry has received a healthy injection 
of funds with the recent announcement of nearly $2 million in Federal 
Government grants. 
<P>
The $1.4 million offered under the National Ecotourism Program (NEP) and 
$0.43 million offered under the third round of the Forest Ecotourism 
Program (FEP) will go to 52 projects which aim to increase opportunities 
for tourists to experience and learn about our natural environment while 
making a major contribution to environmental conservation and management. 

<P>
Announcing the grants on World Environment Day, Federal Minister for 
Tourism, Michael Lee, said that Australia, with its spectacular natural 
features, remarkable flora and fauna, and unique cultural heritage, had 
the potential to become one of the world's most favoured ecotourism 
destinations. 
<P>
"Our success depends, however, on how well we manage, conserve and 
present our valuable ecotourism resources," he said. 
<P>
"Projects such as those being funded will help to enhance our reputation 
as a world leader in the sensitive and sustainable development of 
ecotourism." 
<P>
The NEP funding is for 32 infrastructure, planning or research projects 
across all States and Territories. They range from research into the 
effects of human activity on our fauna and flora, including the impact on 
dolphins of people swimming nearby, to the use of new energy-efficient 
technology at Broome's Bird Observatory. 
<P>
The FEP funding is for 20 projects which will help people to explore and 
better understand our magnificent forest areas while at the same time 
protecting the environmental values that draw people to the forests. 
<P>
<B><I>"Our success depends, however, on how well we manage, conserve and 
present our valuable ecotourism resources." </I></B>
<P>
The projects cover a range of forest types - from Queensland's tropical 
rainforests to the alpine woodlands of Victoria's high country - and 
include walking tracks to help people appreciate local flora, fauna and 
indigenous culture, a solar-powered FM radio forest information service 
and a multi-media geographic information system for planning  
and promoting forest ecotourism.
<P>
Applications for grants under the 1995-96 round of funding will be called 
for in August. For further information on the NEP, please call Ken Morgan 
Nature Based and Indigenous Tourism, (06) 279 7149. For further 
information on FEP please call Mary Jinman, Environment Management (06) 
279 7147. 
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Photoofbus.GIF" ><P>
<I>A tour vehicle next to existing basic amenities at the Angatja Atal 
Tourist Camp, Mann Ranges, South Australia. The facilities will be 
upgraded using minimal construction techniques and natural materials.</I>

<P>

<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Photoofshack.GIF" ><P>
<I>The Pitjantjatjara Council received a NEP grant to construct a minimal 
impact campsite at the Angatja Atal Tourist Camp. The Wiltja, used for 
sleeping and cooking, has been constructed by adapting a traditional 
Pitjantjatjara design.</I><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
