<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Understanding Tourism Labour Markets
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20  SRC="LobourMarkets.GIF"><P>
The tourism industry has good potential for continued strong employment 
growth and is 'ripe' for enterprise bargaining.  This was one of the 
conclusions at a workshop on tourism labour markets and employment held 
in Melbourne on 31 May-1 June.
<P>
Organised by the Department of Tourism and the Industry Commission, the 
workshop attracted representatives from key industry organisations, 
unions, government departments, hotel operators, and labour market 
economists and researchers. 
<P>
The forum featured panel-style discussions following each formal 
presentation - ensuring stimulating and thought provoking debate. A key 
feature was the international perspective on 'tourism related employment 
and the unemployed' brought to the discussions by Dr Marilyn Mohan from 
Canada's Mana Research Limited. 
<P>
Some of the key issues raised at the workshop were that: 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Tourism's share of total Australian employment has increased in 
recent years. 
<LI> Inbound tourism's share of total employment is expected to double 
over the next decade. 
<LI> Tourism employment is largely represented by young, female and 
casual workers. 
<LI> Tourism can be an effective job generator, creating jobs which are 
suited to a high proportion of job seekers. 
<LI> Measuring the employment impact of tourism growth requires detailed 
information about labour market conditions and links between industries. 

<LI> The characteristics of the tourism labour market, the flexibility 
available to deploy labour and overall labour market conditions have 
enabled Australia's tourism industry to adjust to increased demand 
without major difficulties. 
<LI> The challenge for enterprise bargaining in the tourism industry is 
to improve efficiency and skills in the workplace by spreading bargaining 
to the large number of small to medium sized operators. 
<LI> For tourism to realise its full potential we must have an 
appropriately trained workforce to meet the industry's possible labour 
requirements for the next century.
</UL> 
<P>
It was also noted that the development of a Tourism Satellite Account (a 
statistical means of linking tourism to the national accounts)  in 
Australia would provide a statistical framework to measure the 
contribution tourism makes to the economy and would greatly assist in 
formulating policies that affect the industry. 
<P>
 <ADDRESS>For further information on any of the presentations given at 
the workshop, contactKylie Hill, Economic Policy Branch, on (06) 279 
7231.</ADDRESS> 
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>

<H3>NEW REPORT ON TOURISM LABOUR MARKETS</H3>
<P>
Tourism is a relatively labour intensive industry, and employment in 
tourism-related industries has experienced rapid growth over the past 
decade. 
<P>
The industry is creating jobs across a range of skill levels and has the 
capacity to provide jobs for many groups vulnerable to long-term 
unemployment - groups such as the young, the unskilled and people from 
different cultural backgrounds. Tourism is also helping to diversify the 
employment base of regional economies. 
<P>
<I>Photo courtesy of the ATC</I>
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Photoofpeople.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT><P>
Given the future potential of the industry for job creation, the 
department commissioned the Western Australian Labour Market Research 
Centre to examine the operation of the tourism labour market to gain a 
better understanding of the nature of employment in the industry. 
<P>
The outcomes of that study are now available in a new publication, <I>How 
Tourism Labour Markets Work.</I> 
<P>
The report, the first in a new series of research papers to be published 
by the Department of Tourism, uses statistical analysis and case study 
research to examine the structure of employment in the industry and how 
it adjusts to fluctuations in demand. 
<P>
It looks at issues such as staff recruitment and turnover, employee 
earnings and mobility, the educational levels of staff, training 
arrangements and the development of career paths. 
<P>
The report is important reading for tourism operators, and private and 
public sector agencies involved in the future development of the tourism 
industry's workforce. 
<P>
<ADDRESS>Copies are available from the department's information officer 
on (06) 279 7162 or 008 804 465.</ADDRESS><P>


<I>Caption: Tourism labour markets and employment were the subject of a 
joint Department of Tourism/Industry Commission workshop.</I><P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
