<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - In Brief
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="InBrief.GIF" ALIGN=MIDDLE><P>
<H3>SPECIAL AWARD FOR NEW TOURIST INFO CENTRE</H3>
<P>
The Snowy River Shire Council has received a $50 000 Tourism Minister's 
'special award' for the use of innovative energy-conserving technology 
and recycled products in the construction of the new Jindabyne Tourist 
Information Centre. 
<P>
It is the first time such an award has been made. 
<P>
Plans for the new centre include the use of a range of recycled products 
both inside and outside the building, including recycled timber floor and 
wall panelling, second hand bricks for paving, and recycled timber and 
plastics in the landscaping. 
<P>
Energy conservation options being considered include geothermal heating 
and cooling systems, double glazing, controlled power usage and automated 
internal lighting systems. 
<P>
When finished, the building will be a showcase for visitor centres 
throughout Australia, and as the gateway to the Snowy Mountains, will 
help pave the way for further innovation in recycled products and energy 
conservation techniques in Australian building design. 
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>

<H3>TOURISM PARTNERS '95 </H3>
<P>
The arts, culture and natural beauty  - Australia is incredibly rich in 
all, as we know and a growing number of international tourists are 
finding out. 
<P>
Just what we can offer the increasingly sophisticated tourist will be on 
display at the first Tourism Partners expo and workshops being held in 
Sydney from 20-21 July. 
<P>
Set to become an annual event on the tourism industry's calendar, Tourism 
Partners  is all about building links and fostering partnerships between 
people already running, or thinking of setting up, tourist ventures in 
each of these sectors of the industry. 
<P>
A large selection of uniquely Australian tourism attractions will be 
represented, with participants enjoying the opportunity to make valuable 
contacts and gain some practical ideas on how to develop and establish 
creative, new tourist enterprises. 
<P>
The Department of Tourism is supporting this initiative through its 
involvement with the Department of Communications and the Arts in 
implementing the Federal Government's Cultural Tourism Program. 
<P>
Tourism Partners '95 promises to be an information-rich experience - be 
there to make sure you share the wealth.   
<P>
When: 20-21 July 1995 
<P>
Where: Richmond Campus, <BR> 
University of Western Sydney 
<P>
<ADDRESS>Further information: Rohan Boehm<BR> 
Event Manager - Phone: (045) 70 1690 Fax: (045) 70 1686 </ADDRESS>
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>

<H3>RURAL TOURISM -- ALL YOU NEED TO KNOW!</H3> 
<P>
Cross Country, one of Australia's leading television shows on rural 
issues, is working with the Department of Tourism to produce a series of 
segments on rural tourism. The series will go to air later this year. 
<P>
As part of the project, an information kit is also being developed for 
individuals and groups involved in or who are interested in becoming 
involved in, the business of tourism. 
<P>
The kit will feature a video compilation of the TV segments and a booklet 
highlighting a range of rural tourism ideas, case studies of successful 
rural tourism and key information to `get started' at business and 
community levels. 
<P>
The kit will address issues such as product development, business 
planning, marketing, cooperation between industries, infrastructure - 
essential information for successful tourism involvement. 
<P>
The information kit will be available towards the end of the year at a 
cost of around $20.00. 
<P>
If you would like to receive further information on the kit, please 
register your interest with the <ADDRESS>Australian Government Publishing 
Service, PO Box 84, Canberra ACT 2601, or phone 008 020 049.</ADDRESS> 
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>

<H3>RURAL TOURISM SCHOLARSHIP ON OFFER</H3> 
<P>
Applications are invited from highly motivated people interested in 
gaining a Rural Tourism Scholarship under the Australian Rural Leadership 
Program (ARLP). 
<P>
The ARLP is designed for people who have established themselves as 
community leaders or leaders of specific industries in rural areas, and 
have the capacity and commitment to become involved in broader, 
high-level regional development work. 
<P>
It aims to help rural communities to: 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> develop sustainable, internationally competitive and profitable 
rural industries; 
<LI> build links and establish strategic alliances within and across 
industry sectors; 
<LI> understand the tactics, arguments and values of competing interest 
groups; 
<LI> identify the issues competing for industry, community and government 
support;
<LI> deal confidently with industry, government and community leaders, 
both in Australia and overseas; and 
<LI> participate in shaping national policies.
</UL> 
<P>
The successful applicant will participate in a two-year, part-time course 
designed to develop leadership skills, examine key national and 
international issues, and establish contact with a wide range of 
government, industry and community leaders. She or he will join about 30 
other scholarship holders from a wide range of rural industries. 
<P>
If you are active in the tourism industry, are aged between 30 and 45 
years, have the potential, prospects and drive to be a leader, and are 
committed to developing and sharing a vision for rural Australia this 
could be the perfect opportunity for you. 
<P>
For further information contact: 
<P>
<ADDRESS>Australian Rural Leadership Foundation Limited  <BR>
PO Box 4591 <BR>
Kingston ACT 2604 <BR>
Phone: (06) 281 0680 <BR> 
Fax: (06) 285 4676 </ADDRESS>
<P>
