<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Funding for Rural Tourism
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG  BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Funding.GIF">
<H2>Rural Tourism Program</H2> 
<P>
Rural and regional areas of Australia can offer both domestic and 
international tourists an unlimited range of experiences. But with only 
one-third of overseas visitors currently venturing beyond the big cities 
and major gateways, country areas have yet to realise the full potential 
of tourism.
<P>
The Federal Government's four-year, $4 million, Rural Tourism Program 
(RTP) aims to address this issue by funding innovative projects to help 
rural Australia gain a greater share of the tourist dollar. Discretionary 
grants have so far been targeted at projects which involve market 
analysis, raising industry standards, education and training, and 
product/infrastructure development.
<P>
An important aspect of the RTP is that the approach taken in these 
individual projects can be adapted for use right across the country - 
they are examples to others of what can be achieved with a little 
foresight, imagination and commitment.
<P>
Six major projects have received $610 000 under the RTP in 1994-95:
<P>
$145 000 for an agricultural interpretation centre at the University of 
Adelaide's Roseworthy Campus (District Council of Light).
<P>
$128 400 for a tourist trail which will link the quality wine and food 
producing areas around Albury - Wodonga with the heritage and scenery of 
the Victorian high country (Tourism Albury Wodonga).
<P>
$63 000 for displays and signs along Tasmania's Agricultural Trail 
(Wilderness Gateway Tourism Association).
<P>
$40 000 to employ a facilitator to begin implementing Cape York 
Peninsula's tourism strategy (Cape York Peninsula Development Authority).

<P>
$23 000 for signs to direct tourists to the many attractions of the 
south-east Gulf of Carpentaria (Gulf Local Authorities Development 
Association).
<P>
$12 500 to extend the trial of an accreditation scheme for farm stays and 
country retreat accommodation in NSW, SA and Tasmania (Victorian Tourism 
Operators Association).
<P>
Research by the Bureau of Tourism Research into the motivation and 
experiences of international visitors who have travelled in country 
Australia is also being funded this year.
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>

<H2>Regional Tourism Development Program</H2> 
<P>
Like the RTP, the Regional Tourism Development Program (RTDP) is designed 
to help spread the economic and social benefits of tourism throughout 
rural and regional Australia.
<P>
This year, the Government delivered $6.2 million in funding under the 
highly competitive program for 54 projects which will help improve the 
capacity of regional Australia to attract both domestic and international 
tourists.
<P>
In New South Wales, 15 projects received $1.2 million in funding, ranging 
from initiatives to market the State's mining and industrial heritage as 
a tourist drawcard, to the development of strategies to guide the future 
growth of tourism in specific regions.
<P>
Eight Victorian projects received a total of $1.7 million, with most of 
the funding to be used to build modern visitor information and 
interpretive centres to introduce travellers to the scenic, historic and 
cultural wealth of the Geelong Sunraysia, Echuca-Moama and Upper Yarra 
regions.
<P>
The West attracted $1 million, including a $400 000 grant for the 
construction of a Tourism Information Gateway - a one-stop shop for 
visitors and investors alike - in Kununurra. 
<P>
A $600 000 package went to Queensland for seven projects, five of which 
will involve the development of comprehensive regional tourism plans, 
while South Australia received 
<P>
$800 000 for seven projects including new visitor information centres for 
the McLaren Vale and Riverland regions and for Kangaroo Island.
<P>
In Tasmania, seven projects received a total of $500 000 in funding, 
including a $100 000 grant to restore Australia's first hydro-electric 
power station in Cataract Gorge as a tourist drawcard.
<P>
The Northern Territory attracted $200 000 in funding for two projects - a 
tourist complex at Tennant Creek's historic 'Battery Hill' gold stamp 
site and a tourism development plan for the region covering Gove, 
Nhulunby and Groote Eylandt.
<P>
The Federal Minister for Tourism, Michael Lee, said the projects 
reflected the scale and diversity of the largely untapped tourism product 
in areas outside of the major metropolitan centres.  
<P>
Applications for RTDP grants under the 1995-96 round of funding will be 
sought in early July. <ADDRESS>For further information please call Jane 
Bailey, Regional Development, (06) 279 7192.</ADDRESS>
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>
<H2>Rural Tourism? - The Sky's the Limit!</H2>
<P>
`Passport to the Stars', a new enterprise which markets our astronomical 
achievements as a major new tourist attraction, is proof that 'the sky's 
the limit' for tourism in rural Australia.
<P>
The special passport will provide people travelling the Newell Highway 
with an informative guide to 10 major optical and radio telescope 
observatories and space tracking stations in NSW and the ACT. It will 
also highlight other tourist attractions in the nearby communities of 
Cowra, Parkes, Dubbo, Gilgandra, Coonabarabran, Canberra and Narrabri.
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Satelite.GIF" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P>
As they travel along the 'astro highway', visitors will have their 
passports stamped as a unique reminder of their experiences.  
<P>
Launching the passport in Parkes recently, Federal Parliamentary 
Secretary Paul Elliott said it was a great example of what could be 
achieved when tourism opportunities were developed, packaged and marketed 
with flair and creativity. 
<P>
"With the project being funded through a $46 000 RTP grant, it also 
demonstrates the effectiveness of that program in encouraging innovation 
in rural tourism," Mr Elliott said.

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>
