<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Access for all
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Access.GIF">
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG  BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Laughting.GIF"><BR>
<I>
Photo courtesy of the Wheel Resort, Byron Bay
</I><P>

<B><I>Ensuring tourism is accessible to all people makes sound business 
sense. </I></B>

<P>One in every six Australians has some form of disability, ranging from 
asthma through to a severe physical or intellectual disability, and with 
Australia's population ageing rapidly this figure is expected to reach 
one in five within the next decade. (1993 ABS Survey of Disability, 
Ageing and Carers).
<P>
People who have a disability have the same aspirations and expectations 
of life as those who don't - including the desire to experience the 
excitement and enjoyment that travel can bring. <P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<H2><I>But there is a problem.</I></H2>
<P>
<STRONG>
For a large group of people whose mobility, or sight, or 
hearing is impaired, the hurdles and frustrations they 
experience as a tourist are at times so daunting that they 
rule out many travel options.
</STRONG><P>

These obstacles can range from lack of information, to difficulties with 
transport.  This can mean that someone simply cannot gain access to an 
attraction, or that they face additional, often hefty, expenses to get 
there in the first place.
<P>
Whatever the hurdle, the result is the same - a lost opportunity to enjoy 
the things that most of us take for granted and a lost opportunity for 
Australia's tourism industry to tap into a large and growing 
international and domestic travel market.
<P>
While some enterprising individuals and organisations within the tourism 
industry are already improving facilities for people with a disability, 
we have a long way to go. 
<P>
Many rightly see the issue of increasing access for people with a 
disability in terms of it being a social and legislative responsibility 
with the introduction of the <I>Disability Discrimination Act 1992</I>.
<P>
But it also makes good business sense to better cater for, and actively 
market to, a significantly large group of consumers - with the Sydney 
2000 Olympics and the Paralympics on the horizon, there are sound 
economic reasons to do so.
<P>
While much of the work to remove the barriers can only be done at 
government level, through changes to major infrastructure for example, 
with a little forethought much can also be done within the industry to 
create a more accessible environment for all consumers.
<P>
If you are already in the business of tourism, ask yourself the following 
questions to make a very basic assessment of how accessible your facility 
or enterprise is. If you are thinking of getting into the business -- 
whether it be through designing a new hotel or operating a guided tour -- 
examine its design to ensure you don't inadvertently exclude a large part 
of the population and therefore limit your business potential.
<P>
If you would like further information or checklists on how to assess and 
modify your premises or facility, and which Australian standards to 
follow, contact ACROD (Australia's peak council of disability services) 
on (06) 282 4333 (national office) or its State Divisional offices in 
each capital city.
<P>
Independent Living Centres in each State and Territory can also advise on 
equipment or fittings that are suitable for people with a disability, and 
local consumer organisations for people with a disability can also help 
you to determine how needs can be better met.
<P>
Future issues of <I>Talking Tourism</I> will feature case studies on what 
some organisations are already doing to better cater to the needs of 
these consumers.
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<H2><I>How Accessible Is Your Facility?</I></H2>

<I>For someone who is blind or has limited vision ...</I>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Is it easy to find the way?
<LI> Are there any hazards on the route, such as dangerous  steps?
<LI> Is information available in an audio format? Would raised tactile 
buttons be helpful? 
<LI> Are there ways to help people better appreciate this art, this 
entertainment or this scenery?
</UL>

<P>
<!-- List Tag -->

<I>For a person with impaired hearing ...</I>
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Are any announcements clear? Is the public address system set up for 
people with hearing aids?
<LI> Is the information available in written format?
<LI> Is technology, or other assistance available to enable this person 
to make a phone booking?
</UL>
<P>
<I>For a person who uses a wheelchair ...</I>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Are there wide car parks close by?
<LI> Are walkway gradients gentle, and the paths smooth?
<LI> Is there room to manoeuvre?
<LI> Are the walkways and entrances level, or ramped?
<LI> Are displays, phones, lift buttons, etc. all within easy reach?
<LI> Are the toilets accessible?
</UL>
<P>
<I>For a person who can walk, but only with difficulty ...</I>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Are there handrails on the steps?
<LI> Is there seating so people can rest?
<LI> Is there shelter from the weather?
</UL>
<P>
<I>For a person with an intellectual disability ...</I>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> Are the signs and explanations clear and easy to understand?
<LI> Is it easy to find your way around?
<LI> Is assistance available?
</UL>
<P>
</I><IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Skier.GIF"><BR>
<I>
Photo courtesy of NICAN
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>
<!-- Link Tag -->
