<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - Budget Good News for Tourism Operators
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<IMG BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Budget.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT>

<P>
<B>Pre-Budget fears about the introduction of a bed tax and a significant 
reduction in funding to the Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) were laid 
to rest on 9 May when the Federal Government brought down its 1995-96 
Budget.</B> 
<P>
The bed tax proposal was rejected and ATC funding was maintained in a 
Federal Budget aimed at increasing business investment by 13 per cent, 
encouraging employment growth by 3 per cent during 1995-96, keeping 
interest rates and inflation down and boosting national savings. 
<P>
Accelerated development of Sydney West Airport, continued funding for 
Department of Tourism programs and ongoing support for the research and 
statistical initiatives of the Bureau of Tourism Research and the Tourism 
Forecasting Council were features of a Budget that encourages investment 
in growth industries such as tourism. 
<P>
In preparation for the Sydney 2000 Olympics, $762 million was allocated 
to construct international and domestic airport facilities at Sydney 
West, including road links to Sydney City, and to identify a rail 
corridor.  
<P>
Costs for development of Sydney West will be recouped from a special 
charge on Sydney airport users equivalent to approximately $1.70 per 
passenger. 
<P>
Key tourism highlights of the Budget were the continued funding for 
ongoing programs: 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> $5.2 million for the Regional Tourism Development Program; 
<LI> $3.4 million for the National Ecotourism Program and the Forest 
Ecotourism Program; 
<LI> $0.7 million for the Sites of National Tourism Significance Program; 
and 
<LI> $2.6 million to stimulate the development of special interest 
tourism markets including rural tourism, the backpacker market and cruise 
shipping.
</UL> 
<P>

These programs are encouraging regional tourism development, expanding 
ecotourism and helping to develop niche markets. 
<P>
Support for the Tourism Forecasting Council and the Bureau of Tourism 
Research will also continue, with $1.3 million provided to the BTR for 
the ongoing development of the tourism industry's statistical and 
research base. 
<P>
The ATC will receive a record $80 million to continue its overseas 
marketing activities.  When supplemented by industry contributions, the 
ATC's total budget expenditure is expected to be some $111 million. 
<P>
The Budget also provides funds to give single service tourism operators 
access to the Export Market Development Grants Scheme.  Operators will be 
able to claim eligible promotional expenditure incurred in 1994-95. 
<P>
Changes to visitor entry requirements should facilitate easier entry for 
business travellers. To streamline and simplify entry procedures, 
temporary resident categories for business people have been reduced to a 
single visa class.   
<P>
In addition, periods of stay for visa applicants have been redesigned to 
include: 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> a one-month category with no application fee; 
<LI> a three-month, multiple entry category valid for five years or the 
life of a passport (whichever is greater), with an application fee of 
$35; and  
<LI> a greater than three-month category, with the existing application 
fee of $140 (due to rise by $5 on 1 July 1995 owing to indexation). 
</UL>
<P>
To improve the nation's roadways, the Budget allocated $840 million for 
construction and maintenance of the national highway system. 
<P>
The Budget also included a number of initiatives that will help to 
conserve and manage environmental resources important to Australians and 
visitors: 
<P>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> an additional $14 million for the Great Barrier Marine Park 
Authority for planning and environmental management; 
<LI> increased funding of $6 million for the National Protected Areas 
Program, which includes the management of national parks; 
<LI> $53 million to improve management of Australia's coastline; 
<LI> $53 million to implement the National Forest Policy Statement; and  

<LI> an additional $5 million for conservation and management of 
Australia's wetlands. </UL><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
