<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Talking Tourism - On the Shelf
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Factsheets.GIF"
><H2>
<I>Factsheets</I>
</H2>
<P>
The department has recently revised and updated its series of free 
'factsheets' which provide information on 24 topics ranging from 
ecotourism to international expositions. 
<P>
<ADDRESS>Call the information officer on (06) 279 7162 or 008 804 465 
(toll free)</ADDRESS> and ask for a publications order form to select 
those of interest to you.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>
<P>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Rural.GIF"><P>
<H2><I>Rural Travellers to Australia</I></H2>
<P>
The Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) has just released, <I>Rural 
Travellers to Australia</I>, a 'must-read' for anyone involved in rural 
tourism.
<P>
Funded by the department and developed as a marketing tool, this valuable 
report profiles potential international rural travellers in terms of 
their tourism needs, holiday activities, perceptions of Australia, 
accommodation preferences, anticipated length of stay, travel 
arrangements, media usage and travel experience.
<P>
A companion to the ATC's <I>International Tourism Marketing Manual</I>, 
it provides essential information and advice on trends in international 
tourism, marketing your product, the role of the ATC and useful contacts.

<P>
<ADDRESS>Copies are available free-of-charge from the ATC on (02) 360 
1111.</ADDRESS>
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>

<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="International.GIF"><P>
<H2><I>Leading Indicators of Australian Visitor Arrivals (BTR Occasional 
Paper No. 19)</I></H2>
<P>

A reliable view of the short-term prospects for inbound visitor numbers 
is essential for tourism business and policy decisions.
<P>
In this report, 'leading indicators' have been identified which give 
advance warning of movements about the long-term trend in visitor 
arrivals, from one to two years ahead of the actual movement. These 
indicators are OECD gross domestic product, OECD unemployment and the 
Trade Weighted Index.
<P>
The indicators show that the growth rate in short-term visitor arrivals 
to Australia will ease during the next few years, with growth in this 
area seeming to have reached a cyclical peak in late 1993 when tourist 
numbers increased by 15 per cent in one year.
<P>
Arrivals are now expected to grow at a more moderate rate for the next 
two to three years, although the present recovery in the world economy 
should stimulate an increase in the growth rate again after that time.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="DTM.GIF"><P>
<H2><I>Domestic Tourism Monitor<BR>
Annual Report 1993-94</I></H2>
<P>
This comprehensive review of travel by Australians in Australia, provides 
detailed tables and analyses for interstate, intrastate and day trips. 
Data includes State or Territory of residence and visit, purpose of 
visit, transport used, type of accommodation, seasonality of travel, 
duration of trip, and the age and sex of travellers.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Visitorstoregions.GIF"><P>
<H2><I>Regional Reports 1995</I></H2>
<P>
These brief summaries provide five years of regional data from the 
International Visitor Survey (IVS) and Domestic Tourism Monitor  (DTM) 
for visitor nights and visits to regions for each State and Territory. 
Calendar year IVS and financial year DTM statistics are given to provide 
a composite picture of the regional market. Details are also given of the 
State share in national tourism activity so that the regional results can 
be examined in an Australian context.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="Backpackers.GIF"><P>
<H2><I>Backpackers in Australia (BTR Occasional Paper No. 20)</I>
</H2><P>
This major new publication from the Bureau of Tourism Research (BTR) 
provides the first detailed profile of Australia's domestic and 
international backpacker market.
<P>
It examines the characteristics and behaviour of this type of traveller, 
exploding the long-held belief that backpackers are tourists on a 
shoestring budget - they actually stay longer, spend more, visit more 
regions, use more forms of travel and take part in more activities than 
other types of tourist.
<P>
The report gives detailed data on backpackers' reasons for travelling, 
where they visit and how long they stay for, their age, sex and 
occupation, the activities they participate in, and how much they spend, 
for example. It also highlights some interesting differences between the 
domestic and international backpacker market.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=3 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 SRC="WorkProgram.GIF">
<H2><I>BTR Work Program  (1995-96 edition)</I></H2>
<P>
This report of major achievements for the previous year and new tasks and 
priorities for the coming year is a must for all BTR clients.
<P>
<ADDRESS>Information on all BTR publications is available from the 
publications line, (06) 279 7183.</ADDRESS>
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
