<H1><B>Table of Contents</B></H1>
<UL TYPE=disk>
<LI>
<B><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="Chairman.html">Message from the Chairman</A></B><BR>
An introduction from the Chairman, Frank Conroy.<P>
<LI><B>
<!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="VisitorArrivals.html">Visitor arrivals to double by 
2000</A></B><BR>
Inbound tourism is set to grow at an average annual rate of 11 per cent 
to 2000, maintaining its position as the fastest-growing sector of 
Australia's tourism industry.<P>
<LI><B><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="visitor.html">International visitor nights and expenditure in 
Australia</A></B><BR>
Spending by international tourists is expected to grow by 9 per cent a 
year, visitor nights by about 8 per cent a year, and visitor nights in 
hotels, motels and guest houses by almost 11 per cent a year.<P>
<LI><B><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="departures.html">Resident departures to rise rapidly</A> 
</B><BR>
Continuing strong economic growth in Australia should see rapid increases 
in the level of overseas travel by Australians - rising at an average 
annual rate of 9 per cent over the next five years.<P>
<LI><B><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="indicators.html">Looking short-term with leading 
indicators</A></B><BR>
The growth rate in short-term visitor arrivals appeared to peak in late 
1993. International visitor arrivals will continue to increase, but the 
rate of growth is likely to be  slower than in the early 1990s. <P>
<LI><B><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="accommodation.html">An encouraging but patchy recovery
for hotels and motels</A></B><BR>
Nationally, the accommodation industry has recovered well from the  
recession, but there are still difficulties confronting owners in some 
regions because of oversupply.<P>
</UL>
