<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created by Charles Dean of Computer
Law Services-->
<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - Department of Tourism</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">DEPARTMENT OF TOURISM
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">THE DEPARTMENT OF TOURISM
</A></H2>
<P>The Department of Tourism's mission is to enhance the contribution
tourism makes to the wellbeing of Australians.  Its objectives are to:</P><P
></P><UL>
<LI>promote the development of an economically efficient industry
consistent with broader national economic objectives;</LI>
<LI>encourage responsible planning and management practices which
provide for ecologically sustainable tourism and which respect
Australia's cultural diversity;</LI>
<LI>seek favourable social outcomes of tourism;</LI>
<LI>undertake research and facilitate the provision of timely and
accurate advice and information; and</LI>
<LI>ensure that the Department operates efficiently and effectively.</LI></UL><P
></P><P>The Department undertakes analysis of a broad range of tourism
related policy issues and administers a range of programs outlined
below:</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">REGIONAL TOURISM DEVELOPMENT
PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Government is encouraging the development of regional Australia
to generate long-term economic and employment growth.  A significant
element of its commitment to regional Australia is the Regional Tourism
Development Program (RTDP).</P><P></P><P>The RTDP aims to spread the
economic benefits of tourism to rural and regional Australia by
providing assistance for strategic tourism planning, infrastructure
projects and tourism information coordination within a region. This kind
of regional development will improve the capacity and ability of
regional Australia to attract international and domestic tourists.</P><P>
</P><P>RTDP will provide a total of  $23 million over the four years to
1996-97:</P><P></P><UL>
<LI>$5.5 million in 1993-94</LI>
<LI>$6.5 million in 1994-95</LI>
<LI>$5.5 million in 1995-96</LI>
<LI>$5.5 million in 1996-97.</LI></UL><P></P><P><B>Eligibility</B></P><P
><B></B></P><P>Applications are sought annually from eligible
organisations.</P><P></P><P>Eligibility for assistance under the
Program is restricted to local government authorities, regional tourism
associations and regional development organisations, which may submit
applications separately or jointly.</P><P></P><P><B>Selection
Criteria</B></P><P><B></B></P><P>Projects are selected on a
competitive basis.  Their selection is determined by how well they meet
the aim and priorities of the Program and an assessment against the
following criteria:</P><UL>
<LI>Projects should be fundamentally viable, economically and
environmentally sustainable and permit regional areas to benefit from
the growth of tourism.</LI>
<LI>Projects should have the potential to stimulate private sector
tourism development.</LI>
<LI>Projects must be in response to an identified tourist market.</LI>
<LI>Projects should bring potential tourism benefits to a region as a
result of:<UL>
<LI>increased visitor numbers;</LI>
<LI>increased tourism investment; and</LI>
<LI>improvements in income and employment including through multiplier
effects.</LI></UL></LI></UL><P>The RTDP provides funding to local
government authorities, regional development organisations and regional
tourism associations for the:</P><UL>
<LI>development of regional tourism plans;</LI>
<LI>provision of tourism infrastructure to increase the capacity of a
region to support a range of tourism attractions;</LI>
<LI>diversification of the product base in regional areas to widen
their drawing power; and</LI>
<LI>coordination of information at the regional level.</LI></UL><P></P><P>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P></P><P>RTDP Hotline (06) 279 7206</P><P>
or write to</P><P>The Director</P><P>Regional Development Section</P><P>
Department of Tourism</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>
Tel: (06) 279 7192</P><P>Fax: (06) 279 7189</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC4"
>NATIONAL ECOTOURISM STRATEGY AND PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The National Ecotourism Strategy was released in March 1994. The
Strategy aims to identify the major issues affecting the planning,
development and management of ecotourism in Australia and to develop a
national framework to guide ecotourism operators, natural resource
managers, planners, developers and all levels of government in
addressing those issues.</P><P></P><P>The Government has committed $10
million to implement the Strategy through the National Ecotourism
Program.  Funding of $2 million is being provided in 1993-94 and 1994-95
and $3 million in 1995-96 and 1996-97.  Funding is available under this
Program for projects that assist:</P><UL>
<LI>the development of appropriate ecotourism <B>infrastructure</B>;</LI>
<LI>with <B>baseline studies and monitoring</B> to assess and
contribute to the management of ecotourism impacts;</LI>
<LI>the integration of ecotourism into <B>regional planning</B>;</LI>
<LI>in the organisation of ecotourism <B>conferences and workshops</B>.</LI></UL><P
></P><P>Program components will vary and will be set against guidelines
reviewed annually. In later years of the Program, ecotourism education,
energy and waste minimisation and business development may be areas in
which grants will also be available.</P><P></P><P><B>Eligibility</B></P><P
></P><P>Funding is available to Commonwealth, State/Territory and local
government agencies, natural  resource management agencies, education
and training bodies, research institutions, cultural and conservation
bodies, community organisations, professional associations, indigenous
communities and regional development organisations.</P><P></P><P>Individuals,
private companies and profit-making enterprises are ineligible.</P><P></P><P
><B>Selection Criteria</B></P><P></P><P>Applications will be assessed
against criteria set out in the guidelines of the Program, available on
request.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Director</P><P>
Nature Based and Indigenous Tourism Section</P><P>Department of Tourism</P><P
>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 279 7126</P><P>
Fax: (06) 279 7189</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC5">FOREST ECOTOURISM
PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Forest Ecotourism Program aims to encourage and facilitate
ecotourism in forests throughout Australia on a sustainable basis. It is
directed towards developing opportunities for visitors and tourism
operators to understand and appreciate forest environments while
encouraging the sustainable management of natural resources.</P><P></P><P>
The Program is a competitive grants program developed under the National
Forest Policy Statement and administered by the Department of Tourism.</P><P
></P><P>The 1992-93 Budget included $1.9 million over four years for
forest ecotourism initiatives. Fifteen projects were funded in 1992-93,
and 17 in 1993-94. A limit of $30,000 for individual grants under the
Program is usually applied.</P><P></P><P>The Program objectives are
to:</P><UL>
<LI>provide opportunities for visitors to enjoy and appreciate forest
environments and to learn and understand their impacts on these
environments;</LI>
<LI>increase the number of informed tourism operators with the capacity
to provide educational experiences in forested areas;</LI>
<LI>encourage ecologically sustainable planning and management of
visitor use of forests; and</LI>
<LI>facilitate research  that contributes to the Program's goal and
objectives.</LI></UL><P></P><P><B>Eligibility</B></P><P><B></B></P><P>
The Program is directed at Commonwealth, State/Territory and local
government agencies, natural resource management agencies, education and
training bodies, research institutions, cultural and conservation
bodies, community organisations, professional associations, indigenous
communities and regional development organisations with a particular
interest in ecotourism.</P><P></P><P>Grantees must generally be
incorporated non-profit organisations that can demonstrate a commitment
to the principles of ecologically sustainable forest tourism and the
capacity to develop and implement ecotourism opportunities or products. 
Grantees are required to adhere to grant conditions.</P><P></P><P>A
wide range of projects will be considered for funding.  These may
include minor infrastructure projects (such as tourist boardwalks,
viewing platforms and interpretive signs) education and awareness
activities, applied research, development of forest ecotourism planning
and management strategies, and tour operator training
workshops/seminars.  Projects are required to be completed within 12
months of receipt of a grant.</P><P></P><P><B>Selection Criteria</B></P><P
><B></B></P><P>Proposed projects must meet the goals and objectives of
the Program.</P><P></P><P>Applications will be assessed in accordance
with the criteria set out in the Program guidelines. These are available
on request.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Director</P><P
>Environment Management Section</P><P>Department of  Tourism</P><P>GPO
Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT 2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 279 7146</P><P>Fax:
(06) 239 6411</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">NATIONAL RURAL TOURISM
STRATEGY AND PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Department is currently developing a National Rural Tourism
Strategy which will examine the key issues in country tourism and
provide a framework for achieving a greater level of cooperation between
the Government and industry in developing the rural tourism sector.</P><P>
</P><P>Under the Rural Tourism Program, $4 million is being provided
over the four years to 1996-97 to stimulate tourism development in rural
and regional Australia.</P><P></P><P>The Program assists the industry
development, education and training, standards and marketing needs of
the rural tourism sector at the national level.  Its aim is to develop
rural tourism opportunities that provide both domestic and international
visitors with a broad range of tourism experiences while, at the same
time, benefiting country communities through increased business and
employment growth.</P><P></P><P>Funding in the initial year of the
Program (1993-94) covered areas identified through public and industry
consultations, including discussions with the Rural Tourism Focus Group
which comprises key tourism representatives from industry and
government.</P><P></P><P>A `needs analysis' consultancy is to be
conducted in conjunction with the preparation of the National Rural
Tourism Strategy.</P><P></P><P>The Direction of the Program over the
three remaining years will reflect the outcome of the consultancy and
the Strategy.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The
Director</P><P>Regional Development Section</P><P>Department of
Tourism</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06)
279 7192</P><P>Fax: (06) 239 6411</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">SITES
OF NATIONAL TOURISM SIGNIFICANCE PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Sites of National Tourism Significance Program was announced in
the Prime Minister's Statement on the Environment in December 1992.  The
Program aims to encourage and facilitate the ecologically sustainable
management and use of natural sites of national tourism significance. 
The Government will provide $2 million over three years from 1993-94 to
fund the Program.</P><P></P><P>The Program objectives are to:</P><UL>
<LI>promote the adoption of ecologically sustainable development
principles in the management of sites of national tourism significance;</LI>
<LI>reduce the environmental impacts of tourism through infrastructure
projects;</LI>
<LI>enhance visitor appreciation of environmental values and increase
their understanding of the impacts of their activities on the natural
environment and ecological processes; and</LI>
<LI>facilitate applied research into sustainable management of tourism
in natural areas.</LI></UL><P></P><P><B>Eligibility</B></P><P></P><P>
The Program is directed at:</P><UL>
<LI>State/Territory Governments and local government authorities that
contribute to the development, management and conservation of natural
sites of national tourism significance;</LI>
<LI>natural areas of current national and/or international tourism
significance where the environmental values are under threat by
increasing levels of tourist activity;</LI>
<LI>natural areas of potential or emerging national and/or
international tourism significance where the environmental values are
likely to be under threat by increasing levels of tourist activity; and</LI>
<LI>projects that contribute to ecologically sustainable tourism
development, natural resource management, site planning, visitor and
operator education and training and applied research.</LI></UL><P></P><P>
<B>Selection Criteria</B></P><P><B></B></P><P>Proposed projects must
meet the description of an `eligible site' and will be assessed in
accordance with the goals, objectives and priorities of the Program.</P><P>
</P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Director</P><P>Environment
Management Section</P><P>Department of Tourism</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>
Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 279 7146</P><P>Fax: (06) 239 6411</P><P
></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC8">INDIGENOUS TOURISM STRATEGY AND INITIATIVES
</A></H3>
<P>The Department of Tourism encourages increased involvement by
indigenous people in the tourism industry to enhance visitors'
experiences, generate wider understanding of the culture of indigenous
Australians, and provide business opportunities for Aboriginal and
Torres Strait Islander people.  In addressing these objectives, the
Department is undertaking the following activities:</P><P></P><P><B><A NAME="RTFToC8_1"
>NATIONAL ABORIGINAL AND TORRES STRAIT ISLANDER TOURISM STRATEGY</A></B></P><P
></P><P>The Department of Tourism and the Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander Commission (ATSIC) are jointly developing the National
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Tourism Strategy. The Strategy
aims to enhance opportunities for self determination, self management
and economic self sufficiency in tourism for indigenous Australians.</P><P>
</P><P>To oversee the development of the Strategy, the Tourism Industry
Advisory Committee (TIAC) has been established.  TIAC members include
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander representatives, tourism
operators, tourism industry organisations, State/Territory nominees and
Commonwealth agencies (the Department of Tourism, ATSIC and the
Department of Employment, Education and Training).  An ATSIC
Commissioner chairs the Committee.</P><P></P><P>Further information on
the Strategy and the work of TIAC is outlined on page 37.</P><P></P><P><B>
<A NAME="RTFToC8_2"><I>A TALENT FOR TOURISM</I> BOOKLET</A></B></P><P></P><P
>As part of a range of Commonwealth initiatives to recognise the
International Year of the World's Indigenous People, the Department of
Tourism published
<I>A Talent for Tourism</I>, a booklet profiling a range of successful
tourism ventures.</P><P></P><P>The profiles are intended to be used as
a resource by other indigenous groups proposing to enter the tourism
industry and as a resource for the tourism industry.</P><P></P><P>TO
OBTAIN A BOOKLET CONTACT:</P><P>The Information Officer</P><P>Department
of  Tourism</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel:
(06) 279 7222</P><P>Fax: (06) 248 0734</P><P>Toll Free: 008 804 465</P><P>
(answering machine)
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC9">BACKPACKER PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>In recognition of the growing significance of the backpacker market,
the Government is providing almost $4 million over four years to 1996-97
for the development of this market.</P><P></P><P>The Program aims to:</P><UL
>
<LI>facilitate the development of a viable, professional and
internationally competitive backpacker  industry;</LI>
<LI>facilitate wider dispersion of the employment, economic and social
benefits of tourism throughout the Australian community; and</LI>
<LI>provide opportunities to broaden the tourism product base and cater
for a wider cross-section of visitors.</LI></UL><P></P><P>Broadly, the
Backpacker Program is expected to reduce impediments to growth, expand
marketing networks, improve standards in the backpacker accommodation
sector, encourage a strategic approach to the development of the market
and to ensure a positive return to the economy.</P><P></P><P>Under the
first year of the Program, $830 000 was allocated to the Australian
Tourist Commission (ATC) to undertake marketing activities in the short
term, specifically targeted to the backpacker market with concentration
on priority international markets including the UK, North America,
Japan, Germany, Austria, Switzerland and Scandinavia.</P><P></P><P>A
scheme for classifying backpacker accommodation is being developed in
conjunction with the Australian Automobile Association (AAA), its
constituent members and key industry groups.  The scheme is intended to
provide recognisable standards of quality of facilities for the
information of tourism operators and travellers.</P><P></P><P>A
Strategic Plan for the development of the backpacker market in the
medium to longer term is also being prepared.  The Plan, which is being
developed in consultation with the tourism industry and State and
Territory tourism authorities, will provide direction for future funding
initiatives.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Director</P><P
>Industry Development Section</P><P>Department of  Tourism</P><P>GPO
Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 279 7141</P><P>Fax:
(06) 247 9241</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC10">NATIONAL CRUISE
SHIPPING STRATEGY
</A></H3>
<P>The international cruise shipping industry has been one of the
fastest growing segments of the tourism industry over the last decade. 
As existing destinations become overcrowded, operators are likely to be
seeking new locations to base their ships and new itineraries to attract
both first-time and repeat passengers.  This suggests that there is a
window of opportunity for the Australian tourism industry.</P><P></P><P>
The Government is currently developing a National Cruise Shipping
Strategy with a view to determining the most advantageous operating
environment for foreign cruise ships, within the framework of broader
Government policy.</P><P></P><P>Funding was provided in the 1993-94
Budget and work is progressing on the development of both policy and
promotional aspects of the Strategy.</P><P></P><P>Following extensive
government and industry consultation, a discussion paper,
<I>Towards a National Cruise Shipping Strategy</I>, was released for
public comment.  The discussion paper provides an overview of issues
affecting cruise ships in Australia.</P><P></P><P>Action is also under
way to promote Australia as a cruise destination.  The Department of
Tourism contributed to a major ATC/industry cooperative print media
campaign in the United Kingdom, and for the first time, Australia had a
strong presence at Seatrade Miami, the major annual international cruise
shipping trade fair.  The ATC, with funding assistance from the
Department, coordinated an Australia-New Zealand stand with the theme
`Cruising Down Under'.  A database of ports was produced by the
Department to provide details of port facilities and essential support
services and includes a facility to create itineraries. The database was
distributed to international cruise operators.  An updated database will
be released shortly.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The
Director</P><P>Market Development Section</P><P>Department of Tourism</P><P
>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 279 7129</P><P>
Fax: (06) 247 9241</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC11">TOURISM
FORECASTING COUNCIL
</A></H3>
<P>In 1993, the Prime Minister announced the establishment of the
Tourism Forecasting Council (TFC).</P><P></P><P>The Council is a high
profile reporting body comprised of representatives from the tourism,
finance, construction, property and union sectors.  It is supported by a
technically oriented advisory body chaired by the Director of the Bureau
of Tourism Research (BTR).</P><P></P><P>The primary aim of the Council
is to produce and disseminate credible and timely forecasts of industry
activity as a basis for sound investment decision-making.  This will
help to avoid the boom and bust cycles of investment activity that have
characterised the industry in the past.  The Council's work has gained
momentum with the publication of its first report
<I>Forecast </I>in August 1994 which focuses on forecasts of domestic
tourism and the TFC's sponsorship of a tourism and leisure index on the
Australian Stock Exchange.  Areas of future TFC work include:</P><UL>
<LI>forecasts of international visitor arrivals by country/region,
leading indicators of international arrivals, and forecasts of outbound
trips by purpose (available late 1994);</LI>
<LI>forecasts of domestic visitor nights by purpose and hotel activity
by region (available from early 1995); and</LI>
<LI>forecasts of regional destination choices for domestic tourists,
leading indicators of visitor arrivals by country and short-term
forecasts of visitor arrivals (available from mid-1995).</LI></UL><P></P><P
>The TFC will continue to encourage tourism investment based on
professional business planning, long-term operating viability, and an
achievable vision of the industry's future.  The Council acknowledges
that new investment will only occur in response to realistic
expectations of sustainable profitability. Getting the right level of
future investment depends on the availability and use of accurate and
timely forecasts of the balance between supply and demand.</P><P></P><P>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Secretary</P><P>Tourism Forecasting
Council</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06)
279 7115</P><P>Fax: (06) 279 7273</P><P><B></B>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">The Business of Tourism - A FINANCIAL
MANAGEMENT MANUAL
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>The Department has sponsored the publication of  <I>The
Business of Tourism</I>, a financial management manual developed in
association with the Australian Bankers' Association to assist in the
development of quality financial management of tourism businesses.  All
material was developed after consultation with relevant tourism
operators, industry associations and banks.</P><P></P><P>The manual
was designed to assist those already operating in the tourism or
hospitality related industries, or those thinking of establishing a
business in those sectors.  It provides information on:</P><UL>
<LI>how to operate a small tourism venture;</LI>
<LI>sources of finance for tourism businesses;</LI>
<LI>preparation of loan proposals; and</LI>
<LI><B></B>day-to-day financial management.<B></B></LI></UL><P><B></B></P><P
><B></B>The manual also contains general reading material, a workbook,
checklists and case studies.  Although the manual is available as a
three-ring folder for $37.95, the loose-leaf contents can also be
purchased separately for $32.95 (including postage and handling).</P><P></P><P
>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>Australian Bankers' Association</P><P>Education
Service</P><P>Level 42</P><P>55 Collins Street</P><P>Melbourne  VIC 
3000</P><P>Tel: 008 033 652</P><P>Toll Free</P><P>Fax: (03) 650 1756</P><P
>or the Department of Tourism Information Service (06) 279 7222</P><P></P><H3
><A NAME="RTFToC13">Welcome To Australia - BROCHURE FOR INTERNATIONAL
VISITORS
</A></H3> The Department of Tourism has developed an information
brochure for international visitors called <I>Welcome to Australia</I>.<P>
</P><P>As well as welcoming overseas visitors, the brochure ensures
that they are provided with information that can contribute to their
safety, security and health.  This is particularly important where
visitor safety may be jeopardised due to unfamiliarity with Australian
conditions.</P><P></P><P>Information contained in the brochure
includes advice on health, driving safety, emergency numbers, contact
numbers for tourism information and the Telephone Interpreter Service. 
The brochure contents were identified and refined with the assistance of
the tourism industry, the Australian Tourist Commission and Government
departments.</P><P></P><P><I>Welcome to Australia </I>was launched by
the Minister for Tourism in July 1994.  The brochure is available in
four languages and will be evaluated following a six-month trial.  The
languages being trialed are English, Japanese, Mandarin and German.</P><P>
</P><P>During the pilot phase, the brochure will be distributed through
Sydney International Airport with the assistance of the Australian
Customs Service, the Federal Airports Corporation (FAC) and Tourism New
South Wales. Distribution will be through a number of static displays
placed in the primary line and baggage collection areas of the arrivals
halls and through the Tourism New South Wales `Meet and Greet' staff. 
Distribution will also take place through the FAC's Travellers
Information Service Desk at Melbourne International Airport.</P><P></P><P>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Information Officer</P><P>Department
of  Tourism</P><P>GPO Box 1545</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel:
(06) 279 7222</P><P>Fax: (06) 248 0734</P><P>Toll Free: 008 804 465</P><P>
(answering machine)</P><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC14">DEPARTMENT OF
TOURISM INFORMATION SERVICE
</A></H3>
<P>The Department produces a range of publications and Facts Sheets on
tourism issues.  A publications list is available from the Information
Office.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>The Information
