<TITLE>MARKETING AND EXPORT ASSISTANCE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">MARKETING AND EXPORT ASSISTANCE
</A></H1>
<P>
</P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">AUSTRALIAN TOURIST COMMISSION
</A></H2>
<P>The Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) markets Australia
internationally as a tourist destination for the economic and social
benefit of all Australians. Its role is to work closely with industry to
identify market opportunities; develop awareness of, and desire to,
travel to Australia; develop tourism product, and distribute information
to the travel industry and consumers.</P><P></P><P>The ATC works with
the State and Territory tourism authorities and industry in cooperative
marketing programs.  In the 1994-95 Budget, the Government allocated a
record $78.942 million to the ATC.  This funding is expected to be
complemented by industry contributions and revenue from other services
totalling $32.5 million.</P><P>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">PARTNERSHIP AUSTRALIA
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>Partnership Australia is a cooperative marketing
venture between the ATC and all State and Territory tourism
organisations.  The initiative was designed to coordinate the State,
Territory and Commonwealth tourism marketing effort, thus improving the
economic efficiency of international promotion.</P><P></P><P>Partnership
Australia produces a more focussed promotional image, better tailored
travel packages, and coordinated distribution of travel information to
travel agents and consumers.</P><P></P><P>It is designed to convert
strong international interest in Australia as a holiday destination into
sales through increased tactical marketing, improved information
servicing, and the development and distribution of tourism products.</P><P>
</P><P>Opportunities for the Australian travel industry include
advertising in ATC and State/Territory brochures, listings on Facts
Sheets and promotion though trade communications. Market intelligence is
provided through feedback from trade and consumer help lines.</P><P>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC4">COOPERATIVE MARKETING GUIDE
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>This free publication assists tourism operators plan
their international marketing activities.  It includes information on:</P><UL
>
<LI>advertising rates, application and copy deadlines, and publication
dates for the ATC's <I>Traveller's Guide </I>series, as well as for
more specialised trade and media publications such as <I>G'Day Asia</I>
and the <I>Aussie Specialist Newsletter</I>;</LI>
<LI>direct mail opportunities worldwide;</LI>
<LI>trade shows, cooperative marketing promotions and special marketing
events in which the ATC is involved, including the Australian Tourism
Exchange (ATE) and International Tourismus Borse (ITB) in Berlin;</LI>
<LI>the Visiting Journalists Programme (VJP);</LI>
<LI>accessing the ATC's extensive photographic and video library;</LI>
<LI>making use of the ATC's corporate library; and</LI>
<LI>Partnership Australia activities.</LI></UL><P>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC5">INTERNATIONAL TOURISM MARKETING MANUAL
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>The International Tourism Marketing Manual has been
developed to provide new and established tourism operators with
appropriate information to explore, plan and target their international
marketing activities.  The manual is aimed at those:</P><UL>
<LI>with no prior experience of tourism who wish to explore
opportunities in the tourism industry;</LI>
<LI>with experience in domestic tourism who wish to explore a possible
expansion into one or more international markets;</LI>
<LI>with experience in some international markets who wish to expand
into other markets perceived as more difficult (for example, because of
different languages and cultures); and</LI>
<LI>operators with considerable experience who wish to access
up-to-date information on market segments identified through ATC
research.</LI></UL><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>Australian
Tourist Commission</P><P>Level 3, 80 William Street</P><P>Woolloomooloo</P><P
>Sydney  NSW  2011</P><P>Tel: (02) 360 1111</P><P>Fax: (02) 331 3385</P><P
>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">CONVENTION ASSISTANCE SCHEME
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>The Convention Assistance Scheme (CAS) offers direct
financial assistance to the convention industry as a means of
encouraging Australian associations to bid for international
conventions, or maximise overseas attendance at an international
convention being held in Australia.</P><P></P><P>CAS supports the
production of suitable promotional material to enhance bid submissions. 
It also assists with production of brochures, overseas mailings, video
production, trade show participation and use of promotional give aways.</P><P
></P><P>The level of support approved by the ATC is determined by the
size of the conference, its budget and type of promotional activities.
Usually the maximum allocation is $5 000.  In 1994-95, the CAS budget
was $260 000, and increase of $50 000 over the 1993-94 allocation.  In
1993-94, CAS assisted 70 conventions and bids, including:</P><UL>
<LI>the 17th Annual International Congress of Allergology and Clinical
Immunology to be held in Sydney in the year 2000;</LI>
<LI>the 1998 International Council of Museums General Assembly in
Melbourne with an expected 2000 delegates; and</LI>
<LI>the 1996 Second World Fisheries Congress in Brisbane with an
expected 1 500 delegates.</LI></UL><P>CAS has assisted in winning some
very significant conferences for Australia: the 1993 Rotary
International Convention, Melbourne, with 22 000 delegates and worth $80
million; and the 1996 World Congress of Anaesthesiologists, Sydney which
is expected to generate over $43 million.</P><P></P><P>Since the
scheme's inception, $1.2 million has been allocated to over 365
associations for events expected to bring into Australia more than 270
000 visitors and inject over $1.3 billion into the Australian economy.</P><P
></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P></P><P>Australian Tourist
Commission</P><P>Level 3, 80 William Street</P><P>Woolloomooloo  NSW 
2011</P><P>Tel: (02) 360 1111</P><P>Fax: (02) 331 4809</P><P></P><P>
</P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC7">AUSTRADE</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC8">EXPORT MARKET DEVELOPMENT GRANTS SCHEME
</A></H3>
<B></B><P><B></B>Tourism operators who are Australian residents can
apply for Export Market Development Grants which reimburse up to half
the cost of eligible overseas promotional expenses.</P><P></P><P>Grants
are available to operators who spend at least $30 000 in a grant year
with expenditure after the first $15 000 being eligible.  The maximum
grant is $250 000 in any grant year.  To target assistance to small to
medium-sized businesses, operators with export earnings in excess of $25
million are excluded from the Scheme.</P><P></P><P>Operators must
promote one or more of the following amenities to people overseas:</P><UL>
<LI>passenger services by land;</LI>
<LI>passenger services by water;</LI>
<LI>passenger services by air</LI>
<LI>accommodation;</LI>
<LI>	tours with escort (not driver); and</LI>
<LI>admission to a tourist attraction.</LI></UL><P></P><P>For
operators who promote a package of at least three of the above amenities
for an all inclusive price, a grant rate of 50 cents in the dollar is
payable. Amended legislation expected to come into effect for the
1994-95 grant year will allow operators promoting less than three
amenities a grant rate of 25 cents in the dollar.  The legislation will
also provide for the inclusion of convention centres as an additional
amenity and the extension of the accommodation amenity to include
restaurants and casinos.</P><P></P><P>The Scheme is retrospective and
grants in any one year are payable in respect of eligible expenditure in
the previous year.  Claims may be lodged in the period 1 July to 30
November following a particular grant year.</P><P></P><P>Applicants
are eligible to receive up to eight grants with an export earnings test
applying in the third and subsequent years.  First time applicants can
aggregate expenditure over two successive grant years.</P><P></P><P>FOR
FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT AUSTRADE:</P><P></P><P>New South Wales/ACT</P><P
>AIDC Tower</P><P>Level 22</P><P>201 Kent street</P><P>Sydney  NSW 
2000</P><P>Tel: (02) 390 2787</P><P>Fax: (02) 390 2796</P><P></P><P>Victoria/Tasmania</P><P
>Level 21</P><P>Tower East</P><P>40 City Road</P><P>South Melbourne 
VIC  3205</P><P>Tel: (03) 284 3140</P><P>Fax: (03) 284 3144</P><P></P><P>
Western Australia</P><P>36th Floor</P><P>Exchange Plaza</P><P>2 The
Esplanade</P><P>Perth  WA  6000</P><P>Tel: (09) 261 7911</P><P>Fax:
(09) 261 7965</P><P></P><P>Queensland</P><P>Level 13</P><P>145 Eagle
Street</P><P>Brisbane  QLD 4000</P><P>Tel: (07) 364 7752</P><P>      
(07) 364 7771</P><P>Fax: (07) 832 1529</P><P></P><P>South
Australia/Northern Territory</P><P>1st Floor</P><P>70 Hindmarsh Square</P><P
>Adelaide  SA 5000</P><P>Tel: (08) 202 7811</P><P>Fax: (08) 202 7878</P><P
>
</P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC9">INTERNATIONAL TRADE ENHANCEMENT SCHEME
</A></H2>
<B></B><P><B></B>The International Trade Enhancement Scheme (ITES)
offers tourism operators low cost, repayable finance to support export
marketing activities such as offshore set-up costs, travel, promotion,
advertising and salaries. The Scheme is designed to enhance and
accelerate export projects that have the potential to contribute
substantially to Net Foreign Exchange (NFE) earnings.</P><P></P><P>Administered
by Austrade, the ITES is directed at projects that will generate at
least $10 million in NFE earnings over five years.  Finance of up to
$2.25 million ($5 million for exceptional projects) is available on the
basis of Austrade contributing $1 for every $20 of projected NFE
earnings.</P><P></P><P>Support is provided in the form of either a
concessional loan or an advance which attracts royalty payments
calculated as a percentage of export revenues. Concessional loans are
interest free for the first three years.  The interest rate currently
averages around 1.8 per cent per annum over the six-year period of the
loan.</P><P></P><P>To qualify for ITES, applicants must first complete
a short questionnaire to determine eligibility.  Following this
screening process, those selected can lodge an application and a
business plan for the proposed project.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER
INFORMATION</P><P>NSW, Queensland and ACT</P><P>State Manager, ITES
Austrade</P><P>22nd Floor, AIDC Tower</P><P>201 Kent Street</P><P>Sydney
 NSW  2000</P><P>Tel: (02) 390 2386</P><P>Fax: (02) 390 2730</P><P></P><P
>Victoria and Tasmania</P><P>State Manager, ITES Austrade</P><P>Southgate
Tower East</P><P>40 City Road</P><P>South Melbourne  VIC  3205</P><P>Tel:
(03) 284 3139</P><P>Fax: (03) 284 3144</P><P></P><P>Western
Australia, South Australia and Northern Territory</P><P>State Manager,
ITES Austrade</P><P>36th Floor</P><P>Exchange Plaza</P><P>2 The
Esplanade</P><P>Perth  WA  6000</P><P>Tel: (09) 261 7911</P><P>Fax:
(09) 261 7965</P><P>
</P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC10">EXPORT FINANCE AND INSURANCE CORPORATION
</A></H2>
<P>The Export Finance and Insurance Corporation (EFIC) provides
assistance to exporters through a specialised range of insurance
guarantee and finance facilities including export credit insurance,
export finance, bonding facilities and overseas investment insurance.</P><P>
</P><P>The key eligibility criterion is that the export must have
majority Australian content.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P><P>
Mr Peter Johnson</P><P>NSW Branch</P><P>Level 8</P><P>22 Pitt Street</P><P
>Sydney  NSW  2000</P><P>Tel:(02) 201 2222</P><P>Fax: (02) 251 3851</P><P>
</P><P>Mr Arnold Baldwin</P><P>WA Branch</P><P>Exchange Plaza</P><P>The
Esplanade</P><P>Perth  WA  6000</P><P>Tel:(09) 231 4222</P><P>Fax:
(09) 231 4211</P><P></P><P>Mr Philip Marley</P><P>SA &amp; NT Branch</P><P
>Level 1</P><P>70 Hindmarsh Square</P><P>Adelaide  SA 5000</P><P>Tel:
(08) 400 7800</P><P>Fax: (08) 400 7848</P><P></P><P>Mr Tyrrell
McGeever</P><P>QLD Branch</P><P>Level 9</P><P>484 Queen Street</P><P>Brisbane
 QLD  4000</P><P>Tel: (07) 405 2600</P><P>Fax: (07) 831 2021</P><P></P><P
>Mr Glenn Rothberg</P><P>VIC &amp; TAS Branch</P><P>Level 20 Southgate
Tower East</P><P>40 City Road</P><P>South Melbourne  VIC  3205</P><P>Tel:
(03) 206 4902</P><P>Fax: (03) 206 4914</P><P></P><P>
</P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC11">AUSTRALIAN INTERNATIONAL DEVELOPMENT
ASSISTANCE BUREAU
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">PRIVATE SECTOR LINKAGES PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Australian International Development Assistance Bureau (AIDAB),
which is an administratively autonomous unit within the Department of
Foreign Affairs and Trade, is responsible for all aspects of Australia's
official development assistance.  The main objectives of the Private
Sector Linkages Program (PSLP) are to promote sustainable development in
developing countries in response to Australia's humanitarian concerns
and to further Australia's commercial and foreign policy interests.</P><P>
</P><P>The PSLP provides grants to Australian business enterprises
wishing to extend their linkages in Asia. It aims to promote sustainable
development and economic growth through activities which link
market-oriented enterprises in Australia and selected developing
countries.  Grants of up to $250 000 on a dollar for dollar cost sharing
basis are offered.  The minimum level of funding assistance is $25000.</P><P
></P><P>Eligible activities include:</P><UL>
<LI>short-term training (no longer than six months);</LI>
<LI>	pre-feasibility and feasibility studies;</LI>
<LI>demonstration, adaptation and supply of Australian technology; and</LI>
<LI>pre-investment studies.</LI></UL><P></P><P><B>Eligibility</B></P><P>
</P><P>To be eligible to submit a proposal for support under the
Program, an applicant must be an Australian company carrying on business
in Australia, an Australian industry association, or an Australian
government business enterprise.</P><P></P><P><B>Selection Criteria</B></P><P
><B></B></P><P><B></B>Applications are assessed according to their
developmental priority, their contribution to sustainable development
and economic growth in the developing country, the extent to which they
promote trade and investment links, and the capacity of the applicant
and its nominated overseas counterpart.</P><P></P><P>FOR FURTHER
INFORMATION:</P><P>Business Co-operation Section</P><P>AIDAB</P><P>GPO
Box 887</P><P>Canberra  ACT  2601</P><P>Tel: (06) 276 4058</P><P>Fax:
(06) 276 4875</P><P><B></B></P><P><B></B>
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
