<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created Adam Clarke of Computer Law
Services.-->
<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - AUSINDUSTRY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">AUSINDUSTRY</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">AUSINDUSTRY</A></H2>
<P>One of the key industry assistance initiatives outlined in the
Government's May 1994 White Paper, <I>Working Nation</I>, is the
development of AusIndustry. The Office of AusIndustry, within the
Department of Industry, Science and Technology, will improve the
coordination and delivery of business assistance programs, and provide a
better, more focused service to Australian business.  A private
sector-led Board of AusIndustry will guide these efforts.</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">BUSINESSLINK</A></H3>
<P>Through BusinessLink, the Commonwealth is working cooperatively with
State and Territory Governments to develop computer-based information
sources for small to medium-sized enterprises.  BusinessLink will
underpin AusIndustry's role as an entry point for all Commonwealth
business improvement programs, and will include a quality information
and referral service and a marketing network for the programs of other
Departments.</P>
<P></P>
<P>BusinessLink's objectives are to:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>provide access to business information when required;</LI>
<LI></LI>
<LI>provide information in the most cost effective manner;</LI>
<LI></LI>
<LI>provide information in a proactive way; and</LI>
<LI></LI>
<LI>provide information in a useable format.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>BusinessLink will provide information about export services, tenders
and other business opportunities, finance, business assistance measures
and programs, technology and product information, licensing
requirements, taxation, industrial awards, management advice and
training and industry assistance measures and services.</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC4">BIZHELP</A></H3>
<P>The first BusinessLink product to be marketed will be a new
computer-based guide to programs and services called BizHelp. BizHelp
will provide an accurate computer disk information guide on the full
range of Commonwealth and State industry support measures, as well as
selected private sector programs.  The guide is designed for use by
business advisers and includes a software package in diskette form,
quarterly updates, a basic training package and access to a help desk
service.  It will be distributed to a large number of intermediaries
including AusIndustry centres, the National Industry Extension Service
(NIES) and Small Business Development Corporation (SBDC) offices,
industry associations, accountants and consultants.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Other BusinessLink products to be developed are expected to include
information products covering licensing requirements and training
sources.</P>
<P></P>
<P>BizHelp is currently being piloted in a number of sites and is
expected to be widely available by the end of 1994.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr Peter Sagar</P>
<P>Assistant Secretary</P>
<P></P>
<P>or</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr Mike Wilson</P>
<P>Director</P>
<P>Marketing and Business Information Unit</P>
<P>Office of AusIndustry</P>
<P>Department of Industry, Science and Technology</P>
<P>GPO Box 9839</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: 008 026 121</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 276 1055</P>
<P>Email: Psagar@dit.gov.au or M Wilson@dit.gov.au</P>
<P></P>
<P>Specific information about BizHelp can be obtained from:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr Geoff Williams</P>
<P>Marketing and Business Information Unit</P>
<P>Office of AusIndustry</P>
<P>Department of Industry, Science and Technology</P>
<P>GPO Box 9839</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06)  276 1348</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 276 2237</P>
<P>Email: geoff.williams@dit.gov.au</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC5">NATIONAL INDUSTRY EXTENSION SERVICE
</A></H3>
<P>The National Industry Extension Service (NIES) is a joint
Commonwealth, State and Territory program which helps small and medium
sized Australian firms in the manufacturing and services sectors to
become internationally competitive through enterprise improvement. NIES'
overall strategy is to improve the internal efficiency and external
focus of enterprises and thereby to increase international
competitiveness.  Firms are encouraged to undertake enterprise
improvement activities as part of continuous improvement.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NIES has specially trained field officers in all States/Territories
to provide advice and information to firms. Firms can receive subsidies
to engage external consultants to facilitate and/or implement enterprise
improvement programs. While the level of funding is determined at the
State/Territory level, typically up to 50 per cent of the cost of
external advice is funded.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Since 1991-92, NIES has increased its focus on the services sector
through the Services Industry Extension Program (SIEP). SIEP aims to
raise the level of management and business skills in service industries
to enable them to compete more effectively in world markets.  The
initiative provides significant opportunities for increasing the
efficiency of the services sector and its contribution to export
earnings and import replacement.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Through SIEP, NIES provides firms with access to an expanded network
of accredited consultants, specialist field officers and a range of
enterprise improvement programs in best management practices.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In general, NIES subsidies are available to service firms with a
proven commercial record and a commitment to export.  States and
Territories target services sectors of significance to their regions,
including education, health, recreation and tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The availability of NIES subsidies for tourism operators varies
between States and Territories.  The States and Territories that do
target subsidies to tourism operators use guidelines to limit subsidies
to firms with an export and performance record and a growth objective. 
In most cases, access to subsidies is decided on a case by case basis.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NIES has developed a range of programs for small to medium sized
enterprises, covering:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>world competitive services;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>export market planning;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>benchmarking;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>total quality management; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>improvement through people.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">WORLD COMPETITIVE SERVICES
</A></H3>
<P>World Competitive Services (WCS) is a strategic planning process for
service based enterprises which emphasises that long-term success is
only achieved by companies continuously delivering superior value to
their chosen market segments.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The WCS process is designed to provide service-based enterprises
with a pragmatic, customer driven and effective strategic planning
process which culminates in the competitive repositioning of the company
in domestic and/or international markets.  The program includes:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>customer and employee perceptions;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>competitor and best practice benchmarking;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>internal attitudes and climate; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>customer and service profitability.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>WCS is a tightly integrated strategic planning process which focuses
on identifying and improving those critical aspects of the company which
impact on its competitive position.</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">EXPORT MARKET PLANNING
</A></H3>
<P>The Export Market Planning (EMP) program is designed to assist firms
to strategically plan and manage their exporting activities.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The program is delivered to firms by trained NIES consultants who
will tailor the program to suit the unique needs of individual companies
regardless of size, export base or market focus.  EMP contains an export
diagnostic and planning tool leading to the development of an effective
international marketing strategy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>EMP was developed in conjunction with Austrade and assistance is
available from Austrade for the market research components of the
program.</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC8">BENCHMARKING</A></H3>
<P>Benchmarking is an ongoing systematic process to search for and
introduce international best practice into an organisation.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NIES and the Best Practice Demonstration Program, which is jointly
administered by the Department of  Industrial Relations and the
Australian Manufacturing Council, recently released the <I>Self-Help
Benchmarking Manual</I> providing:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>a step-by-step guide to assist Australian firms to implement
benchmarking; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>smaller firms with access to clear and practical information on
benchmarking to enable them to design the most appropriate benchmarking
process for their organisation.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC9">TOTAL QUALITY MANAGEMENT
</A></H3>
<P>The Total Quality Management (TQM) program has as its primary
objective the achievement of international competitiveness for
Australian enterprises through the implementation of Total Quality
Management.</P>
<P></P>
<P>This management approach achieves continuous incremental improvement
in all processes, goods and services through the creative involvement of
all people. TQM is recognised as strategically important for a firm's
economic survival and as a major tool for lifting competitiveness in
world markets.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NIES Industry Advisers provide advice to help firms gain competitive
advantage through attention to TQM processes.  Financial subsidies are
available for eligible companies to enable them to engage consultants
licensed to deliver the NIES TQM `How to' model which is a uniquely
Australian interpretation of the world-wide TQM approach.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The TQM for Small business (TQMSB) program is flexible enough to
also assist smaller firms to plot their own course of development.</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC10">IMPROVEMENT THROUGH PEOPLE
</A></H3>
<P>Improvement Through People (ITP) is a program designed to draw
together all the people-oriented elements which go into making a
successful company. While other NIES programs include the principles of
good people management, ITP deals more specifically with the human
elements of good business and provides specialist human resource
assistance to companies in areas such as workplace redesign, cultural
change, training and cooperative management.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NIES field officers in each State and Territory are specialist ITP
facilitators, trained to identify and advise on basic issues.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>New South Wales</P>
<P>(02) 228 3050</P>
<P></P>
<P>Queensland</P>
<P>(07) 224 2075</P>
<P></P>
<P>South Australia</P>
<P>(08) 300 1500</P>
<P></P>
<P>Western Australia</P>
<P>(09) 481 2525</P>
<P></P>
<P>Northern Territory</P>
<P>(089) 89 7993</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tasmania</P>
<P>(002) 718 177</P>
<P></P>
<P>ACT</P>
<P>(06) 205 0614</P>
<P></P>
<P>AusIndustry</P>
<P>51 Allara St</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 276 1627</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 276 1586</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC11">ENTERPRISE NETWORK PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Enterprise Network Program assists small to medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs) to cooperate in strategic areas of business.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Networking enables firms to develop joint solutions to common
problems which might be beyond the capabilities of a single enterprise. 
Firms in a network can exploit mutual strengths in resources, equipment
and markets, thereby improving their competitive position.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Enterprise Network Program provides support for an external
network broker to guide networks through a three-stage development
process.  This process involves looking into the network feasibility of
the idea in stage 1, establishing a business plan and legal basis in
stage 2, and beginning networking operations in stage 3.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Department of Industry, Science and Technology</P>
<P>51 Allara Street</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 276 1625</P>
<P></P>
