Law Services.-->
<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - INVESTMENT INCENTIVES, LOANS AND TAX 
CONCESSIONS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">INVESTMENT INCENTIVES, LOANS AND TAX
CONCESSIONS
</A></H1>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">AUSTRALIAN TAXATION OFFICE
</A></H2>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">TAX CONCESSIONS FOR PLANT AND BUILDINGS
</A></H3>
<P>An income tax deduction may be available for capital expenditure on
the construction of new buildings (including extensions, alterations or
improvements to buildings) for tourist purposes.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The buildings or extensions could include tourist accommodation,
apartments, units, flats, tourist attractions, resorts and restaurants.</P>
<P></P>
<P>For buildings used to provide short-term traveller accommodation and
which can produce assessable income, where construction commenced after
26 February 1992, the costs are written off at 4 per cent per annum over
25 years.  For buildings that commenced before 27 February 1992, other
rates may apply.  Your local tax office has details.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In addition, certain structural improvements such as sealed car
parks, sealed roads, sealed runways, seawalls, and covered shelters for
paths and outdoor activities can be written off at 2.5 per cent.</P>
<P></P>
<P>New depreciation rates for items of plant and equipment were
introduced on 26 February 1992 and relate to items purchased after that
date.  These rates, listed below, are based on the effective life of an
item which is defined as the period during which an item of plant can
reasonably be used for income-producing purposes.</P> 
<PRE>
<I>Effective life rates class        New rate of depreciation</I>
Year                             Prime Cost       Diminishing
Less than 3                         100              100
3 to less than 6                     40               60
5 to less than 6 2/3                 27               40
6 2/3 to less than 10                20               30
10 to less than 13                   17               25
13 to less than 30                   13               20
30 and over                           7               10</PRE> 
<P>The Government introduced measures to simplify and clarify the
depreciation system, such as self-assessment provisions on items for
which the relevant rate of depreciation can be determined, broad-banding
of rates, pooling of items with similar rates and deductibility of items
$300 or less or with a life of less than three years.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Should businesses elect not to self-assess, the Commissioner of
Taxation's published `safe-harbour' rates can be adopted for
convenience.  For further information contact your local tax office.
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC4">DEPARTMENT OF THE TREASURY
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC5">FOREIGN INVESTMENT REVIEW BOARD
</A></H3>
<P>The Government recognises the substantial contribution that foreign
investment can make to the development of Australia's industries and
resources.  The Government's policy is to encourage direct foreign
investment that is consistent with the interests of the Australian
community.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Certain proposals involving foreign interests need to be submitted
to the Foreign Investment Review Board (FIRB) for examination and these
are outlined in FIRB's publication <I>Australia's Foreign Investment
Policy - A Guide for Investors</I>.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Proposals for investments in hotels, motels and other tourist
facilities will generally be approved unless they are contrary to the
national interest. Proposals for investment in residential real estate
for development or under construction are normally approved, but there
are restrictions on acquisitions of established residential real estate.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Foreign Investment Review Board</P>
<P>Department of the Treasury</P>
<P>Parkes Place</P>
<P>Parkes ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 263 2111</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">TAX CONCESSIONS FOR ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT STUDIES
</A></H3>
<P>Taxpayers are allowed a deduction for capital expenditures incurred
primarily and principally in undertaking an environmental impact study.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Expenditure, other than on plant and equipment, is deductible on a
straight line basis over a period of the lesser of the life of the
project or 10 years. For this purpose, the life of the project includes
any period involving completion of the environmental impact study and
between completing the study and the expected cessation of operations. 
Where the project does not go ahead, expenditure on the environmental
impact study is deductible in the year of income in which the project is
abandoned.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The deduction is available from the year in which the expenses are
incurred and in equal instalments.  Where the environmental impact study
takes place over a number of years, expenditure in each year is eligible
for write off commencing from the year it is incurred.  Deductions are
available for offset against any income from other sources and any
resulting losses will be subject to the general carry forward and group
loss transfer provisions of the taxation law.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Deductions remain with the taxpayer who incurred the expenditure
irrespective of whether the project to which they relate is subsequently
sold:  deductions are not transferable; nor is there any clawback, where
the taxpayer sells the project in whole or in part.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Expenditure on plant and equipment used in undertaking an
environmental impact study is depreciable in accordance with the general
depreciation provisions by treating such plant and equipment as if used
for the purpose of producing assessable income.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The concession applies to expenditure incurred after 11 March 1991.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Director</P>
<P>Business Taxation Branch</P>
<P>Department of the Treasury</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 263 3753</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 263 3066</P>
<P></P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">COMMONWEALTH DEVELOPMENT BANK
</A></H3>
<P>The Commonwealth Development Bank (CDB) provides term loans and
equipment finance for small and medium-sized businesses.  The Bank is
particularly looking to finance viable growth.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In the evaluation of applications for finance, the CDB is interested
primarily in the prospects for success, rather than the nature or extent
of available security.  This approach requires close examination of the
applicant's business strategies, management track record,
product/service strengths and weaknesses, and sales and marketing
issues.</P>
<P></P>
<P>CDB views its term loan clients as `partners' and seeks to add value
to its relationships.  There is a capacity to provide equity capital in
appropriate circumstances.</P>
<P></P>
<P>CDB is a provider of term loan finance for periods of up to 15
years.  The preferred maximum amount is $5 million and repayment
arrangements are structured to suit projected cash flows.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Equipment finance contracts are generally written for a four-year
period.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Commonwealth Development Bank</P>
<P>Toll free</P>
<P>1 800 011 164</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC8">DEPARTMENT OF INDUSTRY, SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC9">POOLED DEVELOPMENT FUNDS PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The Pooled Development Funds (PDF) Program provides equity
investments primarily for established and start-up businesses of small
to medium sized companies which are expanding production capacity or
markets.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Companies seeking equity capital under the PDF Program must be
resident in Australia and have total assets of less than $50 million. 
While PDF legislation states that tourism projects are eligible
investments, projects which involve retailing and property development
are ineligible.  The PDF Registration Board will, however, examine
prospective tourism projects that have elements of both property
development and retail to assess their eligibility.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Director</P>
<P>Development Capital Section</P>
<P>Department of Industry, Science and Technology</P>
<P>GPO Box 9839</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 276 1681</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 276 1851
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC10">INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE SUPPORT SCHEME
</A></H3>
<P>The Department of Industry, Science and Technology administers the
International Conference Support Scheme (ICSS) for the Institution of
Engineers, Australia.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Financial advances of up to $15 000 are available under ICSS to
organisers of international engineering, science and technology
conferences and symposia.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Advances may be in the form of a loan, repayable from conference
profits, or a grant to assist in the preparation of bids to hold
conferences in Australia.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>Any Australian institute, corporation or government body with the
capacity to conduct such conferences is eligible to apply.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Manager</P>
<P>International Conference Support Scheme</P>
<P>Institution of Engineers, Australia</P>
<P>11 National Circuit</P>
<P>Barton ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 270 6555</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 273 2051</P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC11">DEPARTMENT OF COMMUNICATIONS AND THE ARTS
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">TAX INCENTIVE FOR CONSERVATION WORK ON
HERITAGE-LISTED BUILDINGS
</A></H3>
<P>In 1994, the Commonwealth Government introduced a 20 per cent tax
rebate to encourage conservation work on heritage-listed buildings or
structures.  The incentive will support a maximum $9.5 million worth of
conservation work in a year.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Given the expenditure cap, conditions apply for the concession, and
not all applications may succeed.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>The following criteria must be fulfilled:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>the applicant must own land or hold a Crown lease over the
land on which the building or structure is situated;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>the building or structure must be listed on the Register of the
National Estate, or a State/Territory heritage register; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>the heritage conservation work must cost $5 000 or more.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The tax incentive will not be available for any work completed prior
to the approval of an application.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tax Incentive for Heritage Conservation</P>
<P>Department of Communications and the Arts</P>
<P>GPO Box 2154</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 275 4438</P>
<P>Toll free: 1 800 064 068</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 275 4499</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
