<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created by Adam Clarke of Computer
Law Services.-->
<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - BUSINESS ADVICE, REFERRAL AND TOURISM
INFORMATION</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">BUSINESS ADVICE, REFERRAL AND TOURISM
INFORMATION
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">DEPARTMENT OF HOUSING AND REGIONAL DEVELOPMENT -
OFFICE OF REGIONAL DEVELOPMENT
</A></H2>
<P>The Commonwealth Government's Regional Development Strategy is an
initiative of
<I>Working Nation</I>, the Government's White Paper on Employment and
Growth, released in May 1994.  The initiatives are not specific to
tourism but will provide opportunities for tourism related projects,
planning and innovation to be integrated with broadly based regional
economic development strategies and activities directed at improving the
competitiveness of regions in international markets.</P>
<P></P>
<P>It is administered by the Office of Regional Development which
became part of the Department of Housing and Regional Development in
April 1994.  The Office is responsible for coordinating and implementing
the Government's Regional Development Strategy (RDS) and associated
programs.  The Government has earmarked some $150 million in RDS program
outlays over the four financial years to 1997-98.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Program should also provide opportunities for linking economic
initiatives in various sectors, including tourism, and support
partnership approaches with private industry and the three spheres of
government.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The RDS has two primary component programs:</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">REGIONAL BEST PRACTICE PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The <B>Regional Best Practice Program</B> ($81.4 million over 4
years) aims to support and encourage leadership and the implementation
of regional development plans.  There are four elements of the Program:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Structures, Strategies and Projects: aims to encourage the
development of agreed vision and enabling strategies by regions; build
more effective linkages between stakeholders; and achieve best practice
approaches to regional development;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Management and Skills Enhancement: aims to develop an information
network and advice for regional development practitioners on best
practice approaches and provide innovative opportunities for training
and skills enhancement;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Improvements in Program Delivery: aims to develop best practice in
government to support regional development.  It will involve extending
the reach of key business improvement programs such as National
Enterprise Improvement Scheme, Austrade and innovation support schemes
to regions and, over time, ensure the better coordination of regionally
focused activities of Commonwealth departments; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Partnerships: aims to establish a number of consultative forums for
elected representatives and officials of the three tiers of government
and their interaction with regional bodies and groups.</LI></UL>
<P>	
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC4">INFRASTRUCTURE PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>The <B>Infrastructure Program</B> aims to facilitate regional
infrastructure projects that are identified as integral to the economic
development strategy of a region and which can demonstrate commercial
and economic viability.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Individual projects funded under this component require a
contribution of up to 50 per cent from other sources.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>Eligibility for assistance will vary according to the elements of
the two Programs.  The main funding recipients will be Regional Economic
Development Organisations (REDOs).</P>
<P></P>
<P>Funding may also be available for local councils and Regional
Organisation of Councils (ROCs) committed to the formation of a REDO. 
Tertiary institutions with demonstrated interest and expertise in areas
relevant to regional development may also apply for assistance. 
Interested industries and firms with regional projects or initiatives
relevant to the economic development strategy of a region should contact
the local REDO, council or ROC in the first instance.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Applications will be considered only in the context of an integrated
economic development strategy which focuses on business development and
investment from an adequately defined region with a broadly based
development body.  These bodies may include tourism representatives as
well as a range of other economic sectors and groups in the region.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Selection Criteria</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>For particulars of the selection criteria for projects under the
various elements of the Programs, contact the Office of Regional
Development on 1 800 801 957.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr B Dastidar</P>
<P>Assistant Director</P>
<P>Regional Economic Development Group</P>
<P>PO BOX 9834</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 248 4464</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC5">ABORIGINAL AND TORRES STRAIT ISLANDER COMMISSION
</A></H2>
<P>The Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC) was
established in March 1990 to replace the former Department of Aboriginal
Affairs and the Aboriginal Development Commission.  Elected
representatives of Aboriginal peoples and Torres Strait Islanders make
decisions about programs and policies at the national and regional
levels.  ATSIC is the main Commonwealth agency operating in the field of
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander affairs.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">BUSINESS FUNDING SCHEME
</A></H3>
<P>This is a commercial Scheme to assist Aboriginal peoples and Torres
Strait Islanders to buy or set up money making enterprises by providing
low interest loans, bank guarantees, business advice, training and
services.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility/Criteria</B></P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>People who borrow money under this Scheme have to be able to
provide security over the loan.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Applications for loans must be made on special application forms
and be sent with a business plan to the agency appointed by ATSIC in
each State and Territory.</LI></UL>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">COMMUNITY ECONOMIC INITIATIVES SCHEME
</A></H3>
<P>This Scheme provides grants to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
community organisations to assist them set up small money making
enterprises.  Assistance is available to help new projects or support
existing projects that are likely to be successful.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility/Criteria</B></P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Ideas for projects must come from the community and address
the goals of the community plan.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Applications for grants must be made on an ATSIC Grant Application
form and lodged, together with a business plan, with an ATSIC Regional
Office.</LI></UL>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC8">ENTERPRISE EMPLOYMENT ASSISTANCE
</A></H3>
<P>This Program aims to increase the viability of eligible enterprises
owned by Aboriginal peoples and Torres Strait Islanders by providing a
wage subsidy to assist them to employ previously unemployed Aboriginal
peoples and Torres Strait Islanders.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility/Criteria</B></P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Enterprises are required to supply a business development plan
with projected cash flow and employment proposals for each position to
be established, showing that these positions will be self-funded when
support ceases.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Applications are to be made on an ATSIC Grant Application form and
lodged at an ATSIC Regional Office.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>The Program has links with the Community Economic Initiatives
Scheme.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Your local ATSIC Office </P>
<P>or</P>
<P>Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission</P>
<P>PO Box 17</P>
<P>Woden ACT 2606</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 289 1222</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 281 0772</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC9">NATIONAL ABORIGINAL AND TORRES STRAIT ISLANDER
TOURISM STRATEGY - A PROGRESS REPORT
</A></H3>
<P>As part of the Government's response to the recommendations of the
Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody, provision was made
for the development, implementation and evaluation of a strategy to
strengthen tourism industry participation by Aboriginal peoples and
Torres Strait Islanders.  The Tourism Industry Advisory Committee (TIAC)
was established to further this aim.</P>
<P></P>
<P>TIAC is advising ATSIC and the Department of Tourism on the
development of a National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Tourism
Strategy.  TIAC's objective is to develop a draft strategy to support
increased active participation of indigenous peoples in the Australian
tourism industry and to select pilot projects which will test aspects of
the draft strategy.  The document will be presented to the Board of
Commissioners and to Government in September 1994. The Committee has
held consultative meetings in various locations to identify the major
issues to be considered when developing the final Strategy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A major national study on indigenous involvement in the tourism
industry was commissioned by TIAC.  The consultancy covers: the
attitudes of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people to tourism;
industry and consumer expectations of indigenous tourism ventures;
supply of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander tourism activities
(including current levels of employment); reasons for business
success/failure (enterprise analysis); and developmental needs
(including training).</P>
<P></P>
<P>An issues paper also canvassed Aboriginal peoples' and Torres Strait
Islanders' attitudes to the development of indigenous tourism
enterprises and increased employment opportunities in established
tourism operations.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Pilot projects to test elements of the draft Strategy will be
identified and financially supported during 1994-95 and 1995-96.  A
final Strategy is due to be completed by July 1997.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Tourism Information Guide</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>ATSIC has produced a <I>Tourism Information Guide</I> which
outlines Commonwealth, State/Territory and non-government programs that
may be of assistance to Aboriginal peoples and Torres Strait Islanders
wishing to embark on tourism enterprises.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>TIAC Secretariat Economic Development and Industry Policy Section</P>
<P>Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission</P>
<P>PO Box 17</P>
<P>Woden ACT 2606</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 289 8911</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 282 5027</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC10">DEPARTMENT OF PRIME MINISTER AND CABINET -
ABORIGINAL RECONCILIATION UNIT
</A></H2>
<P>The Aboriginal Reconciliation Unit is located in the Department of
Prime Minister and Cabinet and acts as Secretariat to the Council for
Aboriginal Reconciliation.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Council comprises 25 members, of whom 12 are Aboriginal and two
are Torres Strait Islanders.  The Council's task is to look for ways for
indigenous and other Australians to share Australia as equals, and to
examine opportunities for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples
to control their destinies. The tourism industry offers significant
opportunities for indigenous people.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC11">INDUSTRY COMMITTEE
</A></H3>
<P>The Industry Committee aims to enhance employment prospects for
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in the private sector and
to promote productive cultural diversity in the workplace.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Committee and its agents meet with employers and union groups in
all States and Territories and at the national level.  The meeting
produces and disseminates an information package on reconciliation
targeted at employer groups and unions (see below, the `Working as One'
package).</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Committee also sponsors an award for businesses whose activities
have contributed to the reconciliation process.  In September 1993, the
award was presented to the <I>Koori Mail</I>, in recognition of the
newspaper's efforts in providing information and promoting positive
images of indigenous Australians.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Committee contributed to and participated in the First National
Indigenous Business Conference, held in Alice Springs in September 1993.
 The Conference recognised the two-fold increase in indigenous
businesses over the last five years (many of which operate in the
tourism field), as well as the contribution of indigenous businesses to
establishing an independent economic base for indigenous Australians.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Committee recognises that the tourism industry is one of
Australia's largest growth industries, and a vital economic activity for
many centres throughout Australia.  The findings of a 1992 survey of
inbound visitors revealed that more than 70 per cent of overseas
visitors wanted an indigenous Australian cultural experience.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Other initiatives of the Committee include current sponsorship of a
Cairns tourism/Queensland Confederation of Industry initiative which
will promote the involvement of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
peoples in tourism.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">`WORKING AS ONE' PACKAGE
</A></H3>
<P>The `Working as One' package includes a video, booklet and poster,
and is designed to encourage union and employer groups and members to
work against discrimination, and for recognition and inclusion of
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander perspectives in their workplaces.</P>
<P></P>
<P>It contains positive examples of the contributions indigenous
Australians make to business and economic development in Australia, as
employees, employers and partners.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The package also promotes the networks set up in the ACTU and the
Australian Chamber of Commerce and Industry to encourage greater
employment opportunities for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
peoples.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Secretariat to the Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation</P>
<P>Industries Policies Section</P>
<P>Aboriginal Reconciliation Branch</P>
<P>Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 271 5345</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 271 5168</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC13">DEPARTMENT OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS AND TRADE
</A></H2>
<P>The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) is responsible
for international negotiations aimed at removing barriers and
impediments to the export of Australian services.  These negotiations
are conducted at a bilateral government-to-government level and at a
multilateral level through the General Agreement on Trade in Services
(GATS) and the World Trade Organisation, which is expected to be
established at the beginning of 1995.</P>
<P></P>
<P>DFAT conducts trade promotion activities for a number of business
sectors, including tourism.  Some of these are:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>the annual National Trade and Investment Outlook Conference,
which brings together key Australian and international business people;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Asian Business Visits Program for Asian business executives to
visit Australia and forge links with business leaders;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Special Visits Program sponsoring key overseas politicians and
officials to personally see what Australian industry has to offer; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Overseas Media Visits Program which sponsors visits for key media
personnel with influence over the images of Australia portrayed in
newspapers, television and radio.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The Department produces a number of trade publications including:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Services File newsletter - information on developments in
services trade, including updates on GATS negotiations;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Country Economic Briefs - detailed economic and political reporting
and analysis on our major trading partners;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Asialine - commercially valuable political and economic reports on
countries in our region specifically designed for business; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>East Asia Analytical Unit reports - featuring forward-looking
research and analysis of emerging market prospects in Asia.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The Department provides introductions and market information for
prospective exporters or investors in overseas markets through its
network.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Business Affairs Unit</P>
<P>Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 261 2413</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 261 2465</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC14">DEPARTMENT OF PRIMARY INDUSTRIES AND ENERGY
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC15">AGRIBUSINESS PROGRAMS
</A></H3>
<P>The Agribusiness Programs aim to enhance the international
competitiveness of Australia's agricultural and related industries by
providing practical assistance to agribusinesses or industry/grower
groups.  This can include assistance for the development of rural
tourism initiatives.</P>
<P></P>
<P>$23.5 million is currently available for the Programs up to the end
of 1996-97. Assistance is principally through the provision of grants to
enable access to professional services, to foster the adoption or
development of modern business and marketing skills.  Funding is
provided to engage consultancy support for projects which focus on:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>export and/or import replacement through competitive value
adding and innovation;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>improvements in strategic business development, general commercial
practice and quality management systems;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>improvement of the international marketing skills of managers;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>adoption of world best practice;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>development and enhancement of networks and better linkages through
the agribusiness chain; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>establishment or expansion of viable community-based enterprises.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The Programs are overseen by the Agribusiness Programs Board, which
comprises members predominantly from the private sector.  Applications
are considered on merit and preference is given to those with the
greatest prospects for commercial success.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Assistance is generally calculated on a 50/50 cost share basis
between the applicant and the Agribusiness Programs.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Programs do not fund land, working capital, plant, machinery,
stock, formal education courses, scientific research and development,
overseas travel costs of project participants or retrospective
activities.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr David Gregory</P>
<P>Director</P>
<P>Marketing and Business Services</P>
<P>Department of Primary Industries and Energy</P>
<P>Canberra  ACT  2600</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 272 5096
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC16">DEPARTMENT OF ADMINISTRATIVE SERVICES
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC17">AUSTRALIAN SURVEYING AND LAND INFORMATION GROUP
</A></H3>
<P>The Australian Surveying and Land Information Group (AUSLIG)
provides mapping and land related information services which can assist
tourists and tourist promotion bodies.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AUSLIG produces general topographic maps covering Australia at
1:250,000 and 1:100,000 scale.  Topographic maps show natural and
constructed features including land surface, streams, lakes, roads,
vegetation type and density, nature conservation reserves, forestry
resources and Aboriginal land.  These are of particular interest, not
only to bushwalkers and off-road travellers, but also to organised tour
providers/companies.  In addition, selected Northern Australia maps are
published with survival resources information on the back of each map.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AUSLIG produces the following tourist maps that include information
on tourist services and facilities, and what to do and see:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>tourist map of Australia;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Northern Australia tourist map;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>South Eastern Australia tourist map;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Kakadu National Park and surrounds;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Norfolk Island map and visitors guide;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Uluru National Park;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Australian Capital Territory; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Australian Alps National Park.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>It also provides a customised mapping service.  For example, it has
prepared maps for the <I>Harley Owners' Group Touring Handbook of
Australia and New Zealand</I>, and is currently working on the mapping
component of <I>4WD Escapes</I>, an atlas featuring maps and notes for
4WD treks in remote areas of Australia.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AUSLIG maps are available, or can be ordered, from more than 300
retail outlets throughout Australia and overseas, particularly from
specialist map shops, outdoor leisure shops and bookshops.</P>
<P></P>
<P>MAPS AND INFORMATION ON THE CUSTOMISED MAPPING SERVICE CAN BE
OBTAINED FROM
<I>AUSLIG</I> BY PHONING THE TOLL FREE NUMBER 1800 800 173.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Head Office</P>
<P>Scrivener Building</P>
<P>Dunlop Court</P>
<P>Fernhill Park</P>
<P>Bruce ACT 2616</P>
<P></P>
<P>Senior Departmental Contact:</P>
<P>Mr John Payne</P>
<P>AUSLIG Manager, Retail Sales</P>
<P>PO Box 2</P>
<P>Belconnen ACT 2616</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 201 4310</P>
