<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - TRAINING, EDUCATION AND WORKPLACE
REFORMS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">TRAINING, EDUCATION AND WORKPLACE REFORMS
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">TOURISM TRAINING AUSTRALIA
</A></H2>
<P>Tourism Training Australia was established in 1980 by the tourism
industry with the support of the Federal Government.  Its role is to
ensure that the industry has the skilled staff and managers required to
meet the needs of its markets and to operate profitably.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism Training Australia is the industry's peak body on education
and training and is concerned with all levels of skills development from
entry level through to senior management.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Its functions include research, policy development, promotion of
career paths/national training standards, and the provision of training
services and resources to industry.  These include:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>a directory of currently available education and training
programs (university, TAFE, private provider and company based) which
have been recognised as meeting the industry's training requirements set
by the Australian Hospitality Review Panel/Australian Tourism Training
Review Panel. These requirements cover entry level through to management
level;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>training programs, workshops, information kits and self-paced
learning programs;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>`on the job' qualifications - ACCESS, a new training skill program;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>a range of training resources for in-house use by companies to
train their staff;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>advice on training requirements under industrial awards and
government legislation; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>a consulting service for companies in areas such as training needs
analysis and skills audits, training program design and delivery,
service quality management and workplace reform.</LI></UL>
<P>	</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>National Office:</P>
<P>Tourism Training Australia</P>
<P>PO Box Q309</P>
<P>Queen Victoria Building</P>
<P>Post Office</P>
<P>Sydney NSW 2000</P>
<P>Tel: (02) 290 1055</P>
<P>Fax: (02) 290 1001</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC3">DEPARTMENT OF EMPLOYMENT, EDUCATION AND TRAINING
</A></H2>
<P>The Department of Employment, Education and Training (DEET) funds a
number of projects designed to increase employment, education and
training in the tourism industry.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>GPO Box 9880</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 240 9533</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC4">TRAINING INCENTIVES PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>Funds are available to explore and test innovative training programs
that improve skills training in industry.  The Program assists employer
and union groups, industry associations and industry training committees
to undertake projects supporting the training reform agenda.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC5">TRAINING SERVICES AUSTRALIA
</A></H3>
<P>Training Services Australia is a fee-for-service training and
consultancy group that conducts public and in-house training courses on
human resources planning and design.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">INSTITUTIONAL DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
</A></H3>
<P>Grants are available to peak and key employer and employee bodies to
develop industry and entry level training.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">GROUP TRAINING ARRANGEMENTS
</A></H3>
<P>Group training arrangements assist group training companies to
establish new training opportunities for apprentices and trainees.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC8">APPRENTICE TRAINING INCENTIVE
</A></H3>
<P>The Apprentice Training Incentive (ATI) was introduced to improve
the quality of apprentice training through incentive payments.  ATI pays
incentives at key points during the apprenticeship, including
commencement and completion. Incentive grants are also available under
the Trade Training System, which aims to move the apprenticeship system
away from a time-serve approach and towards improving competency levels.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC9">AUSTRALIAN TRAINEESHIP SYSTEM
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC10">AUSTRALIAN VOCATIONAL CERTIFICATE TRAINING
SYSTEM
</A></H3>
<P>A new national system of vocational education and training, the
Australian Vocational Certificate Training System (AVCTS) is being
implemented and is applicable to young people undergoing the transition
between school and work.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC11">CAREER START TRAINEESHIP SCHEME
</A></H3>
<P>An interim program, the Career Start Traineeship system links the
current training system with the AVCTS and provides greater flexibility
to trainees in the interim.  The AVCTS changeover date will be 1 January
1995 with full implementation by 1997.  A series of workplace and
institutional pilots are under way to test a range of alternatives to
AVCTS.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">AUSTRALIAN STUDENT TRAINEESHIP FOUNDATION
</A></H3>
<P>In the 1994 White Paper, <I>Working Nation</I>, the Government
announced the establishment of the Australian Student Traineeship
Foundation (ASTF) to support greater industry ownership of entry level
training and improve links between industry and school programs.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Foundation will be a national industry driven body, at arms
length from Government, responsible for developing and supporting school
industry-based programs through a network of local and regional brokers.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A board with a majority of members from industry will be appointed.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Once programs are established with schools, the local/regional
brokers will be eligible to apply for funds to purchase off the job
training from TAFE and other providers.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC13">NATIONAL EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING TASKFORCE
</A></H3>
<P>In <I>Working Nation</I>, the Government announced the
establishment of the National Employment and Training Taskforce
(NETTFORCE) to encourage employers to make more job and training places
available to unemployed people generally and to young unemployed people.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A key element of its work will be to promote a streamlined training
approval process to minimise bureaucratic red tape.</P>
<P></P>
<P>NETTFORCE will comprise people from business and unions committed to
improving employment and training opportunities.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC14">NATIONAL SKILLS SHORTAGE
</A></H3>
<P>The program provides short-term training assistance to industries
and enterprises in occupations that are in short supply.  Emphasis is
given to occupations requiring temporary reliance on skilled migration. 
Assistance under the program includes: development and provision of
short-term formal and on the job training; development of course
curriculum; production and training aids; and wage subsidies for on the
job training.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC15">JOBSTART</A></H3>
<P>This is a program of wage subsidies paid to employers who engage
long-term unemployed workers.  To be eligible for the scheme, job
seekers must be unemployed and registered with the CES for twelve
months, or especially disadvantaged.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC16">SKILLSHARE</A></H3>
<P>Assists the long-term unemployed to obtain employment, or to gain
access to further education and training.  Skillshare offers training in
bar and waiting skills, food preparation, cleaning and reception, and
many participants are eligible for Jobstart on course completion.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC17">JOBSKILLS</A></H3>
<P>Jobskills assists government, community and other non-profit
organisations to provide subsidised work experience and structured
training for those unemployed for more than 12 months.  Participants
must be aged 21 or over, registered as unemployed with the CES, and in
receipt of a Social Security benefit for a minimum of 12 months.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC18">NEW ENTERPRISE INCENTIVE SCHEME
</A></H3>
<P>This Scheme assists job seekers to set up commercially viable self
employment ventures.  Applicants must be between 18 and 65 years and
registered with the CES for full-time employment.  The Scheme includes
business advice and training, as well as income support for one year.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC19">JOBTRAIN</A></H3>
<P>Emphasises vocational skills training applicable to local industry
needs. Applicants must be unemployed and registered with the CES for at
least six months to be eligible.  Access to the scheme is based on
available resources, local employment opportunities and trainee needs.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC20">NATIONAL TRAINING WAGE
</A></H3>
<P>The National Training Wage provides a further incentive for
employers to take on trainees and contribute to, and benefit from,
skills formation.  It also offers workers the opportunity to receive a
recognised and portable qualification.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The National Training Wage will enable adults to access traineeships
for the first time and will also simplify and expand the existing
traineeship arrangements for entry level training.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Employers who take on the unemployed under the National Training
Wage will be eligible for subsidies for 13 to 26 weeks.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The (relevant) Program Manager</P>
<P>DEET National Office</P>
<P>GPO Box 9880</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 240 9533</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC21">LANDCARE AND ENVIRONMENT ACTION PROGRAM
</A></H3>
<P>This Program assists young people to enhance their employment
opportunities through a 26 week program which combines formal training
and practical experience.  The Program is delivered by non-profit
community organisations and local, State and Commonwealth Government
agencies contracted by DEET.  Projects under this Program have a
conservation focus either in landcare or cultural heritage.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Young people between the ages of 15 and 20 years, who are registered
with the CES as unemployed, are eligible for this Program.  Priority is
given to long-term unemployed youth or youth at risk of becoming
long-term unemployed.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>DEET National Office:</P>
<P>Janet Popovic</P>
<P>Director LEAP</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 203 3104</P>
<P>DEET Area Offices:</P>
<P>Ask for the Community Strategy Branch</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC22">AUSTRALIAN NATIONAL TRAINING AUTHORITY
</A></H2>
<P>The Australian National Training Authority (ANTA) aims to identify
national training needs and priorities and ensure that vocational
educational and training programs are closely related to industry and
job priorities.</P>
<P></P>
<P>ANTA became fully operational on 1 January 1994.</P>
<P></P>
<P>ANTA will offer:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>training programs that will better reflect and meet the needs
and priorities of industry;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>training strategies developed in accordance with the national
strategic plan;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>strengthened links between all education providers; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>improved training opportunities for people wanting employment in
the tourism industry.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Mr T Moran</P>
<P>Chief Executive Officer</P>
<P>ANTA</P>
<P>GPO Box 3120</P>
<P>Brisbane QLD 4001</P>
<P>Tel: (07) 246 2300</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC23">DEPARTMENT OF INDUSTRIAL RELATIONS
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC24">WORKPLACE BARGAINING
</A></H3>
<P>The Workplace Bargaining program aims to promote productive and
cooperative bargaining in Australian workplaces.  The main focus is on
funding projects which lead to Federal certified agreements, enterprise
flexibility agreements, or the use of enterprise flexibility clauses in
awards.  The results of funded projects will be publicised to
demonstrate successful processes and the benefits which can be derived
from workplace agreements.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Workplace bargaining encourages workers and managers to get together
and agree on how best to put productivity changes into place for their
particular business.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The program provides a practical starting point for enterprises
wishing to pursue workplace bargaining under the changes to Federal
industrial relations law which came into effect in March 1994.  Projects
can focus on particular issues encountered in negotiation of workplace
agreements, such as the needs of migrant workers and women.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Funding is available to groups seeking to negotiate a certified
agreement or enterprise flexibility arrangement.  Project funding is
based on competitive bids which are assessed against selection criteria.
 Some sectors of the tourism industry have already taken advantage of
the Program.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Department of Industrial Relations</P>
<P>GPO Box 9879</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: 1 800 646 498</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
