<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - RESEARCH AND STATISTICS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">RESEARCH AND STATISTICS
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">BUREAU OF TOURISM RESEARCH
</A></H2>
<P>The Bureau of Tourism Research (BTR) is a professional, independent
research agency servicing the statistical and research needs of
Commonwealth, State and Territory governments, the tourism industry and
the community at large.  It is jointly funded by the Commonwealth, State
and Territory governments and exists to provide a national focus for the
collection, analysis and dissemination of tourism and related data.</P>
<P></P>
<P>BTR is responsible for two major surveys of tourism activity in
Australia:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The <B>International Visitor Survey</B> (IVS) draws on personal
interviews with 12,000 overseas visitors each year and is the most
comprehensive source of information available on the travel patterns and
characteristics of visitors to Australia; and</P>
<P></P>
<P>The <B>Domestic Tourism Monitor</B> (DTM) involves interviews with
65,000 Australians each year and provides information on travel
undertaken in Australia by these people, including day trips as well as
trips involving nights away from home.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Results of these surveys are published in both quarterly and annual
reports. Detailed analysis of the results provides the basis for other
reports and publications.  Complete survey data are available on compact
disk, and special tabulations or supplementary surveys can be produced
by BTR as required.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In addition to its survey output, BTR provides:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>a telephone statistical inquiries service, covering all
aspects of tourism data;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>estimates of the economic significance of tourism;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>special reports and occasional papers focussing on particular
aspects of tourism;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>support for and assistance with conferences, seminars and workshops
on tourism statistics and research;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>research and consultancy services to both government and industry;
and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>technical support to the Tourism Forecasting Council.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Bureau of Tourism Research</P>
<P>GPO Box 1545</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 279 7176</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 279 7298</P>
<P></P>
<P>AUSTRALIAN BUREAU OF STATISTICS</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) publishes a wide range of
tourism and tourism-related information, including:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Survey of Tourist Accommodation - monthly supply and demand
data for hotels, motels and other commercial accommodation;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Overseas Arrivals and Departures - numbers and characteristics of
inbound and outbound visitors;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Tourism Indicators - a new quarterly publication containing trend
and other data and analysis from the Survey of Tourist Accommodation and
the Overseas Arrivals and Departures collections;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Service Industry Surveys - financial and structural data on
tourism-related industry sectors;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Directory of Tourism Statistics - a comprehensive guide to ABS and
non-ABS sources of tourism-related statistics;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Building Approvals and Activity - value of hotel building approvals
and activity;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Labour Force Surveys - estimates of the number and characteristics
of employees in the recreation, personal and other services industries;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Average earnings of employees - average weekly earnings of
employees in the recreation, personal and other services, retail trade
and transport and storage industry sectors and related occupations;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Population Census - numbers and characteristics of visitors and of
persons employed in the recreation, personal and other services
industries; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Many other statistical series containing information important to
tourism, including: Household Expenditure Surveys, Consumer Price Index,
Balance of Payments, Survey of International Travel Enterprises, Surveys
of Motor Vehicle Use, and specific State-level surveys.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>ABS offices in State/Territory capitals, or</P>
<P>Australian Bureau of Statistics</P>
<P>Cameron Offices</P>
<P>Chandler Street</P>
<P>Belconnen ACT 2616</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 252 7911</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC3">CSIRO</A></H2>
<P>The CSIRO is presently conducting a formal priority-setting exercise
to identify tourism research gaps and priorities.  Discussions are under
way with industry, government and several other agencies (for example,
universities and the Cooperative Research Centres on Tropical
Rainforests and the Great Barrier Reef) with tourism research interests.
 One important feature of this priority-setting procedure is to identify
existing research efforts so that not only research gaps are identified
but the possibility of duplication of effort is reduced.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The resulting initiative will involve collaboration with the tourism
industry to identify research needs at the national strategic level
and/or to perform research for industry on a contract basis.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Research topics are currently being prioritised under four broad
categories:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>tourism planning;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>	tourism infrastructure;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>environmental impacts of tourism; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>tourism information technology.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Dr Dick Braithwaite</P>
<P>Officer-in-Charge/Program Leader</P>
<P>CSIRO</P>
<P>Division of Wildlife and Ecology</P>
<P>Private Mail Bag 44</P>
<P>Winnellie  NT  0821</P>
<P>Tel: (089) 221 735</P>
<P>Fax: (089) 470 052
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC4">AUSTRALIA COUNCIL
</A></H2>
<P>The Australia Council is the Federal arts funding and advisory body
that undertakes research into issues affecting the arts.  The following
research papers on arts and tourism participation are available free of
charge from the Council's library:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI><I>Arts Attendance by International Visitors 1991</I>,
Research Paper No 8, September 1992.  Results of a survey of attendance
at museums/galleries and theatre/music performances October-December
1991, with comparisons of attendance rates for the four quarters of 1991
and for October-December 1990.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI><I>International Visitors and Aboriginal Arts</I>, Research Paper
No. 10, July 1993.  Report of a survey of international visitors to
Australia, February-March 1993.</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI><I>Culture on Holiday</I>, September 1991.  A survey of Australian
domestic tourists' cultural participation, December 1990-April 1991.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Communications and Research</P>
<P>Australia Council</P>
<P>PO Box 788</P>
<P>Strawberry Hills NSW 2012</P>
<P>Tel: (02) 950 9000</P>
<P>Fax: (02) 950 9111</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC5">DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORT
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC6">AVSTATS</A></H3>
<P>The Commonwealth Department of Transport is responsible for
collecting and publishing official statistics relating to the Australian
aviation industry. The Aviation Statistical Unit (AVSTATS), within the
Department's Aviation Division, maintains statistics on all sectors of
the aviation industry including international, domestic, regional and
general aviation.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Its databases are the source of most aviation industry analyses
performed by the Government and private sectors, and from these
databases a series of regular publications including collected data and
analyses are produced for each sector.  In addition to its publications,
AVSTATS provides a statistical request service.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AVSTATS HOTLINE:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Department of Transport</P>
<P>GPO Box 594</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 274 7720</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 274 7727</P>
<P>or</P>
<P>Mr Jon Henchy</P>
<P>Director</P>
<P>AVSTATS</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 274 7912</P>
<P></P>
