<TITLE>Tourism Assistance Guide - ENVIRONMENTAL MEASURES</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">ENVIRONMENTAL MEASURES
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT, SPORT AND TERRITORIES
</A></H2>
<P>The Department of Environment, Sport and Territories (DEST) is
responsible for advising the Commonwealth Government on policies,
initiatives and programs in the areas of environment, sport and the
administration of mainland and island territories.</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC3">ENVIRONMENT STRATEGIES DIRECTORATE
</A></H3>
<P>The Department, through the Environment Strategies Directorate,
administers programs relevant to the tourism industry, such as:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>the National Strategy for Ecologically Sustainable
Development;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>implementation of National Strategies on Greenhouse Gases and
Biological Diversity;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>improved management of natural resources, for example, in
Australia's coastal zone, inland waterways and World Heritage Areas; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>the development of environmental indicators and State of the
Environment reporting.</LI></UL>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC4">COMMONWEALTH ENVIRONMENT PROTECTION AGENCY
</A></H3>
<P>The Commonwealth Environment Protection Agency (CEPA), an agency
within DEST, has oversight of environmental quality issues at the
commonwealth level.  It also manages Commonwealth programs and
implements policies in fields such as:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Environmental Impact Assessment;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Waste Minimisation and Management;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>the phase-out of ozone depleting substances; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>integrated management and environmental technologies and processes.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The <B>Territories Office</B> of the Department is available for
discussion of tourism initiatives in relation to Commonwealth
Territories, including the Jervis Bay Territory, Norfolk Island,
Christmas Island, and the Cocos (Keeling) Islands.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Department's <B>Antarctic Division</B> should be consulted in
relation to tourism proposals in Australia's Antarctic and Sub-Antarctic
Territories. Note: Information about tax concessions for Environmental
Impact Studies is contained on page 29.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>CEPA</P>
<P>PO Box E305</P>
<P>Queen Victoria Terrace</P>
<P>ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 274 1999</P>
<P>        008 803 772</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 274 1666</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC5">AUSTRALIAN HERITAGE COMMISSION
</A></H2>
<P>The Australian Heritage Commission was set up in 1975 to help
Australians identify and appreciate the national estate and promote its
conservation.  The Register of the National Estate, maintained by the
Commission, now has nearly 11,000 entries which have been selected for
their natural, historic or Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
significance.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Register can include places ranging from archaeological sites to
areas important for their ecological values, as well as buildings or
other cultural sites.  Sites can include Aboriginal shell middens,
expanses of tropical rainforest, and buildings from our colonial past,
amongst others.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Commission, through State and Territory Governments, also funds
and coordinates a small grants program for projects by non-profit-making
bodies to identify, conserve and help raise awareness of our national
estate sites.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Note: Information about tax concessions for conservation work on
heritage-listed buildings or structures is contained on page 32.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Australian Heritage Commission</P>
<P>GPO Box 1567</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 271 2111</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 273 2395</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC6">AUSTRALIAN NATURE CONSERVATION AGENCY
</A></H2>
<P>The Australian National Parks and Wildlife Service was established
in 1975 as the principal nature conservation organisation within the
Commonwealth Government.  In June 1993 its name was changed to the
Australian Nature Conservation Agency (ANCA) to reflect its wider
conservation role.  A large part of the Agency's work is done in close
cooperation with government conservation organisations in the States and
Territories.  The Australian and New Zealand Environment and
Conservation Council (ANZECC) is the formal forum where government
ministers meet to discuss national issues.  It performs a similar role
to that of the Tourism Ministers' Council.</P>
<P></P>
<P>ANCA manages five national parks (Christmas Island, Jervis Bay,
Kakadu, Norfolk Island and Uluru-Kata Tjuta), two botanic gardens (the
Australian National Botanic Gardens in Canberra and Norfolk Island
Botanic Gardens) and several marine reserves (Ashmore Reef,
Coringa-Herald, Elizabeth and Middleton Reefs, Lihou Reef, Mermaid Reef
and the Commonwealth waters of Ningaloo and the Solitary Islands).</P>
<P></P>
<P>In its broader conservation role, the Agency is responsible for
administering laws about wildlife protection (the import and export of
native animals, plants and products derived from them), endangered
species and whales.  It is also active in promoting community
participation and research in nature conservation outside protected
areas through programs such as Wetlands Conservations, Save the Bush,
One Billion Trees and Waterwatch.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Much of ANCA's work involves bringing together people and nature
conservation in an ecologically sustainable way.  The Agency provides
the following benefits for the tourism industry:</P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>visitor facilities and interpretive services (guided tours,
specialist talks) in some of Australia's most naturally and culturally
significant sites;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>help with specialist educational tours to botanic gardens and
national parks;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>tour operator training courses and handbooks for Kakadu and
Uluru-Kata Tjuta national parks;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>accreditation for tour operators and guides at Uluru-Kata Tjuta
national park;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>advice on regional tourism liaison (Kakadu, Uluru-Kata Tjuta and
the Australian Alps national parks; the Australian National Botanic
Gardens);</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>employment opportunities for Aboriginal people in tourism;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>contacts with State and Territory conservation agencies;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>advice on the import or export of tourist souvenirs derived from
native animals and plants;</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>information about wildlife viewing (book on <I>Whales and Whale
Watching</I>, whale watching guidelines for tour operators);</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>free and saleable publications and videos, Australian Alps tourist
map, national parks and botanic gardens visitor guides (some in Japanese
and German), Uluru tourism video, Kakadu holiday planner, low impact
camping, wildlife rules for overseas travellers etc; and</LI>
<LI>	</LI>
<LI>Australian souvenirs (posters, greeting cards, ties, scarves).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
