<P>Australian National Botanic Gardens</P>
<P>GPO Box 1777</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 250 9530</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 250 9528</P>
<P></P>
<P>Astrida Upitis</P>
<P>Conservation Policy Coordination</P>
<P>Australian Nature Conservation Agency</P>
<P>GPO Box 636</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 250 0200</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 250 0399</P>
<P>
</P>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC7">CONTRACT EMPLOYMENT PROGRAM FOR ABORIGINALS IN
NATURAL AND CULTURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT
</A></H3>
<P>In addition to working with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
traditional owners and residents in its national parks, the Australian
Nature Conservation Agency runs the Contract Employment Program for
Aboriginals in Natural and Cultural Resource Management.  Aboriginal and
Torres Strait Islander communities, working with tour operators, can
apply for funding under this Program.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Examples of tourism employment include walkabout tours at Jervis Bay
south of Wollongong, boat tours at Geikie Gorge National Park in Western
Australia and activities in the Brambuk Cultural Centre in the
Grampians, Western Victoria.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Kim Orchard</P>
<P>Aboriginal Program Section</P>
<P>Australian Nature Conservation Agency</P>
<P>GPO Box 636</P>
<P>Canberra ACT 2601</P>
<P>Tel: (06) 250 0324</P>
<P>Fax: (06) 250 0735</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC8">GREAT BARRIER REEF MARINE PARK AUTHORITY
</A></H2>
<P>In 1975 the Australian Government acted to establish a system which
amounts to self regulation of the Great Barrier Reef by the people who
use and depend on it, by creating the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park
Authority (GBRMPA).</P>
<P></P>
<P>With its main office in Townsville Queensland, GBRMPA is responsible
for the care and development of the world's largest multiple use marine
park to provide for the wise use, understanding and enjoyment of the
Great Barrier Reef in perpetuity.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The functions of GBRMPA are: planning and management of the Marine
Park, implementing zoning plans and strategies through enforcement and
the assessment of environmental impacts of use and development;
undertaking research and monitoring to improve the knowledge and
understanding of the Great Barrier Reef; providing education and advice
to users of the Marine Park; coordinating Commonwealth and State
government policies as they apply to the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park
and the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area; and the operation of the
Great Barrier Reef Aquarium.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Assistance Measures</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism is a significant use of the Marine Park and GBRMPA can
provide regulatory and technical assistance, management and educational
advice to the tourism industry for activities and development within the
Marine Park.  GBRMPA assists ongoing tourism in the Great Barrier Reef
Marine Park by ensuring that all approved use is sustainable.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Eligibility/Criteria</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>There are no specific eligibility criteria.  Most commercial tourist
operations and developments within the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park
require an assessment of their environmental impact and a Marine Parks
Permit. Prospective tourist developers and operators with proposals
within or adjacent to the Marine Park can contact GBRMPA for information
on zoning, environmental impact assessment, and permit requirements.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority</P>
<P>PO Box 1379</P>
<P>Townsville QLD 4810</P>
<P>Tel: (077) 81 8811</P>
<P>Fax: (077) 72 6093</P>
<P>Executive Officer: Dr Wendy Craik</P>
<P>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC9">WET TROPICS MANAGEMENT AUTHORITY
</A></H2>
<P>The Wet Tropics Management Authority was formed through an agreement
on 10 March 1990 between the Prime Minister and the Premier of
Queensland to jointly fund the Authority as manager of the Wet Tropics
of Queensland World Heritage Area.  The primary goal of the Authority is
to `provide for the implementation of Australia's international duty for
the protection, conservation, presentation, rehabilitation and
transmission to future generations of the Wet Tropics of Queensland
World Heritage Area, within the meaning of the World Heritage
Convention'.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Assistance Measures</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>The Wet Tropics Management Authority confers with developers,
potential developers and land owners regarding developments in or
adjacent to the Wet Tropics World Heritage Area.  The desired approach
is to develop cooperative management agreements which seek to achieve
the primary goal for the Wet Tropics.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Wet Tropics Management Authority is developing visitor centres
in north Queensland which promote the values of the Wet Tropics World
Heritage Area. The preferred approach to development is through joint
ventures with community groups, private enterprise and other government
agencies.  Guidelines for the development of visitor centres are
available from the Authority's community relations program.</P>
<P></P>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</P>
<P></P>
<P>Wet Tropics Management Authority</P>
<P>PO Box 2050</P>
<P>Cairns QLD 4870</P>
<P>Tel: (070) 52 0555</P>
<P>Fax: (070) 31 1364</P>
<P>Contact:</P>
<P>Mr Peter Hitchcock</P>
<P>Executive Director</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
