HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:47:09 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 12204
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 06:06:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>LandTransport.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Land Transport</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task </FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>To move clients, staff or 
goods</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">Transport is the major energy impact of tourism. For tour 
operators, it is the main 
direct energy impact, while for facility operators, it is a major 
indirect impact.<P>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Travel to ecotourism destinations</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT 
SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT 
SIZE=5>Encourage longer stays</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI> If tourists stay in one area for a longer period (for example due to 
discounts or interesting packages involving more than one operator) 
transport energy use per tourism day is reduced. Energy consumption for 
long-distance travel is often the largest single energy factor in a 
holiday.
</UL></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT 
SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT 
SIZE=5>Encourage clients to use fuel-efficient transport</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI> Packages that encourage clients to travel from major cities to 
ecotourism destinations by train or bus (rather than car) can be 
developed, and the trip itself can be integrated into the tourism 
experience with information materials, timetables, organised meals 
enroute or stop-offs at sites of environmental interest.
</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT 
VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI> Transport from airport or city to a destination can be provided or 
coordinated to reduce energy use. Some State regulations exclude small 
operators from hiring vehicles to provide this service, but operators can 
still encourage clients to share transport.
</UL></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Staff travel</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Use transport more effectively</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Where staff have to travel long distances to a site, carpools or a 
staff bus could 
be organised, or arrangements with existing bus services negotiated to 
reduce energy 
use. A nine to eleven seat, diesel minibus uses about as much fuel as an 
average 
six cylinder car.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Staff travel may be combined with guest transport and/or delivery of 
supplies.</UL></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>On-site, staff may find that bicycles are convenient, quiet and save 
fuel.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Mobile phones, radio communications or improved operational systems 
can be used by 
staff to organise their activities more efficiently and reduce 
travel.</UL></TD></TR>
</TR>
</TR></TABLE>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Travel on tour</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Reduce vehicle use</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Walk and use non-motorised transport such as bicycles whenever 
feasible.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>The distance travelled can be reduced by planning tours and support 
vehicle routes and schedules.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action 
</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select 
fuel-efficient vehicles</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>The Department of Primary Industries and Energy publishes its annual 
<CITE>Fuel Consumption Guide</CITE> for passenger vehicles, some 
four-wheel drives and light commercial vehicles.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Diesel-powered vehicles are 20 to 40 per cent more fuel-efficient 
than their petrol counterparts.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Appropriate vehicles can reduce fuel consumption per passenger. For 
example, the Australian made OKA can carry 14 people while using the same 
amount of fuel as a conventional five to seven passenger four-wheel drive 
vehicle. In many cases, a conventional vehicle with limited slip 
differential, suitable tyres and, possibly, a winch, can carry out tasks 
for which more expensive and less fuel-efficient four-wheel drives have 
often been used.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>A light vehicle with a trailer is often suitable when larger capacity 
is required, and is also more fuel-efficient than using a large vehicle 
for all purposes.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Drive for 
fuel-efficiency</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>A computerised fuel consumption monitor can provide feedback to 
drivers to help them develop driving techniques that optimise fuel 
efficiency.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Driver training courses can help improve fuel efficiency and 
safety.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Driving at 90 km/h instead of 110 km/h on the open road consumes 20 
per cent less fuel for most vehicles.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action 
</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Maintain 
optimum vehicle performance</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Regular servicing saves fuel. Fuel efficiency can be maintained by 
keeping an engine in tune, wheels aligned, etc. Monitoring fuel 
consumption helps identify when a vehicle needs tuning.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>When servicing, ensure that used oil is recycled. Most service 
stations can arrange for recycling, otherwise contact your local 
council.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Reduce rolling resistance and fuel consumption by keeping tyre 
pressures at the recommended levels.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action 
</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Setup and 
operate vehicles for fuel-efficiency</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Air resistance caused by pack racks and large trailers can increase 
fuel consumption by 10 per cent or more. Use air deflectors, aerodynamic 
fairings and tarpaulins to reduce drag. The tailgate of an empty trailer 
should be removed, folded down or fitted with a tarpaulin, so it doesn't 
act as a wind-catcher. </UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>A normal car engine consumes more than 1.5 litres of petrol per hour 
of idling. Larger engines consume much more. Switch engines off instead 
of leaving them idling.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Total weight makes a difference. An extra 50 kilograms can add 2 per 
cent to fuel consumption in urban conditions or off-road 
work.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT 
SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><FONT 
SIZE=5>Minimise environmental impact of used tyres</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Millions of worn vehicle tyres make a major contribution to 
Australia's waste volumes. Make sure yours don't add to this 
problem.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Running tyres at recommended pressures and maintaining correct wheel 
alignment prolongs tyre life.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Using retreaded tyres where possible gets the most out of each tyre 
carcass.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Tyres which are too worn for road use may still be suitable for 
on-site use on trailers or other vehicles.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Many tyre retailers will take old tyres for recycling (although, in 
some cases, a small fee may be charged). These tyres are recycled into 
useful products such as rubber matting, soaker hoses 
etc.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success stories</B></FONT>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">Australis, a Victorian-based operation, uses suitably 
sized two-wheel drive vehicles 
instead of four-wheel drives to save fuel. 
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Freycinet Experience in eastern Tasmania uses a 12-seater 
Toyota HiAce bus with a 
trailer to collect clients at Launceston, and to return them there after 
their holiday. 
The trip provides an opportunity for clients to begin to get to know each 
other. 
Cradle Mountain Lodge in Tasmania's highlands uses an 18-seat Mazda bus 
to bring staff 
from Devonport to work each day. This saves transport fuel and reduces 
the danger 
associated with driving on slippery roads. Some staff stay on-site, 
avoiding the 
need to use transport while working at the Lodge.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Landscope Expeditions in Western Australia uses 
Australian-made OKA four-wheel drive 
vehicles, which carry 14 passengers while consuming about as much fuel as 
standard 
four-wheel drive vehicles.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Crystal Creek Rainforest Retreat in Queensland has 
reduced transport fuel use per 
guest and increased its business by extending tour duration. According to 
a staff 
member, 'By making tours of a least a few days, we can reduce the energy 
cost per 
day. It also means people get to relax more and absorb more, rather than 
rushing from place 
to place.'
<P ALIGN="LEFT">The Department of Conservation and Land Management in the 
Kimberley region of Western 
Australia has reduced transport fuel use in the Windjari Gorge Park and 
several other 
areas during the wet season by making these areas self-maintaining. 
Rubbish bins 
have been removed and visitors now take out their own rubbish, so rangers 
no longer need 
to collect and dispose of the rubbish.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Lord Howe Island Nature Tours bases its tours on walking 
and cycling. This avoids 
the use of a bus and the incumbent cost and fuel consumption.
</BODY>
